{"term": "1966", "caseName": "Redrup v. New York", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/1966/3", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - October 10, 1966", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren13/oral_argument_audio/14972", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Number 3, Robert Redrup, petitioner, versus New York.", "start": 0, "stop": 12.214, "duration": 12.21}, {"text": "Mr. Rosenwein.", "start": 12.214, "stop": 16.968, "duration": 4.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.", "start": 16.968, "stop": 20.958, "duration": 3.99}, {"text": "This is -- this case arises on a certiorari to the appellate term of the Supreme Court of New York.", "start": 20.958, "stop": 28.417, "duration": 7.46}, {"text": "The judgment of conviction was under an obscenity law under the state obscenity law.", "start": 28.417, "stop": 33.813, "duration": 5.4}, {"text": "Certiorari was limited, three justices dissenting to the issue of scienter.", "start": 33.813, "stop": 41.812, "duration": 8}, {"text": "The case arose in the following manner, on April 10, 1964, a patrolman named Grakenstein (ph) came to a newsstand on 42nd Street that was about 6 p.m.", "start": 41.812, "stop": 64.571, "duration": 22.76}, {"text": "And this newsstand was at a subway arcade, an entrance to a subway arcade.", "start": 64.571, "stop": 72.846, "duration": 8.28}, {"text": "He said to the attendant, the clerk, the petitioner here pointing to a book rack, Lust Pool and Shame Agent, two books of those two types.", "start": 72.846, "stop": 87.763, "duration": 14.92}, {"text": "The petitioner gave him the two books.", "start": 87.763, "stop": 91.013, "duration": 3.25}, {"text": "So testified the police officer.", "start": 91.013, "stop": 94.888, "duration": 3.88}, {"text": "And he gave the petitioner a dollar for the two books.", "start": 94.888, "stop": 101.677, "duration": 6.79}, {"text": "The petitioner said, “They're 90 cents each.”", "start": 101.677, "stop": 104.567, "duration": 2.89}, {"text": "And he said, “I'm sorry” then pointed to the one that said 75.", "start": 104.567, "stop": 107.976, "duration": 3.41}, {"text": "And the petitioner said, “Well then give me $1.65.”", "start": 107.976, "stop": 110.309, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "He paid the $1.65 for the two books, then he placed it in a brown paper bag after that he had taken the bag, he announced that he was a police officer.", "start": 110.309, "stop": 120.893, "duration": 10.58}, {"text": "The clerk said to him, the petitioner here, “What's wrong?”", "start": 120.893, "stop": 123.654, "duration": 2.76}, {"text": "This fellow have a search warrant to search the place.", "start": 123.654, "stop": 126.559, "duration": 2.91}, {"text": "He wasn't permitted to state what kind of search he conducted.", "start": 126.559, "stop": 130.61, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "He said he -- he asked the petitioner who he worked for.", "start": 130.61, "stop": 135.194, "duration": 4.58}, {"text": "The petitioner said, he worked for a Milton Black.", "start": 135.194, "stop": 138.484, "duration": 3.29}, {"text": "He asked him how long he have worked there.", "start": 138.484, "stop": 140.246, "duration": 1.76}, {"text": "He said, “About two years” alternating between a bookstore downstairs in the subway and this newsstand.", "start": 140.246, "stop": 148.625, "duration": 8.38}, {"text": "He stated to the officer, again, this is the conversation that he earns $75.00 a week.", "start": 148.625, "stop": 154.951, "duration": 6.33}, {"text": "And then the officer said to him calling to the officer, “Why do you sell this garbage?”", "start": 154.951, "stop": 159.85, "duration": 4.9}, {"text": "And he says, “There's worse stuff than that around, I think that these books here are worse,” pointing to some girly magazines that were on top.", "start": 159.85, "stop": 167.682, "duration": 7.83}, {"text": "This was the testimony after the prosecution and prosecution rested at that point.", "start": 167.682, "stop": 174.593, "duration": 6.91}, {"text": "The petitioner took the stand.He testified that he had been working for this Mr. Black for about two years.", "start": 174.593, "stop": 185.979, "duration": 11.39}, {"text": "His salary was $75.00 a week.", "start": 185.979, "stop": 188.323, "duration": 2.34}, {"text": "He had never been in any trouble before, never arrested or convicted of any offense or anything to that kind.", "start": 188.323, "stop": 194.092, "duration": 5.77}, {"text": "He hadn't read these books and knew anything about the contents of the books.", "start": 194.092, "stop": 200.369, "duration": 6.28}, {"text": "He had no recollection of his alleged oral conversation he was supposed to have with the police officer and in general simply stated that he had been there for about an hour, he was relieving somebody who had been ill.", "start": 200.369, "stop": 215.064, "duration": 14.69}, {"text": "He had once relieved that way about a week before, but generally he was downstairs within the bookstore generally.", "start": 215.064, "stop": 223.984, "duration": 8.92}, {"text": "The -- I beg your pardon?", "start": 223.984, "stop": 226.222, "duration": 2.24}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was the sentence?", "start": 226.222, "stop": 227.665, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "A suspended sentence.", "start": 227.665, "stop": 229.927, "duration": 2.26}, {"text": "The --", "start": 229.927, "stop": 230.977, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "You would have to (Inaudible) --", "start": 230.977, "stop": 234.447, "duration": 3.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "They had various books there.", "start": 234.447, "stop": 236.11, "duration": 1.66}, {"text": "There were Westerns and --", "start": 236.11, "stop": 237.073, "duration": 0.96}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 237.073, "stop": 240.9, "duration": 3.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "There's nothing in the record to indicate to except that there was some inquiry.", "start": 240.9, "stop": 244.311, "duration": 3.41}, {"text": "\"Well, do you have these kinds of books here and did you see other books,” and he said, “Yes, there were other books of this kind here.”", "start": 244.311, "stop": 250.035, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "That is but all that you have in this newsstand and as far as this record is concerned.", "start": 250.035, "stop": 257.413, "duration": 7.38}, {"text": "The -- or as far as oral conversation was concerned, the officer testified that while it was his custom to make notes of every conversation he had on arrest, at this time he had not made any notes of such a conversation and nor had he included in the complaint.", "start": 257.413, "stop": 272.612, "duration": 15.2}, {"text": "That in general is the case and the basic question here on appeal is whether or not the evidence in the constitutional sense is sufficient to the obscenity prosecution to establish the guilty knowledge in a lawful intent that is required by the First Amendment.", "start": 272.612, "stop": 298.891, "duration": 26.28}, {"text": "Now, on that issue to start off with, I would simply say this Court has stated on many occasions that when factual issues come to the court entangled in some constitutional claim, that it will review the evidence with the scrupulous care demanded by the Constitution that I take it to be basic.", "start": 298.891, "stop": 319.17, "duration": 20.28}, {"text": "Secondly, this Court has stated that the standards for judging whether or not the proof is sufficient where First Amendment issues are involved, where criminal -- alleged criminal speech is involved are very high.", "start": 319.17, "stop": 338.658, "duration": 19.49}, {"text": "In civil actions, this Court has spoken of it as -- it has to be clear, convincing, and unequivocal.", "start": 338.658, "stop": 345.12, "duration": 6.46}, {"text": "Without any troubling doubt as solid in criminal cases, this Court has stated.", "start": 345.12, "stop": 351.893, "duration": 6.77}, {"text": "It has to be beyond the reasonable doubt at the substantial evidence.", "start": 351.893, "stop": 358.25, "duration": 6.36}, {"text": "Our position here is that based on those standards.", "start": 358.25, "stop": 363.11, "duration": 4.86}, {"text": "Those standards as applied to this case have been misapplied.", "start": 363.11, "stop": 366.249, "duration": 3.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now standards -- substantial evidence of what?", "start": 366.249, "stop": 369.201, "duration": 2.95}, {"text": "Or evidence beyond a reasonable doubt of what Mr. Rosenwein?", "start": 369.201, "stop": 372.975, "duration": 3.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "That he knew --", "start": 372.975, "stop": 373.449, "duration": 0.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "That he knew the contents of the book?", "start": 373.449, "stop": 375.793, "duration": 2.34}, {"text": "Or that he knew the contents and that book was obscene?", "start": 375.793, "stop": 380.946, "duration": 5.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well obviously, the question must be that he knew that the contents were obscene.", "start": 380.946, "stop": 385.773, "duration": 4.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I suppose -- let's suppose there's a complete showing or sufficient showing that he knew the content of the book.", "start": 385.773, "stop": 402.172, "duration": 16.4}, {"text": "Then how do you show that he knew the contents were obscene.", "start": 402.172, "stop": 404.898, "duration": 2.73}, {"text": "For example, particularly if you have a difference of opinion on this Court as to whether or not the contents were obscene.", "start": 404.898, "stop": 410.859, "duration": 5.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I --", "start": 410.859, "stop": 411.092, "duration": 0.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's enough for a doubt then I see his knowledge of it, isn't it?", "start": 411.092, "stop": 414.346, "duration": 3.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 414.346, "stop": 414.814, "duration": 0.47}, {"text": "Your Honor, there is no question that it would always be a question as to how you would prove it.", "start": 414.814, "stop": 421.198, "duration": 6.38}, {"text": "But in answer to that, may I state this, this Court has stated in Roth, in Jacobellis, in Memoirs, that the elements of the effects of obscenity before you can be found guilty as far as the book is concerned is that that book must go beyond contemporary community standards under the fiction of sex.", "start": 421.198, "stop": 439.016, "duration": 17.82}, {"text": "It has to appeal to a prurient interest and has to be utterly without redeeming social importance.", "start": 439.016, "stop": 443.989, "duration": 4.97}, {"text": "And this must be -- this must coalesce although independent.", "start": 443.989, "stop": 447.385, "duration": 3.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because I --", "start": 447.385, "stop": 448.395, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, --", "start": 448.395, "stop": 448.79, "duration": 0.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- don't let me interrupt, you finish, excuse me.", "start": 448.79, "stop": 450.827, "duration": 2.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, if that be the situation if you have to prove that, it would seem to me that it follows that the scienter you're talking about, that you spoke about in Smith against California must be the knowledge as in any case whether it's criminal or not.", "start": 450.827, "stop": 466.306, "duration": 15.48}, {"text": "Knowledge that these elements exist.", "start": 466.306, "stop": 469.609, "duration": 3.3}, {"text": "Otherwise, he doesn't know that it's obscene.", "start": 469.609, "stop": 472.435, "duration": 2.83}, {"text": "It follows therefore that the problem is not standard and this is where the difficulty comes from my friend's brief.", "start": 472.435, "stop": 479.109, "duration": 6.67}, {"text": "The problem is not standard they must prove knowledge of obscenity, the question is, how much must they prove?", "start": 479.109, "stop": 485.62, "duration": 6.51}, {"text": "What is the quality of proof?", "start": 485.62, "stop": 487.593, "duration": 1.97}, {"text": "How much proof must there be for that standard?", "start": 487.593, "stop": 489.969, "duration": 2.38}, {"text": "But for a trial judge to tell the jury that all you have to find out is that's he knew the contents and he is guilty on scienter would not be following the standards that are required in the light of this Court's decisions.", "start": 489.969, "stop": 502.908, "duration": 12.94}, {"text": "Now, --", "start": 502.908, "stop": 503.253, "duration": 0.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "I suppose the evidence in this case that you have just reviewed, slim that is which show that would indicate that he did know the contents of the book because he compared it to other publications there on the table.", "start": 503.253, "stop": 516.442, "duration": 13.19}, {"text": "And would further show that he did not think that the book was obscene because he said the other things which are also publicly for sale there were more offensive.", "start": 516.442, "stop": 524.285, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "Now would -- that's not what the evidence indicates, I think, isn't it?", "start": 524.285, "stop": 526.26, "duration": 1.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- at most but I would say this, Your Honor that I don't quite follow even as to knowledge of contents.", "start": 526.26, "stop": 533.198, "duration": 6.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "He compares the book with something else --", "start": 533.198, "stop": 534.972, "duration": 1.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "If I say --", "start": 534.972, "stop": 535.569, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Would imply any -- a knowledge of that book?", "start": 535.569, "stop": 537.682, "duration": 2.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "He's looking at the cover, and that's all he had.", "start": 537.682, "stop": 540.197, "duration": 2.51}, {"text": "He put them in the bag, he looked at the cover and he said, he looks at another and has another cover to similar kind and he simply says, \"I think this is worse than that.\"", "start": 540.197, "stop": 548.686, "duration": 8.49}, {"text": "And after all, all the officer were saying this is pretty offensive, this is pretty tasteless, and he was saying well I think this is more offensive.", "start": 548.686, "stop": 554.614, "duration": 5.93}, {"text": "And he was pointing to two magazines as a matter of fact that had been held to be constitutionally protected by the highest court of the state twice in People against Richmond County, and in Lockett against G.I. Distributors.", "start": 554.614, "stop": 566.392, "duration": 11.78}, {"text": "So it was -- he was clearly innocent.", "start": 566.392, "stop": 568.42, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "Now, as to whether he knew the contents, I say you're just making a jump because --", "start": 568.42, "stop": 573.446, "duration": 5.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "But you say that even assuming, he knew the content by heart, word per word.", "start": 573.446, "stop": 577.954, "duration": 4.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 577.954, "stop": 578.679, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "He is still is as guilty on the appeal also that it was of a qualitative violated criminal law.", "start": 578.679, "stop": 584.086, "duration": 5.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you -- yes, you'd have to have some evidence to show that it is never enough it seems to me.", "start": 584.086, "stop": 588.871, "duration": 4.78}, {"text": "I say this factually.", "start": 588.871, "stop": 590.345, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "It's never enough to merely say a man were shown to have read the book or to have known the contents and per se with nothing else with no other acts or conduct on the part of the defendant to say that merely from the reading of the book one can infer that he knew that the book went beyond community standards and appealed to prurient interest and was utterly without redeeming social value.", "start": 590.345, "stop": 612.95, "duration": 22.61}, {"text": "And so it seems to me that in every one of these cases, the trial court simply has the duty to say to the jury that you must find that he knew the book was obscene as I defined obscenity.", "start": 612.95, "stop": 625.211, "duration": 12.26}, {"text": "Now, you can of course find that from all the elements in the case, all the circumstances in the case.", "start": 625.211, "stop": 630.467, "duration": 5.26}, {"text": "What he did, and if he read the book etcetera.", "start": 630.467, "stop": 633.859, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "But that in essence is the case.", "start": 633.859, "stop": 636.854, "duration": 3}, {"text": "Now, based on that, based on these standards it does not seem to me that a case has been made out here on the constitutional sense to support this conviction on the scienter issue.", "start": 636.854, "stop": 648.448, "duration": 11.59}, {"text": "He was an innocent clerk.", "start": 648.448, "stop": 650.312, "duration": 1.86}, {"text": "Everything that's in this case shows innocence, price is just nominal.", "start": 650.312, "stop": 655.79, "duration": 5.48}, {"text": "The statement is just a statement of protestation of innocence.", "start": 655.79, "stop": 659.242, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "He'd never been convicted before.", "start": 659.242, "stop": 661.351, "duration": 2.11}, {"text": "He denied he had the conversation and I must say as far as oral conversations are concerned, oral admissions, Wigmore -- Professor Wigmore has pointed out that's the most untrustworthy.", "start": 661.351, "stop": 671.401, "duration": 10.05}, {"text": "You want to come in to say, “Why do you keep this and would you want your children to read this?”", "start": 671.401, "stop": 675.73, "duration": 4.33}, {"text": "And then immediately he has known that -- he has assumed to know the contents of the book but to know that it's obscene.", "start": 675.73, "stop": 681.795, "duration": 6.06}, {"text": "If that practice were assumed no bookseller or distributor would be safe.", "start": 681.795, "stop": 690.686, "duration": 8.89}, {"text": "And so, we think that actually all that has been proven here is innocence and innocence never proves guilt and certainly in the case involving the First Amendment that should be the end of it and that conviction.", "start": 690.686, "stop": 705.931, "duration": 15.25}, {"text": "Necessarily would have to be reversed.", "start": 705.931, "stop": 707.724, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "I'd like to reserve the rest of my time.", "start": 707.724, "stop": 709.366, "duration": 1.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "The New York Statute does not expressly require scienter, does it?", "start": 709.366, "stop": 714.347, "duration": 4.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, it has however been interpreted in this Court knows.", "start": 714.347, "stop": 718.293, "duration": 3.95}, {"text": "Your Honor know in Michigan and I take it and I'm assuming despite some of the vagueness of its language which was quoted in Michigan that that means knowledge of obscenity and knowing that the book is obscene, intentionally selling it the calculated purpose of appealing to prurient interest and knowing that it goes beyond temporary standards.", "start": 718.293, "stop": 738.722, "duration": 20.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, what I meant -- understood is getting your submission to us that they appear submission as a constitutional they have a statute and it has to be read, so as to require scienter.", "start": 738.722, "stop": 752.95, "duration": 14.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, of course.", "start": 752.95, "stop": 754.318, "duration": 1.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that -- when you read the statute that way and applied to the facts of this case, you find that there's no evidence of scienter.", "start": 754.318, "stop": 764.134, "duration": 9.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is correct.", "start": 764.134, "stop": 765.944, "duration": 1.81}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why does the statute have to be read as including scienter?", "start": 765.944, "stop": 769.914, "duration": 3.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I would say it would necessarily have to because it doesn't even include the word unlawfully on this, but it has been construed by the state court as including that and reference was made to that Michigan, People against Finkelstein there was that construction although as I say somewhat vague and I have construed it as being able knowledge of obscenity.", "start": 769.914, "stop": 795.843, "duration": 25.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Uviller.", "start": 795.843, "stop": 798.432, "duration": 2.59}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.", "start": 798.432, "stop": 802.675, "duration": 4.24}, {"text": "Our arguments today are addressed to the questions which was specifically left open by this Court in Smith against California and once again in Michigan last year.", "start": 802.675, "stop": 814.331, "duration": 11.66}, {"text": "Given that any obscenity prosecution in the State Court, requires proof of the element of scienter.", "start": 814.331, "stop": 821.055, "duration": 6.72}, {"text": "The question was left open in Smith, what sort of mental element is required.", "start": 821.055, "stop": 827.642, "duration": 6.59}, {"text": "The second question left open in Smith was, “Does an honest mistake concerning the obscenity of the work excused from criminal liability?”", "start": 827.642, "stop": 838.316, "duration": 10.67}, {"text": "Now, in New York our statute has been mentioned.", "start": 838.316, "stop": 842.641, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "It does not specifically refer to scienter as an element.", "start": 842.641, "stop": 846.681, "duration": 4.04}, {"text": "But following this Court's decision in Smith, our high court in Finkelstein construed our statute as implicitly requiring proof of that element.", "start": 846.681, "stop": 857.038, "duration": 10.36}, {"text": "And ever since we have in New York prosecuted as though the statute quite explicitly required proof of knowledge.", "start": 857.038, "stop": 865.609, "duration": 8.57}, {"text": "The --", "start": 865.609, "stop": 866.07, "duration": 0.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did the -- did your Court of Appeals say scienter of what?", "start": 866.07, "stop": 871.168, "duration": 5.1}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that I think is the (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 871.168, "stop": 872.937, "duration": 1.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "So far as the statutory requirement does?", "start": 872.937, "stop": 875.024, "duration": 2.09}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "This Court in Michigan quoted the operative language from Finkelstein and in fact underlined the two phrases in that sentence from the Court of Appeals.", "start": 875.024, "stop": 886.239, "duration": 11.22}, {"text": "The Court of Appeals there said that our statute requires awareness of the character of the work.", "start": 886.239, "stop": 893.544, "duration": 7.3}, {"text": "That it is not innocent but calculated prevails of obscenity which is proscribed.", "start": 893.544, "stop": 900.071, "duration": 6.53}, {"text": "Unfortunately in this entire area, these words have been very loosely used and surprisingly never defined.", "start": 900.071, "stop": 907.329, "duration": 7.26}, {"text": "The term character is frequently used interchangeably with context.", "start": 907.329, "stop": 911.8, "duration": 4.47}, {"text": "I dare say that there are some jurisdictions which feel that the word character means the legal character of the work but I suggest that it's just a susceptible of the construction of factual character.", "start": 911.8, "stop": 921.929, "duration": 10.13}, {"text": "That is to say the category, the type of work, based upon those objectively discernible characteristics or particular a piece of material.", "start": 921.929, "stop": 931.545, "duration": 9.62}, {"text": "And I suggest that the Court of Appeals if they intended to say knowledge of what?", "start": 931.545, "stop": 937.452, "duration": 5.91}, {"text": "Did so in an extremely imprecise fashion and I think the conviction and affirmance of the conviction in this case illustrates that the courts of New York have not interpreted to think of the case as requiring knowledge of the obscenity of the work.", "start": 937.452, "stop": 950.718, "duration": 13.27}, {"text": "It is our submission here that neither did Smith -- scienter as a mental element traditionally refers to knowledge of operative fact.", "start": 950.718, "stop": 960.538, "duration": 9.82}, {"text": "Indeed, it is the circumstances which is susceptible of knowledge by the ordinary layperson or to which the criminal law is applicable.", "start": 960.538, "stop": 970.072, "duration": 9.53}, {"text": "I dare say that obscenity itself is such a difficult concept, legal conclusion that there are many experts in this field who themselves would hesitate to express a firm knowledge that a particular work was obscene because what is involved there is really a prediction of the outcome of litigation are all the way up to this Court.", "start": 970.072, "stop": 992.192, "duration": 22.12}, {"text": "And in as much as this Court has disagreed on particular pieces of work with reference to their obscenity, I think it would be extremely difficult to require knowledge of obscenity from a lawyer let alone from layperson.", "start": 992.192, "stop": 1006.229, "duration": 14.04}, {"text": "Of course, I have seen knowledge defined and broken down in the best spectrum of degrees of knowledge.", "start": 1006.229, "stop": 1013.827, "duration": 7.6}, {"text": "All the way from an accurate certainty through negligence to inquire down to perhaps a doubt of the truth of the converse.", "start": 1013.827, "stop": 1025.865, "duration": 12.04}, {"text": "But I suggest that although these distinctions between different types of knowledge are perhaps interesting from an academic sense that they are virtually impossible to apply at any sort of standard in a criminal prosecution.", "start": 1025.865, "stop": 1039.539, "duration": 13.67}, {"text": "And therefore it seems to me that the question that was left open in Smith is not precisely phrased as what sort of knowledge but rather knowledge of what.", "start": 1039.539, "stop": 1052.623, "duration": 13.08}, {"text": "If it were to be construed as knowledge of obscenity.", "start": 1052.623, "stop": 1058.469, "duration": 5.85}, {"text": "We would not have reached the result.", "start": 1058.469, "stop": 1061.459, "duration": 2.99}, {"text": "I think this Court would not have reached the result it did in the Ginzburg case.", "start": 1061.459, "stop": 1066.251, "duration": 4.79}, {"text": "For -- in the advertisements of the material in that case which were accepted at face value by the Court.", "start": 1066.251, "stop": 1073.81, "duration": 7.56}, {"text": "It was quite clear that while Ginzburg was advertising his work as salacious that he was making no bones about it according to appeal.", "start": 1073.81, "stop": 1083.211, "duration": 9.4}, {"text": "I think at the same time he was evidencing his own belief that the material was constitutionally protective and therefore not obscene because in point of fact, he stated as you -- as the court of calls that the United States Supreme Court an it's decision has specifically allowed the distribution of that sort of material.", "start": 1083.211, "stop": 1103.113, "duration": 19.9}, {"text": "Consequentially, it seems to me that this court in reaching that decision was implicitly recognizing the fact that the scienter could not be the subjective belief in obscenity.", "start": 1103.113, "stop": 1113.565, "duration": 10.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "And also (Inaudible)", "start": 1113.565, "stop": 1118.761, "duration": 5.2}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "As to honest mistake, Justice White, I --", "start": 1118.761, "stop": 1121.466, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1121.466, "stop": 1128.78, "duration": 7.31}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, the --", "start": 1128.78, "stop": 1129.549, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1129.549, "stop": 1133.97, "duration": 4.42}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "I am -- I'm very tempted to agree and say that the honest mistake was specifically rejected by that holding but I hesitate only on the grounds I'm not quite sure what an honest mistake is.", "start": 1133.97, "stop": 1146.501, "duration": 12.53}, {"text": "The extent which good faith figures in the concept.", "start": 1146.501, "stop": 1151.902, "duration": 5.4}, {"text": "I do think however that honest mistake as to obscenity is really just the other way around to the same question of requiring --", "start": 1151.902, "stop": 1159.401, "duration": 7.5}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1159.401, "stop": 1162.354, "duration": 2.95}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "I suppose if it's not honest it's not a mistake and if there is an honest mistake as to obscenity which excuses then you're merely stating the adverse of the proposition which must prove that the person knew or was aware of the obscene quality of the work.", "start": 1162.354, "stop": 1175.547, "duration": 13.19}, {"text": "So, it seems to me that in that sense the second question of Smith really is just another aspect of the first.", "start": 1175.547, "stop": 1184.047, "duration": 8.5}, {"text": "This Court in New York Times against Sullivan in an analogous First Amendment case referred to the Smith question.", "start": 1184.047, "stop": 1195.964, "duration": 11.92}, {"text": "And stated that what was required by Smith was guilty knowledge.", "start": 1195.964, "stop": 1201.33, "duration": 5.37}, {"text": "Again, following this -- the decisions of this Court in Garrison against Louisiana that guilty knowledge was construed to mean a high degree of awareness of the probable falsehood of the statement.", "start": 1201.33, "stop": 1220.149, "duration": 18.82}, {"text": "Well once again, they would seem to me that the knowledge of falsehood would be called a factual sort of determination and not a prediction of the legal conclusion and therefore this own Court's reference to the Smith knowledge is factual.", "start": 1220.149, "stop": 1235.88, "duration": 15.73}, {"text": "Indeed despite the fact that the sort of knowledge was left as an open question there in the body of the Smith decision itself contents are referred to.", "start": 1235.88, "stop": 1249.657, "duration": 13.78}, {"text": "Another analogous area of course is the area of subversion and thereto this Court has looked to the question of scienter.", "start": 1249.657, "stop": 1257.699, "duration": 8.04}, {"text": "And has required not only knowledge by an individual adjoining a subversive organization of its purposes but a shared intent in those unlawful purposes but again, this was a factual sort of scienter.", "start": 1257.699, "stop": 1272.11, "duration": 14.41}, {"text": "It was not knowledge that if he engaged in this conduct, he would be violating the law that it would be subversion but only the espousal of the purposes, a factual determination.", "start": 1272.11, "stop": 1288.104, "duration": 15.99}, {"text": "The petitioner in a footnote purports to recite -- does no more in States which have in their laws construed the scienter requirement as knowledge of obscenity.", "start": 1288.104, "stop": 1305.412, "duration": 17.31}, {"text": "However, a reference to those cases and to other cases and those jurisdictions reveals that unfortunately this is a term which in application loses its significance.", "start": 1305.412, "stop": 1318.355, "duration": 12.94}, {"text": "In California for example which one of the jurisdictions mentioned by the petitioner.", "start": 1318.355, "stop": 1323.878, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "There is a case which part explicitly states that the knowledge of obscenity is a knowledge of contents only and not a knowledge of legal result.", "start": 1323.878, "stop": 1333.383, "duration": 9.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I suppose in the practical operation of the law in those states Mr. Uviller it's a two-step thing, --", "start": 1333.383, "stop": 1340.781, "duration": 7.4}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1340.781, "stop": 1341.398, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- isn't it?", "start": 1341.398, "stop": 1341.692, "duration": 0.29}, {"text": "You've showed -- you show knowledge by the defendant of the contents of the book.", "start": 1341.692, "stop": 1349.513, "duration": 7.82}, {"text": "And then there's a finding by the court that the contents are obscene.", "start": 1349.513, "stop": 1354.618, "duration": 5.11}, {"text": "And therefore he knew the contents.", "start": 1354.618, "stop": 1357.771, "duration": 3.15}, {"text": "We say it's obscene as a matter of fact it's the law therefore he knew it was obscene.", "start": 1357.771, "stop": 1364.238, "duration": 6.47}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, as a matter of fact I --", "start": 1364.238, "stop": 1365.179, "duration": 0.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was that about the process that the --", "start": 1365.179, "stop": 1368.466, "duration": 3.29}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that is the process that those jurisdictions would follow.", "start": 1368.466, "stop": 1371.726, "duration": 3.26}, {"text": "And I think that it's not necessary to do so.", "start": 1371.726, "stop": 1377.534, "duration": 5.81}, {"text": "As you pointed out the facts of this case is susceptible of our conclusion that he knew the facts but did not know obscenity.", "start": 1377.534, "stop": 1384.581, "duration": 7.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "So it was not obscene?", "start": 1384.581, "stop": 1385.628, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "In that sense, exactly, and the same with Ginzburg.", "start": 1385.628, "stop": 1388.803, "duration": 3.18}, {"text": "However, those States which have attempted to apply a legal standard have come back to a factual standard and actual operations.", "start": 1388.803, "stop": 1395.995, "duration": 7.19}, {"text": "And I think necessarily so.", "start": 1395.995, "stop": 1397.811, "duration": 1.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, now what if we accept the hypothesis that there was a sufficient evidence in this case to show that he knew the content of the book and that the evidence is in equipoise as to whether or not he knew it was obscene.", "start": 1397.811, "stop": 1416.555, "duration": 18.74}, {"text": "And let's say that among the membership of this Court there's a division of the opinion as to whether or not in fact that involved the contents are obscene and there's certainly a reasonable doubt about his knowledge of the obscenity, isn't it?", "start": 1416.555, "stop": 1430.253, "duration": 13.7}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "There would be a reasonable doubt I think if his knowledge of the obscenity even if the court were unanimous that the work was obscene.", "start": 1430.253, "stop": 1437.82, "duration": 7.57}, {"text": "If the standard were to be his own legal appraisal of the facts that he knew them.", "start": 1437.82, "stop": 1442.844, "duration": 5.02}, {"text": "And that is to say a defendant were presumably in good faith with the standards being as flexible as they necessarily are in this feel that something was not obscene where any court in the land would disagree with it.", "start": 1442.844, "stop": 1456.284, "duration": 13.44}, {"text": "And according to the standard which is here proposed he could acquit himself by his own belief an his innocence.", "start": 1456.284, "stop": 1462.763, "duration": 6.48}, {"text": "And our submission to this Court that this proposition is normally in the criminal law, a man cannot be his own judge.", "start": 1462.763, "stop": 1472.206, "duration": 9.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, there are those that think that any suppression of good faith expression is an anomaly in the criminal law in the light of the First Amendment.", "start": 1472.206, "stop": 1483.404, "duration": 11.2}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that with this proposition is universally accepted I think that the only question is what is a good faith expression.", "start": 1483.404, "stop": 1489.813, "duration": 6.41}, {"text": "I think that anything which is deemed a good faith expression is certainly protected.", "start": 1489.813, "stop": 1496.039, "duration": 6.23}, {"text": "If the material in this case comes within that category I don't think that we need even reach the question of scienter because he would go out on the question of obscenity as defined by Roth.", "start": 1496.039, "stop": 1506.207, "duration": 10.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "In other words if the majority in this Court should find that neither of these books is in fact obscene and there could not be a conviction even though you show that he knew the contents of the books and had a good faith belief that they were obscene.", "start": 1506.207, "stop": 1525.119, "duration": 18.91}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Absolutely.", "start": 1525.119, "stop": 1526.327, "duration": 1.21}, {"text": "His belief --", "start": 1526.327, "stop": 1526.402, "duration": 0.08}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Uviller --", "start": 1526.402, "stop": 1527.216, "duration": 0.81}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "His belief could not convict him.", "start": 1527.216, "stop": 1529.692, "duration": 2.48}, {"text": "If he had a manifested bad belief by advertising the work and such then presumably that conduct on his part would have some effect on the nature of the material itself under the Ginzburg doctrine.", "start": 1529.692, "stop": 1543.451, "duration": 13.76}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now this case is up here (Inaudible)", "start": 1543.451, "stop": 1549.644, "duration": 6.19}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, it is not out there.", "start": 1549.644, "stop": 1550.37, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1550.37, "stop": 1558.48, "duration": 8.11}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct, Justice Harlan.", "start": 1558.48, "stop": 1559.679, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "They don't see how you can separate them out do you because what is involved here is his knowledge.", "start": 1559.679, "stop": 1567.544, "duration": 7.87}, {"text": "His knowledge, and if as you say even though he knew the contents and even though he had a good faith conviction that they were obscene he could not be convicted if they were not obscene.", "start": 1567.544, "stop": 1581.453, "duration": 13.91}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, our --", "start": 1581.453, "stop": 1583.006, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "You've just told us that and I think --", "start": 1583.006, "stop": 1584.552, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, but our submission is that the -- whether he believed they were obscene or believed that they were not obscene is a totally irrelevant consideration from a constitutional standpoint that the questions are merely two.", "start": 1584.552, "stop": 1596.69, "duration": 12.14}, {"text": "Were the books in fact obscene and did he have some awareness of the facts about these books which in the case of obscenity is something which is objectively perceivable?", "start": 1596.69, "stop": 1606.967, "duration": 10.28}, {"text": "You have a written material, you have photographs, you have a physical object about which something can be learned even by a layman.", "start": 1606.967, "stop": 1614.772, "duration": 7.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I ask you, about another phase of this case.", "start": 1614.772, "stop": 1619.36, "duration": 4.59}, {"text": "And my question relates to the possibility that has occurred there may be a difference here between scienter and mens rea and that perhaps that difference could be fruitfully explored.", "start": 1619.36, "stop": 1638.775, "duration": 19.42}, {"text": "Now, in this case the petitioner was a clerk.", "start": 1638.775, "stop": 1645.29, "duration": 6.51}, {"text": "And the policeman came up as I remembered the record and saw these two books on the shelf and he picked them out and handed the clerk the money and the clerk wrapped them up and according to the observer's conversation showing the record which I take it the petitioner denies.", "start": 1645.29, "stop": 1665.983, "duration": 20.69}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did not deny.", "start": 1665.983, "stop": 1667.117, "duration": 1.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "He did not deny.", "start": 1667.117, "stop": 1667.805, "duration": 0.69}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "He said he didn't recall one way or another.", "start": 1667.805, "stop": 1669.032, "duration": 1.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I see, well then in the event if you start thinking about this case in terms of mens rea, perhaps it is somewhat impressive that the policeman selected the books that the petitioner was a clerk he did not place, there's no evidence that he was responsible for displaying these books.", "start": 1669.032, "stop": 1698, "duration": 28.97}, {"text": "That he made no effort to persuade the policeman to take these books.", "start": 1698, "stop": 1704.84, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "He did not push the books on them, he did not suggest the books, he did not advertise the books, and he did not place the books on the rack.", "start": 1704.84, "stop": 1716.111, "duration": 11.27}, {"text": "Now, if you start thinking about that kind of a situation and conventional criminal law terms then you get a kind of an attenuated mens rea, don't you?", "start": 1716.111, "stop": 1730.707, "duration": 14.6}, {"text": "That is to say attenuated in the sense the ancient maxim he done it, didn't he?", "start": 1730.707, "stop": 1737.172, "duration": 6.46}, {"text": "I mean to say he sold the books but it was not -- there's no indication whatever in this record that he had any intent to purvey or to promote the sale of this particular books rather than other books using the phrase or the word in Ginzburg there's nothing like candor that is involved here.", "start": 1737.172, "stop": 1772.625, "duration": 35.45}, {"text": "If there is mens rea it is a very attenuated sort of mens rea.", "start": 1772.625, "stop": 1778.643, "duration": 6.02}, {"text": "Now, if you take that line of approach to this perhaps you get a different view of what scienter means as applied in this vexatious field or perhaps you get away from the scienter entirely and pursue to see what kind of trouble you'll get into using the phrase.", "start": 1778.643, "stop": 1802.396, "duration": 23.75}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1802.396, "stop": 1802.427, "duration": 0.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you'd care to comment on that I'd be most grateful.", "start": 1802.427, "stop": 1805.444, "duration": 3.02}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I have been thinking very much along the same lines myself it's a novel idea in the field.", "start": 1805.444, "stop": 1812.743, "duration": 7.3}, {"text": "I think that a distinction would have to be made quite sharply between knowledge and intent.", "start": 1812.743, "stop": 1818.755, "duration": 6.01}, {"text": "Unfortunately the distinction which is rarely made but it should be in the criminal law, I think that as to knowledge the mental element of knowledge one could be quite content with a factual knowledge as to mens rea or intent.", "start": 1818.755, "stop": 1834.534, "duration": 15.78}, {"text": "What we would be doing in effect is converting this crime into a crime of specific intent.", "start": 1834.534, "stop": 1842.433, "duration": 7.9}, {"text": "The problem of intent as the commentators have noticed in field very frequently is the type of intent whether it would be general or specifically it's not very clearly spelled out and I would say that in New York this usually thought to the legislation to say at least the local state courts.", "start": 1842.433, "stop": 1858.113, "duration": 15.68}, {"text": "But in New York we have not deem this to be a crime of specific intent.", "start": 1858.113, "stop": 1862.564, "duration": 4.45}, {"text": "However, consistently with the opinion of this Court in Ginzburg and related cases I can easily see how it might become a constitutionally necessary element in the crime to prove that the material was distributed with the intent to appeal the prurient interest which is a specific intent rather than a general mens rea sort of intent.", "start": 1862.564, "stop": 1885.405, "duration": 22.84}, {"text": "And I think that this is the kind of element that would probably be imperceptible of proof.", "start": 1885.405, "stop": 1890.456, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "Your Honor, mentioned the number of elements in this particular factual situation that do relate to it and all we have to do is to think back to the Ginzburg and Michigan to see the contrary so with the facts.", "start": 1890.456, "stop": 1900.728, "duration": 10.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "What in the world are these criteria have to do with the First Amendment of the United States Constitution?", "start": 1900.728, "stop": 1909.05, "duration": 8.32}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I'm relying on the Court's decision in the Ginzburg case.", "start": 1909.05, "stop": 1913.222, "duration": 4.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I guess that's the problem.", "start": 1913.222, "stop": 1918.02, "duration": 4.8}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "I --", "start": 1918.02, "stop": 1918.105, "duration": 0.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, obscenity does have some -- this whole field has something to do with the First Amendment, isn't it?", "start": 1918.105, "stop": 1923.488, "duration": 5.38}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Exactly.", "start": 1923.488, "stop": 1924.725, "duration": 1.24}, {"text": "Well, certainly it does and I -- perhaps answered that --", "start": 1924.725, "stop": 1926.509, "duration": 1.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And your question is -– and your question is rather there is a matter of constitutional theory the First Amendment carves out, excepts, eliminates, and make some exception through its words of the entire feel about obscenity whatever that may mean.", "start": 1926.509, "stop": 1950.526, "duration": 24.02}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that's the --", "start": 1950.526, "stop": 1950.859, "duration": 0.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or whether the first -- or whether the only permissible exception that the First Amendment may be the conduct of individuals -- criminal conduct.", "start": 1950.859, "stop": 1964.456, "duration": 13.6}, {"text": "In fact it has been indicated and some of the concurrences and the sense in this Court.", "start": 1964.456, "stop": 1972.702, "duration": 8.25}, {"text": "I believe there's something to that effect in one of the concurring opinions in Smith against California.", "start": 1972.702, "stop": 1982.538, "duration": 9.84}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "There is some history of that usually a minority of the Court, Chief Justices written long before Ginzburg along that line.", "start": 1982.538, "stop": 1990.018, "duration": 7.48}, {"text": "But I would have answered somewhat differently a greater length of question of what this has to do with the Constitution, Mr. Stewart in this fashion.", "start": 1990.018, "stop": 1999.223, "duration": 9.2}, {"text": "The theory of Smith was that because of certain inherent and necessary vagueness in the concept of obscenity and because these ambiguities unfortunately have a tendency to promote self-censorship.", "start": 1999.223, "stop": 2016.017, "duration": 16.79}, {"text": "In violation of the spirit of the First Amendment it is necessary to so far delimit the area of prosecution as to minimize the hazard of self-censorship.", "start": 2016.017, "stop": 2027.388, "duration": 11.37}, {"text": "And that the First Amendment requires us without such measures as will minimize the hazard of self-censorship.", "start": 2027.388, "stop": 2034.671, "duration": 7.28}, {"text": "That I think is the way the intent factor or the knowledge factor comes into the field.", "start": 2034.671, "stop": 2041.741, "duration": 7.07}, {"text": "I do think that however that if it's elusory to believe that by requiring proof to come back to knowledge for a moment, proof of knowledge of obscenity as a means for minimizing the hazards of self-censorship, we're diluting ourselves.", "start": 2041.741, "stop": 2058.505, "duration": 16.76}, {"text": "It has a superficial appeal.", "start": 2058.505, "stop": 2060.659, "duration": 2.15}, {"text": "If you think of the very hardest core pornography they very rarely any doubt that anyone who sees that must know at once not only it's facts or factual character of it but also that it is obscene in proscribed by law.", "start": 2060.659, "stop": 2074.672, "duration": 14.01}, {"text": "Consequently, in eliminating prosecution to the hardest of the hard called pornography but which perhaps is a worthwhile end indeed in New York, our law has been construed as being limited to prosecution of hardcore pornography.", "start": 2074.672, "stop": 2088.987, "duration": 14.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's why it's been verbalized, but that's not the way the courts act in a state?", "start": 2088.987, "stop": 2092.539, "duration": 3.55}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Precisely my next point.", "start": 2092.539, "stop": 2093.809, "duration": 1.27}, {"text": "Unfortunately, this superficial appeal evaporates when you see in the way in which it's applied because just as to one person, something it's unequivocally hardcore pornography and anyone looking at it should have known that it was obscene.", "start": 2093.809, "stop": 2107.173, "duration": 13.36}, {"text": "So to another judge to another court are something, are considerably further along toward the border is just as unequivocally pornographic and should have been perceived as such.", "start": 2107.173, "stop": 2118.198, "duration": 11.03}, {"text": "Consequently, I think that it's elusory to think that we can limit and then -- we were back to the same problem of the definition of obscenity and the fact that courts differ on obscenity.", "start": 2118.198, "stop": 2129.85, "duration": 11.65}, {"text": "I think the border disputes will be with us as long as obscenity is an exception to the First Amendment.", "start": 2129.85, "stop": 2136.359, "duration": 6.51}, {"text": "I do think however that it may be constitutionally preferable to look at it in terms of intent now that we have the Ginzburg decision rather than in terms of knowledge.", "start": 2136.359, "stop": 2150.201, "duration": 13.84}, {"text": "I think it would be an outrage to the theory of the criminal law to require that anyone prosecuted for a crime to be guilty must believe in his own guilt.", "start": 2150.201, "stop": 2162.261, "duration": 12.06}, {"text": "I think it would be circular to define pornography as that which anybody looking at it would know what's pornography.", "start": 2162.261, "stop": 2171.336, "duration": 9.07}, {"text": "Obviously, the circularity of that definition is out.", "start": 2171.336, "stop": 2175.014, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "Consequently, I don't think that the constitutional purpose of limiting the hazards of self-censorship is served as adequately by redefinition of the traditional concept of scienter as it would be by pursuit of Justice Fortas' suggestion that we look at it in terms of scienter.", "start": 2175.014, "stop": 2194.441, "duration": 19.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Specific intent.", "start": 2194.441, "stop": 2195.499, "duration": 1.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, mens rea --", "start": 2195.499, "stop": 2196.293, "duration": 0.79}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "In terms of specific --", "start": 2196.293, "stop": 2196.752, "duration": 0.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- beguile the mind.", "start": 2196.752, "stop": 2197.691, "duration": 0.94}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- specific intent, that's right.", "start": 2197.691, "stop": 2198.793, "duration": 1.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And if you use the standard of specific intent here as we're discussing I would think pretty clearly it follows that that is not present in this case.", "start": 2198.793, "stop": 2210.581, "duration": 11.79}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "It would be extremely difficult for me to argue that in this case the clerk in the store specifically intended to appeal the prurient interests.", "start": 2210.581, "stop": 2219.356, "duration": 8.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "So that in this constitutional case, under the First Amendment of the United States Constitution, what becomes important is the fact that this man is making $75.00 a week as his salary as contracted to Mr. Ginzburg who has been sent to prison for five years because he was making more money, is that it?", "start": 2219.356, "stop": 2237.047, "duration": 17.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2237.047, "stop": 2237.424, "duration": 0.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "How is that relevant?", "start": 2237.424, "stop": 2239.326, "duration": 1.9}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "I certainly don't think that that fact would be the only factor.", "start": 2239.326, "stop": 2243.422, "duration": 4.1}, {"text": "I -- specific intent in any case is of course inferable from operative facts also.", "start": 2243.422, "stop": 2249.715, "duration": 6.29}, {"text": "Again in the sense, you're getting back to a factual question.", "start": 2249.715, "stop": 2254.067, "duration": 4.35}, {"text": "If this police officer had gone up to a $75.00 a week clerk and express his desire for reading material in a manner other than by just naming a title of the book that was on display, asking for the book by title.", "start": 2254.067, "stop": 2271.942, "duration": 17.88}, {"text": "Expressing his desire for certain type of book or movie and the clerk had supplied the book in response to that desire I think it might be reasonable for a fact finder to infer the intent of the seller was to ponder, was to appeal to the prurient interest of the particular customer.", "start": 2271.942, "stop": 2292.392, "duration": 20.45}, {"text": "It's a novel theory, Justice Stewart and it's extremely difficult to try and visit the facts that might fit within it.", "start": 2292.392, "stop": 2300.289, "duration": 7.9}, {"text": "If I were to be completely candid I would probably say that the courts in applying such a new standard would pretty much come around to the same results that they have now.", "start": 2300.289, "stop": 2308.988, "duration": 8.7}, {"text": "Because once again, it would be felt that any person who sold or distributed or displayed the material which the court feels is obscene would be doing so with the intent to ponder because for what other purpose could somebody be selling something that is obscene.", "start": 2308.988, "stop": 2325.484, "duration": 16.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Except you've got an illustration of that, the opposite thing right here and if I'm correct, I remember People against Finkelstein and they also have many case in Minesotta.", "start": 2325.484, "stop": 2337.099, "duration": 11.62}, {"text": "The clerk --", "start": 2337.099, "stop": 2338.57, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "I – the People against --", "start": 2338.57, "stop": 2339.223, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "With the products in the criminal process because a policeman comes to a rack and picks up two books, hands the clerk the money.", "start": 2339.223, "stop": 2351.116, "duration": 11.89}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, yes, it -- I don't know that this Court could say that it's unreasonable for a fact finder to infer from the nature of the book that was sold.", "start": 2351.116, "stop": 2362.211, "duration": 11.09}, {"text": "That the sale was made with the intent to ponder.", "start": 2362.211, "stop": 2367.632, "duration": 5.42}, {"text": "I can see how fact finders might disagree on the question but I don't know that it would be proper to say that it's a matter of law, or constitutional law if such a conclusion would be unreasonable.", "start": 2367.632, "stop": 2377.742, "duration": 10.11}, {"text": "And I think that if we bear in mind that what we're dealing with here is a matter of which in the first instance must be found to be obscene and in New York must be found to be hardcore pornography.", "start": 2377.742, "stop": 2387.697, "duration": 9.95}, {"text": "And therefore, without any other value at all except its appeal to prurient interest, it might well be thought that anybody who purveys or shows itself is necessarily selling it for the purpose or with a specific intent to ponder.", "start": 2387.697, "stop": 2401.219, "duration": 13.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, its (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2401.219, "stop": 2401.766, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's the difficulty with --", "start": 2401.766, "stop": 2403.208, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it's a little too late to say that isn't after Smith against California when which ever one of the opinions one reads or the one reads Justice Harlan's opinion.", "start": 2403.208, "stop": 2416.928, "duration": 13.72}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "I didn't read (Inaudible) --", "start": 2416.928, "stop": 2418.223, "duration": 1.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I'm saying about the --", "start": 2418.223, "stop": 2421.617, "duration": 3.39}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2421.617, "stop": 2423.634, "duration": 2.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "In the other case.", "start": 2423.634, "stop": 2425.892, "duration": 2.26}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2425.892, "stop": 2427.527, "duration": 1.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 2427.527, "stop": 2428.146, "duration": 0.62}, {"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2428.146, "stop": 2432.148, "duration": 4}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Manual?", "start": 2432.148, "stop": 2433.001, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Manual Enterprises cases.", "start": 2433.001, "stop": 2434.626, "duration": 1.63}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, that.", "start": 2434.626, "stop": 2435.715, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "That it says it's too late to say that at the Manual Enterprises where you'll need Justice Harlan's opinion or the opinion of Justice Brennan.", "start": 2435.715, "stop": 2451.67, "duration": 15.95}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's too late to say that the intent can be inferred from the nature of the material.", "start": 2451.67, "stop": 2456.768, "duration": 5.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's too late to say that all you have to do is to show that thing -- book appeals prurient interest and from that as --", "start": 2456.768, "stop": 2464.941, "duration": 8.17}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, no, no.", "start": 2464.941, "stop": 2466.337, "duration": 1.4}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2466.337, "stop": 2467.727, "duration": 1.39}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, no, no, I don't think I made my point clear.", "start": 2467.727, "stop": 2471.653, "duration": 3.93}, {"text": "I said that if the book is found to be obscene by the court, then necessarily it is without any value.", "start": 2471.653, "stop": 2477.804, "duration": 6.15}, {"text": "And someone selling it might therefore be inferred to be selling it for the purpose of appealing since that is by definition the only quality which the work has.", "start": 2477.804, "stop": 2488.209, "duration": 10.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then is that so --", "start": 2488.209, "stop": 2488.344, "duration": 0.14}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap)", "start": 2488.344, "stop": 2489.092, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "You wouldn't say that's scienter, would you?", "start": 2489.092, "stop": 2491.303, "duration": 2.21}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir, I wouldn't say that.", "start": 2491.303, "stop": 2492.568, "duration": 1.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "I wouldn't know, I wouldn't think so.", "start": 2492.568, "stop": 2493.493, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, what I'm saying is that the difficulty with taking a specific intent standard is that specific (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2493.493, "stop": 2498.409, "duration": 4.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- all I want to know is you don't think that -- you wouldn't -- without the conversation in here you would have no proof of scienter.", "start": 2498.409, "stop": 2507.873, "duration": 9.46}, {"text": "I mean without the conversation that well we have worse book.", "start": 2507.873, "stop": 2510.866, "duration": 2.99}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2510.866, "stop": 2511.404, "duration": 0.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "If there is nothing but a sale with 75 cents or $1.85 or whatever it was, no conversation that, I want these two books, here is the money, sale completed and the only evidence there was the book itself plus that transaction, you wouldn't think that conviction on the standard?", "start": 2511.404, "stop": 2533.842, "duration": 22.44}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, well I would -- in this particular instance, or generally, I think --", "start": 2533.842, "stop": 2537.977, "duration": 4.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's the area we heard --", "start": 2537.977, "stop": 2538.298, "duration": 0.32}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- will depend on the quality -- it would depend upon the work.", "start": 2538.298, "stop": 2541.915, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "That is to say, if there is familiar sale of the work which is clearly on its face observable to anybody who looks at it is obscenity.", "start": 2541.915, "stop": 2549.488, "duration": 7.57}, {"text": "Then you would say the person who sold it by looking at it would know that it's -- enough about its factual character.", "start": 2549.488, "stop": 2553.777, "duration": 4.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, yes but you just skipped into the conversation here, the fact that he knew what was in it by looking at it.", "start": 2553.777, "stop": 2561.897, "duration": 8.12}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, and it was --", "start": 2561.897, "stop": 2562.107, "duration": 0.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "And if there's no evidence that he knew what was in it, you would say the conviction were the same.", "start": 2562.107, "stop": 2567.533, "duration": 5.43}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "If there was no evidence that he knew what was in it, the conviction ought not to be the same.", "start": 2567.533, "stop": 2570.969, "duration": 3.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the only evidence in this case is the exchange of, “Why do you sell that stuff?”", "start": 2570.969, "stop": 2575.999, "duration": 5.03}, {"text": "And he says, “We have worse than that.”", "start": 2575.999, "stop": 2579.758, "duration": 3.76}, {"text": "Is that the only evidence?", "start": 2579.758, "stop": 2580.81, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, there's one other thing and that goes back to the question on whether you can tell a book by its cover.", "start": 2580.81, "stop": 2585.95, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "There is the book itself and there is the picture on the book.", "start": 2585.95, "stop": 2589.271, "duration": 3.32}, {"text": "There is the blurb on the front cover.", "start": 2589.271, "stop": 2591.478, "duration": 2.21}, {"text": "There is the description on the back from which even without the conversation.", "start": 2591.478, "stop": 2596.61, "duration": 5.13}, {"text": "A fact finder might conclude that he knew enough about the general nature of the book, the general factual character of the book to be chargeable with the knowledge of its contents under this very doctrine.", "start": 2596.61, "stop": 2606.088, "duration": 9.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "But nobody has ever -- there's no evidence in this case he ever read the blurb.", "start": 2606.088, "stop": 2612.034, "duration": 5.95}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it's only six words long.", "start": 2612.034, "stop": 2615.894, "duration": 3.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but you don't -- I wouldn't suppose that he would read every blurb in every book he ever sold.", "start": 2615.894, "stop": 2621.999, "duration": 6.11}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "But he's not required to Justice White.", "start": 2621.999, "stop": 2624.301, "duration": 2.3}, {"text": "Under the -- under Smith against California, if it is there in front of him and there's enough about it objectively to put him on notice then he cannot escape liability by his failure to investigate further and that is why I understand Smith.", "start": 2624.301, "stop": 2637.461, "duration": 13.16}, {"text": "Its not --", "start": 2637.461, "stop": 2637.585, "duration": 0.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "What you're saying -- you're saying the standards should be either he knew or he should have known?", "start": 2637.585, "stop": 2641.191, "duration": 3.61}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, I think that is the standard under Smith.", "start": 2641.191, "stop": 2643.863, "duration": 2.67}, {"text": "I think quite clearly that that's the standard under Smith.", "start": 2643.863, "stop": 2645.865, "duration": 2}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you say it is the standard under the New York Law.", "start": 2645.865, "stop": 2649.397, "duration": 3.53}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "New York Law does adopt Smith in that respect.", "start": 2649.397, "stop": 2652.308, "duration": 2.91}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Smith laid down under that statute?", "start": 2652.308, "stop": 2654.916, "duration": 2.61}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Smith laid down the standard as --", "start": 2654.916, "stop": 2655.683, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2655.683, "stop": 2658.046, "duration": 2.36}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Smith did not lay down any standard as to what he had to know but Smith did lay down the proposition that a man who is not familiar with every written word in the shop, nonetheless does not escape criminal liability if there were works which he should have investigated further.", "start": 2658.046, "stop": 2676.44, "duration": 18.39}, {"text": "In other words, he cannot chill himself by negligent failure to inquire into the factual nature of the works himself.", "start": 2676.44, "stop": 2684.757, "duration": 8.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I wouldn't suppose the clerk is negligent or that he -- that you can say a clerk should know every word -- every contents of 10,000 volumes in a store, would you?", "start": 2684.757, "stop": 2694.983, "duration": 10.23}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or the book seller, no, neither one.", "start": 2694.983, "stop": 2696.412, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or either -- or the owner either.", "start": 2696.412, "stop": 2697.841, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right, neither one.", "start": 2697.841, "stop": 2699.304, "duration": 1.46}, {"text": "Well, this was specifically discussed in Smith as Your Honor recalls and it was stated that Smith said, --", "start": 2699.304, "stop": 2704.17, "duration": 4.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, my only question is --", "start": 2704.17, "stop": 2704.737, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- that it does not require it.", "start": 2704.737, "stop": 2705.873, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "My only question is why isn't there enough evidence in this case to sustain its conviction?", "start": 2705.873, "stop": 2709.741, "duration": 3.87}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, well in this case --", "start": 2709.741, "stop": 2711.474, "duration": 1.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or narrowly, if you have to know the content --", "start": 2711.474, "stop": 2715.688, "duration": 4.21}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "In this case, if you have to -- if knowledge requires knowledge of the factual contents then a strongest piece of evidence is the defendant himself said, this is not as bad as something else.", "start": 2715.688, "stop": 2727.303, "duration": 11.61}, {"text": "And if he had sufficient knowledge of its character to make a comparison between the working question and another work then he had sufficient knowledge for the purposes of constitutional scienter.", "start": 2727.303, "stop": 2735.483, "duration": 8.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "And if you're saying this is some evidence and we couldn't reverse on this basis as there being no evidence.", "start": 2735.483, "stop": 2741.369, "duration": 5.89}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Correct.", "start": 2741.369, "stop": 2741.522, "duration": 0.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "There's some evidence.", "start": 2741.522, "stop": 2742.455, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "H. Richard Uviller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Correct.", "start": 2742.455, "stop": 2745.525, "duration": 3.07}, {"text": "Thank you.", "start": 2745.525, "stop": 2746.399, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Very well.", "start": 2746.399, "stop": 2747.517, "duration": 1.12}, {"text": "Mr. Rosenwein.", "start": 2747.517, "stop": 2750.862, "duration": 3.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think it -- in answering the arguments of the state to it -- once again state that this Court in Smith against California reiterated and carried forward the thought that it had announced in Roth and Alvis (ph), that an obscenity limitation on speech is an exception and therefore the standards for judging obscenity would have to be narrowed.", "start": 2750.862, "stop": 2776.455, "duration": 25.59}, {"text": "And as against claims of vagueness, against claims of possible self-censorship this Court said, \"We will put in a requirement of scienter.\"", "start": 2776.455, "stop": 2787.217, "duration": 10.76}, {"text": "And in Smith reiterated that that the obscenity laws in general would be in serious difficulty constitutionally unless there was proof of scienter.", "start": 2787.217, "stop": 2798.551, "duration": 11.33}, {"text": "Now this Court also had said, time and again in cases as a significant as perhaps this area, cases involving advocacy built to overthrow the Government by force and violence, there must be proof of specific intent, there must be proof of guilty knowledge because if you don't have that then there are possibilities, great possibilities of self-censorship.", "start": 2798.551, "stop": 2821.063, "duration": 22.51}, {"text": "People will be afraid to talk.", "start": 2821.063, "stop": 2822.457, "duration": 1.39}, {"text": "People will be afraid to write.", "start": 2822.457, "stop": 2824.092, "duration": 1.64}, {"text": "People will be afraid to express themselves and the whole country and the community suffers as a result.", "start": 2824.092, "stop": 2829.045, "duration": 4.95}, {"text": "Now, what does the state argue here?", "start": 2829.045, "stop": 2831.827, "duration": 2.78}, {"text": "The state virtually tells us that although the man who sells the book or distributes or even the publisher is absolutely innocent in his intent.", "start": 2831.827, "stop": 2841.16, "duration": 9.33}, {"text": "He really doesn't know.", "start": 2841.16, "stop": 2843.44, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "And they can't prove that he knows.", "start": 2843.44, "stop": 2845.761, "duration": 2.32}, {"text": "Nevertheless, he must stand convicted.", "start": 2845.761, "stop": 2848.395, "duration": 2.63}, {"text": "Can this lead to anything else if the rule is adopted that the state asked for, which is not only a delusion of the scienter requirement but actually elimination and a pre-Smith situation.", "start": 2848.395, "stop": 2861.401, "duration": 13.01}, {"text": "Can it be anything else but the same self-censorship which this Court has constantly tried to admonish must not happen.", "start": 2861.401, "stop": 2869.429, "duration": 8.03}, {"text": "Now as far as Ginzburg is concerned, my friend forgets the cause that in Michigan, this Court emphasized that the scienter proof is stringent.", "start": 2869.429, "stop": 2879.939, "duration": 10.51}, {"text": "And as far as Ginzburg was concerned I think the question of scienter was stipulated out.", "start": 2879.939, "stop": 2885.732, "duration": 5.79}, {"text": "And if it -- as to whether Ginzburg believed that it was constitutionally protected, I suppose an answer might be a trier of the facts if you had proof.", "start": 2885.732, "stop": 2898.36, "duration": 12.63}, {"text": "If the record in Ginzburg had proof that nevertheless would show that he did believe it was obscene, then I suppose you have a situation where you didn't have to believe them.", "start": 2898.36, "stop": 2907.779, "duration": 9.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "The evidence in the Ginzburg case was that Mr. Ginzburg thought that what he was publishing was protected by the recent decision of this very Court.", "start": 2907.779, "stop": 2919.199, "duration": 11.42}, {"text": "He talked about having been given a green light.", "start": 2919.199, "stop": 2921.885, "duration": 2.69}, {"text": "And it was as I read and understood the opinion of the court in the Ginzburg case that was part of the foundation for his conviction.", "start": 2921.885, "stop": 2929.659, "duration": 7.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Your Honor.", "start": 2929.659, "stop": 2930.431, "duration": 0.77}, {"text": "Let me say this that if the record in the Ginzburg case which of course I'm not familiar had no evidence of the man's guilty knowledge or specific intent.", "start": 2930.431, "stop": 2940.363, "duration": 9.93}, {"text": "And if that issue was open I would think that he had been unfairly convicted.", "start": 2940.363, "stop": 2948.45, "duration": 8.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, I don't -- I am --", "start": 2948.45, "stop": 2949.957, "duration": 1.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, I --", "start": 2949.957, "stop": 2950.096, "duration": 0.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think there is some other evidence in the record.", "start": 2950.096, "stop": 2952.977, "duration": 2.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now on the question of specific intent and guilty knowledge that was raised by Justice Fortas, I would say simply this, I had always understood that both elements are required and as a matter of fact in the States of Louisiana and Ohio, those are the two requirements.", "start": 2952.977, "stop": 2972.734, "duration": 19.76}, {"text": "But one is dependent on the other.", "start": 2972.734, "stop": 2975.703, "duration": 2.97}, {"text": "In other words, specific intent, the intent to appeal the prurient interest knowing that it goes beyond community standards and has any value, that specific intent to appeal the prurient interest is a state of mind.", "start": 2975.703, "stop": 2988.313, "duration": 12.61}, {"text": "How do you prove a state of mind?", "start": 2988.313, "stop": 2990.858, "duration": 2.55}, {"text": "Only by the clearest proof that the man had guilty knowledge.", "start": 2990.858, "stop": 2994.846, "duration": 3.99}, {"text": "So that you would have to prove that he knew that the material was obscene.", "start": 2994.846, "stop": 2999.776, "duration": 4.93}, {"text": "He knew that it went beyond contemporary standards and knew that it had appealed to a prurient interest and knew he was utterly without value and (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2999.776, "stop": 3007.293, "duration": 7.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, isn't there another approach to it and that is, without trying to answer the very difficult question of what he knew or he believed as indicated by Ginzburg as I read it, that the man promoted that what he sold, that he tried to get people to buy it on his representation that it would appeal to prurient interest or whatever more suitable words might be so that you don't get in -- on that basis perhaps you don't get into the refined semantics of scienter, may be getting to some other refined semantics.", "start": 3007.293, "stop": 3054.265, "duration": 46.97}, {"text": "But in any event you don't get into those particulars.", "start": 3054.265, "stop": 3056.987, "duration": 2.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think you would, Your Honor.", "start": 3056.987, "stop": 3058.529, "duration": 1.54}, {"text": "Come into another series of problems if you eliminated scienter or guilty knowledge.", "start": 3058.529, "stop": 3064.166, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "The man had to know.", "start": 3064.166, "stop": 3064.576, "duration": 0.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I didn't suggest -- excuse me, but I didn't suggest eliminating it, I suggested the possibility that when you start using as your instrument for a decision, not the legal concept of scienter but the legal concept of specific intent, perhaps then the role played by the concept of the scienter becomes diluted and therefore perhaps the necessity for a precise definition, a meticulous finding and it even comes less appealable.", "start": 3064.576, "stop": 3102.498, "duration": 37.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Sam Rosenwein", "textObjs": [{"text": "And I -- if I may continue this dialogue, Your Honor, just for one more moment then I would say this, that if you do attempt to -- you have these two standards that is guilty knowledge plus a specific intent and in any way try to dilute one or the other, you always have the basic problem, how does this comport with First Amendment requirements?", "start": 3102.498, "stop": 3128.795, "duration": 26.3}, {"text": "Will this lead to ambiguity, further ambiguity?", "start": 3128.795, "stop": 3132.593, "duration": 3.8}, {"text": "And will this lead to the type of self censorship which we must avoid if speech in press ought to be free in the country?", "start": 3132.593, "stop": 3141.174, "duration": 8.58}, {"text": "In any event, I return to my initial position here that there is simply no evidence in the constitutional sense that is sufficient to justify the conviction that's like Redmond.", "start": 3141.174, "stop": 3155.542, "duration": 14.37}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - October 10, 1966", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren13/oral_argument_audio/23558", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Number 16, William L. Austin, petitioner versus Kentucky.", "start": 0, "stop": 22.668, "duration": 22.67}, {"text": "Mr. Fleishman.", "start": 22.668, "stop": 23.932, "duration": 1.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, members of the Court.", "start": 23.932, "stop": 28.618, "duration": 4.69}, {"text": "Almost three years to the date, a private citizen, a Mrs. Catherine Wolfen, walked into the Read More Bookstore in Paducah, Kentucky and ordered three books, two magazines rather.", "start": 28.618, "stop": 48.301, "duration": 19.68}, {"text": "She ordered four and she purchased two magazines the required title.", "start": 48.301, "stop": 52.61, "duration": 4.31}, {"text": "She then marched over to the McCracken County Court House and swore out a complaint in statutory language.", "start": 52.61, "stop": 64.601, "duration": 11.99}, {"text": "He said that Mr. Austin, the owner of the store, had violated the Kentucky Obscenity Law.", "start": 64.601, "stop": 74.41, "duration": 9.81}, {"text": "The basis of her charge was that purchase by her and her reading of the magazines in her conclusion based on no judicial standards that the magazines were in fact obscene.", "start": 74.41, "stop": 93.102, "duration": 18.69}, {"text": "The statute involved provides that any person who sells an obscene book or magazine, knowing the contents or character is guilty of an offense.", "start": 93.102, "stop": 111.079, "duration": 17.98}, {"text": "The statute also provides that any person who sells a publication found by the jury to be obscene is presumed to know the obscene character of the work.", "start": 111.079, "stop": 129.317, "duration": 18.24}, {"text": "Now the evidence against Mr. Austin is very simple.", "start": 129.317, "stop": 136.254, "duration": 6.94}, {"text": "Mr. Austin stipulated that he was the owner and operator of the bookstore.", "start": 136.254, "stop": 143.227, "duration": 6.97}, {"text": "Mrs. Wolfen testified that she had called up a friend of hers and said, “I'm going to make a buy at Read More come on down and be witness.”", "start": 143.227, "stop": 152.333, "duration": 9.11}, {"text": "And she made a buy. She stated that the magazines were in a rack behind the cash register and she's testified that they were in this rack behind the cash register because a ministerial association had asked Mr. Austin to take them out of reach of minors.", "start": 152.333, "stop": 176.762, "duration": 24.43}, {"text": "And so, Mr. Austin to accommodate himself to this request took them and put them behind the cash register, where only a person who ordered the magazines by title could get them and where no minors could get.", "start": 176.762, "stop": 193.724, "duration": 16.96}, {"text": "The only other evidence in the case is the testimony of Reverend Simpson, a member of the Citizens for Decent Literature and the head of the Moral and Social Welfare Committee of the Paducah Ministerial Association.", "start": 193.724, "stop": 211.533, "duration": 17.81}, {"text": "He testified that he had asked Mr. Austin to come down to a meeting that the ministers had to discuss objectionable material.", "start": 211.533, "stop": 227.292, "duration": 15.76}, {"text": "At that time Mr. Austin told the ministers, that if they had any specific publications they thought were obscene to tell him and he would remove them.", "start": 227.292, "stop": 241.381, "duration": 14.09}, {"text": "And the ministers in effect said, “Get rid of all of them.”", "start": 241.381, "stop": 244.135, "duration": 2.75}, {"text": "That's the sum in substance of what they say.", "start": 244.135, "stop": 248.892, "duration": 4.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the ministers want to get rid --", "start": 248.892, "stop": 250.299, "duration": 1.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Get them -- get rid of all.", "start": 250.299, "stop": 250.908, "duration": 0.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- of all the magazines?", "start": 250.908, "stop": 252.613, "duration": 1.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "No magazines are contained any nudes at least.", "start": 252.613, "stop": 255.788, "duration": 3.18}, {"text": "That was the short of it and that's what the state recognized in their argument, if Your Honor please.", "start": 255.788, "stop": 263.516, "duration": 7.73}, {"text": "In their final argument to the jury, they pointed out that in effect the ministers told them to get rid of Playboy now and forever.", "start": 263.516, "stop": 274.443, "duration": 10.93}, {"text": "Not just Playboy May but Playboy so that there won't be any doubt about it and the language is clear.", "start": 274.443, "stop": 281.649, "duration": 7.21}, {"text": "This is the argument of the prosecutor to the jury.", "start": 281.649, "stop": 287.337, "duration": 5.69}, {"text": "They're talking about Mrs.Wolfen as the censor.", "start": 287.337, "stop": 289.383, "duration": 2.05}, {"text": "I'm talking on page 86 of the record.", "start": 289.383, "stop": 294.102, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "In the first place, I don't hold Mrs. Catherine Wolfen out as the censor of McCracken County. She is not.", "start": 294.102, "stop": 300.36, "duration": 6.26}, {"text": "Neither of the ministers the censors of the McCracken County and they have got no obligation to any person to go out and censor the material as on the stands in Paducah.", "start": 300.36, "stop": 309.349, "duration": 8.99}, {"text": "They recognized that fact.", "start": 309.349, "stop": 310.65, "duration": 1.3}, {"text": "That's a dangerous situation but what did they do?", "start": 310.65, "stop": 313.53, "duration": 2.88}, {"text": "They had a meeting, two meetings, as I recall the testimony.", "start": 313.53, "stop": 315.921, "duration": 2.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "With the prosecutor?", "start": 315.921, "stop": 316.922, "duration": 1}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "With the prosecutor.", "start": 316.922, "stop": 317.852, "duration": 0.93}, {"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 317.852, "stop": 319.024, "duration": 1.17}, {"text": "The last one in May of 1963, and the objection on the part of the ministers was all of the material that he called adult reading.", "start": 319.024, "stop": 327.716, "duration": 8.69}, {"text": "They objected to it, all of it.", "start": 327.716, "stop": 330.072, "duration": 2.36}, {"text": "There weren't going to specify this issue, that issue or some other issue.", "start": 330.072, "stop": 334.878, "duration": 4.81}, {"text": "They told him that they objected to all of it if they should, why if they have told him they object to the May issue of Playboy magazine.", "start": 334.878, "stop": 341.252, "duration": 6.37}, {"text": "All they would have to do is put on the June.", "start": 341.252, "stop": 344.013, "duration": 2.76}, {"text": "That's what we have.", "start": 344.013, "stop": 346.316, "duration": 2.3}, {"text": "This is the evidence and all of the evidence upon which petitioner was convicted.", "start": 346.316, "stop": 356.779, "duration": 10.46}, {"text": "Now at the trial, the petitioner sought to show that he had a good faith belief that the magazines were not obscene.", "start": 356.779, "stop": 369.228, "duration": 12.45}, {"text": "He tried to show it in a variety of ways.", "start": 369.228, "stop": 372.33, "duration": 3.1}, {"text": "First, he tried to show that he tried to limit himself only to those magazines which had second class mailing privileges from the Post Office Department.", "start": 372.33, "stop": 385.031, "duration": 12.7}, {"text": "A magazine that has second class mailing privileges is presumed to be not obscene because the Post Office Department has no right to issue second class mailing privileges to obscene publications.", "start": 385.031, "stop": 397.404, "duration": 12.37}, {"text": "He tried to show that he couldn't possibly read the 11 or 12,000 magazines that were in his store at all times.", "start": 397.404, "stop": 406.33, "duration": 8.93}, {"text": "He tried to show that for years he had been distributing exactly the same type of magazine over a four-state area, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri and Illinois.", "start": 406.33, "stop": 420.433, "duration": 14.1}, {"text": "He tried to show that this Court had found nudist magazines far more revealing than the two magazines involved.", "start": 420.433, "stop": 428.357, "duration": 7.92}, {"text": "But this Court have them to be not obscene and he tried to show that in the Paducah Library, there were books containing portrayals of nudes which were in every respect as frank and as candid as those in the magazines involved here.", "start": 428.357, "stop": 446.811, "duration": 18.45}, {"text": "All of these were totally excluded by the trial court and consistent with the rulings or with these rulings of the trial court.", "start": 446.811, "stop": 455.242, "duration": 8.43}, {"text": "The judge refused to give an instruction requested by the petitioner that if the jury found that he had a good faith belief that the magazines were not obscene, the jury should acquit.", "start": 455.242, "stop": 471.833, "duration": 16.59}, {"text": "It's indicated the jury found the defendant guilty and the Court of Appeals refused to grant a motion to appeal with the Chief Justice dissenting.", "start": 471.833, "stop": 487.273, "duration": 15.44}, {"text": "So the first question we have here is the one left open in Smith against California is a good faith belief on the part of the petitioner that the books he handles himself are not obscene, a defense to a obscenity prosecution.", "start": 487.273, "stop": 517.626, "duration": 30.35}, {"text": "Now, we touch -- it was touch upon in the last page but it does repetition, that there are two important considerations involved in the Smith rule.", "start": 517.626, "stop": 530.054, "duration": 12.43}, {"text": "The first one is that obscenity is defined by this Court is extraordinarily vague.", "start": 530.054, "stop": 540.185, "duration": 10.13}, {"text": "And if a bookseller faced with a very vague law can be held criminally liable when he believes that the publication is in all respect lawful.", "start": 540.185, "stop": 555.874, "duration": 15.69}, {"text": "He either goes out of the business or he goes into a business where the risk is higher than in any other lawful business.", "start": 555.874, "stop": 567.16, "duration": 11.29}, {"text": "And we're talking about bookstores where ordinarily we want to give maximum and not minimum protection.", "start": 567.16, "stop": 578.904, "duration": 11.74}, {"text": "The other alternative to going out of the business is to handle only cook books and even those aren't so safe because there are so aphrodisiac books on eating.", "start": 578.904, "stop": 596.759, "duration": 17.86}, {"text": "Now, the respondent here advances three reasons for denying to the petitioner the right to defend on the ground that he had a good faith belief that the magazines in questions were not obscene and in justifying the trial court's refusal to grant the requested instruction.", "start": 596.759, "stop": 629.667, "duration": 32.91}, {"text": "First of all, the respondent says that the evidence against petitioner is so conclusive, so overwhelming that nobody knowing the facts that petitioner knew could have -- could have a good faith belief that they were not obscene.", "start": 629.667, "stop": 654.788, "duration": 25.12}, {"text": "Now what is this overwhelming evidence?", "start": 654.788, "stop": 658.005, "duration": 3.22}, {"text": "The overwhelming evidence is that the petitioner may have no one that he had in his store magazines which contain portrayals of nudes, that's all and this in the face of untold holdings by this Court and other courts that nudity is not synonymous with obscenity.", "start": 658.005, "stop": 694.601, "duration": 36.6}, {"text": "The second reason given by the respondent is that petitioner couldn't ask and expect to get the instruction on good faith belief because he said, he never read the books, the magazines in the first instance and so, the respondent argues.", "start": 694.601, "stop": 716.931, "duration": 22.33}, {"text": "How can he have a good faith belief that the magazines are not obscene without looking at them?", "start": 716.931, "stop": 724.903, "duration": 7.97}, {"text": "Respondent argues that before a petitioner, before a bookseller may claim the right to a good -- to the defense of good faith belief that the material is not obscene.", "start": 724.903, "stop": 735.813, "duration": 10.91}, {"text": "He will have to take the stand and in effect incriminate himself.", "start": 735.813, "stop": 740.369, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "That is to say the prosecutor wants him to get him on the stand and say, “I read the book so magazines.”", "start": 740.369, "stop": 747.539, "duration": 7.17}, {"text": "And then from that they'll say uh-huh, he read the books and magazines and that's proof enough.", "start": 747.539, "stop": 761.481, "duration": 13.94}, {"text": "And then the prosecutor respondent finally says that the instruction shouldn't have been given because of Rosen against United States.", "start": 761.481, "stop": 773.425, "duration": 11.94}, {"text": "And that Rosen against United States indeed means that the good faith belief on the part of the bookseller that the material he sells is not obscene is irrelevant.", "start": 773.425, "stop": 789.557, "duration": 16.13}, {"text": "With all due respect, we suggest that the Rosen case should not be controlling here.", "start": 789.557, "stop": 799.731, "duration": 10.17}, {"text": "First of all, Rosen was decided, it's almost 70 years now, at that time when there were no First Amendment considerations involved or implicated.", "start": 799.731, "stop": 813.22, "duration": 13.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's a federal case.", "start": 813.22, "stop": 814.173, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was a federal case, Your Honor.", "start": 814.173, "stop": 815.396, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "Yes.", "start": 815.396, "stop": 816.043, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do you say that there was (Inaudible)?", "start": 816.043, "stop": 819.887, "duration": 3.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, none were raised and none were discussed.", "start": 819.887, "stop": 821.987, "duration": 2.1}, {"text": "The entire case was treated as if the First Amendment had no application.", "start": 821.987, "stop": 828.619, "duration": 6.63}, {"text": "I think it might have been argued and discussed in a different fashion but as it was handled.", "start": 828.619, "stop": 833.843, "duration": 5.22}, {"text": "It was no First Amendment considerations were brought to play nor considered in the case.", "start": 833.843, "stop": 841.569, "duration": 7.73}, {"text": "Secondly, Rosen of course was decided the time when Hicklin controls.", "start": 841.569, "stop": 849.331, "duration": 7.76}, {"text": "Now, a determination of obscenity under Hicklin is quite different from a determination of obscenity under Roth, Alberts as expanded by the various cases of this Court.", "start": 849.331, "stop": 861.426, "duration": 12.1}, {"text": "Under Hicklin everything was intuitive.", "start": 861.426, "stop": 864.643, "duration": 3.22}, {"text": "There were no outside considerations if person look at something that he didn't like it or he thought it might offend the most susceptible person that was it.", "start": 864.643, "stop": 878.765, "duration": 14.12}, {"text": "And the fact is that at the present time it is simply irrational to assume or as previously been discussed that a person who reads the book or reads the magazine knows merely from the reading that the publication offends the obscenity law.", "start": 878.765, "stop": 901.451, "duration": 22.69}, {"text": "That is to say that from reading it one would know that it goes beyond customary limits of candor, appeals to prurient interest, and is utterly without redeeming social importance.", "start": 901.451, "stop": 912.684, "duration": 11.23}, {"text": "Mr. Justice Stewart pointed out earlier, if members of this Court have good faith and honest disagreement among their selves with regard to whether a particular book is or is not obscene.", "start": 912.684, "stop": 927.515, "duration": 14.83}, {"text": "Surely that in itself proves that there is room at least for honest difference of opinion with regard to persons who look at the material and reach contrary completions.", "start": 927.515, "stop": 950.221, "duration": 22.71}, {"text": "As indicated, the Kentucky revised statutes provides in 43600 subdivision 4 that the sale of a publication found by a jury to be obscene is presumed to that the seller is presumed to know that it was obscene.", "start": 950.221, "stop": 975.059, "duration": 24.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 975.059, "stop": 980.93, "duration": 5.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Statute?", "start": 980.93, "stop": 981.936, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 981.936, "stop": 983.057, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thats the mere sale, the mere sale without knowing the contents of the publication that is to say in this case, merely because the two magazines were sold that brought the presumption into being and under the statute.", "start": 983.057, "stop": 1001.425, "duration": 18.37}, {"text": "He was presumed to know of the obscene character of the work.", "start": 1001.425, "stop": 1006.161, "duration": 4.74}, {"text": "Now in the face of this presumption, the petitioner sought to adduce evidence to negate it.", "start": 1006.161, "stop": 1014.488, "duration": 8.33}, {"text": "He certainly was putting on evidence which was relevant to his good faith.", "start": 1014.488, "stop": 1020.72, "duration": 6.23}, {"text": "It is, Justice Harlan, indicated in the Smith case, a defendant has the right to put on evidence showing that a work doesn't go beyond customary limits of candor on the issue of obscenity.", "start": 1020.72, "stop": 1036.131, "duration": 15.41}, {"text": "Then he has a light right, we respectfully submit to put on evidence to show that the hidden belief the material is obscene which is what he sought to do in all of which was totally excluded so that on that constitutional issue of scienter.", "start": 1036.131, "stop": 1056.751, "duration": 20.62}, {"text": "There was a totally exclusion of evidence.", "start": 1056.751, "stop": 1061.149, "duration": 4.4}, {"text": "I should point out as we have in our reply brief that after the case here and effective June of this year, Kentucky repealed the statute and amended and enacted a new law and specifically found or in these new statutes, specifically sets the standard as knowledge of obscenity.", "start": 1061.149, "stop": 1086.911, "duration": 25.76}, {"text": "That is to say under the law in Kentucky as it is exists today, a person who sells a publication found to be obscene must -- the prosecution must prove beyond the reasonable doubt that he had knowledge that the work was obscene and the statute as it now exists has eliminated the presumption which was working against the petitioner in the case at the time that he went to trial and at the time that he was convicted.", "start": 1086.911, "stop": 1119.953, "duration": 33.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, all this included evidence on the (Inaudible)?", "start": 1119.953, "stop": 1126.937, "duration": 6.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think not, Your Honor.", "start": 1126.937, "stop": 1127.8, "duration": 0.86}, {"text": "I believe that the excluded evidence was offered on both issues because for the most thought it bore on both the issue of whether the publications were obscene and also bore on whether he had a good faith belief that it was not obscene.", "start": 1127.8, "stop": 1141.944, "duration": 14.14}, {"text": "There was some evidence however which would have been directed solely at his good faith belief that it was not obscene.", "start": 1141.944, "stop": 1148.946, "duration": 7}, {"text": "That was the evidence where he sought to show that he could not possibly have examined the 11,000 or 12,000 publications that he had in his bookstore at all time.", "start": 1148.946, "stop": 1160.771, "duration": 11.83}, {"text": "That was excluded and I assume that was directed solely to the question of scienter.", "start": 1160.771, "stop": 1166.958, "duration": 6.19}, {"text": "But the other evidence, the broad sale of Playboy magazine, Rouge magazine, and others which the petitioner said were all about the same as the two magazines involved his evidence with regard to the second class mailing privileges enjoyed by these magazines would have gone to both of the issues.", "start": 1166.958, "stop": 1188.326, "duration": 21.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, what sentence did this man get from that?", "start": 1188.326, "stop": 1190.401, "duration": 2.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "He received a sentence of $250.00.", "start": 1190.401, "stop": 1194.487, "duration": 4.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "No jail sentence?", "start": 1194.487, "stop": 1195.904, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "There was no jail sentence in this case, Your Honor.", "start": 1195.904, "stop": 1201.35, "duration": 5.45}, {"text": "Now, there is -- I think a consideration here that Your Honors ought to give weight to.", "start": 1201.35, "stop": 1213.182, "duration": 11.83}, {"text": "In the case of Bantam Books against Sullivan, this Court was very anxious to see that a bookseller or a distributor not suppressed books when those who were operating were doing so outside of a judicial framework and not consistent with -- not consistent with legal standards.", "start": 1213.182, "stop": 1240.857, "duration": 27.67}, {"text": "And so it was that the Rhode Island Commission on Morality which was sending out notices not to distribute this or not to distribute that was found to be offending the Constitution and the effect of these notices was seen and recognized in the Court when the distributor in Rhode Island sees distributing each and every one of the books and magazines and there were 106 of them which the Rhode Island Commission condemned.", "start": 1240.857, "stop": 1269.067, "duration": 28.21}, {"text": "This Court was pointed out that in this fashion -- in this fashion much material which was constitutionally protected was being suppressed.", "start": 1269.067, "stop": 1279.95, "duration": 10.88}, {"text": "Now turning to this case --", "start": 1279.95, "stop": 1281.538, "duration": 1.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1281.538, "stop": 1283.654, "duration": 2.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Austin was faced with a problem.", "start": 1283.654, "stop": 1285.921, "duration": 2.27}, {"text": "There was a psychological warfare going on Paducah, Kentucky three years ago.", "start": 1285.921, "stop": 1291.444, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "Mrs. Wolfen was coming down to the bookstore and making purchases regularly, twice before this faithful day.", "start": 1291.444, "stop": 1298.353, "duration": 6.91}, {"text": "She had made other purchases of magazines, twice.", "start": 1298.353, "stop": 1303.19, "duration": 4.84}, {"text": "Mr. Austin was called before this ministerial association.", "start": 1303.19, "stop": 1306.858, "duration": 3.67}, {"text": "Now he had a choice to make. He either could say, I vow and I take everything out of my newsstand or he should say, as I understood this Court was encouraging distributors to say in the Bantam Books case, there shouldn't be suppression of material which is not obscene.", "start": 1306.858, "stop": 1328.395, "duration": 21.54}, {"text": "He made his judgment that these magazines were not obscene in law.", "start": 1328.395, "stop": 1333.998, "duration": 5.6}, {"text": "He tried as a businessman to accommodate himself to the pressures that were put.", "start": 1333.998, "stop": 1339.945, "duration": 5.95}, {"text": "But if he has denied the protection of the law under this circumstance and he can be branded a criminal because he didn't vow totally to the pressures that were put, then we will have more suppression, far more suppression than was have put Bantam Books against Sullivan.", "start": 1339.945, "stop": 1360.256, "duration": 20.31}, {"text": "And I will say that if Mr. Austin is a criminal for having had sold and he didn't do the selling, it was his clerk.", "start": 1360.256, "stop": 1368.919, "duration": 8.66}, {"text": "If he is a criminal because they were sold in his bookstore, these two magazines which are no different from any number of magazines which are circulating throughout the country today and continuously, then every bookseller and every wholesaler in the United States of America is today a criminal.", "start": 1368.919, "stop": 1395.536, "duration": 26.62}, {"text": "And I do not believe that the law can be such that we either disregard all this criminality or that we end up with the kind of suppression that is inherent in this conviction.", "start": 1395.536, "stop": 1410.398, "duration": 14.86}, {"text": "The only way, we respectfully submit, that the bookseller can have any confidence in carrying out his business in a lawful way is to receive the kind of legal protection that was promised in Smith and the promised has not been fulfilled.", "start": 1410.398, "stop": 1429.676, "duration": 19.28}, {"text": "At least in Smith, the thought was apart in around that a bookseller who had a good faith belief that what he was doing was lawful could not be made a criminal.", "start": 1429.676, "stop": 1444.261, "duration": 14.59}, {"text": "We are aware of course of the problems that are always pointed to in terms of, if the prosecution must prove beyond the reasonable doubt that the defendant knew that the work was obscene that there would not be many convictions.", "start": 1444.261, "stop": 1463.225, "duration": 18.96}, {"text": "Nor should that be.", "start": 1463.225, "stop": 1465.647, "duration": 2.42}, {"text": "The number of convictions that are coming out in the United States of America today for selling books is astounding.", "start": 1465.647, "stop": 1475.506, "duration": 9.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1475.506, "stop": 1478.406, "duration": 2.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have not collected them.", "start": 1478.406, "stop": 1479.535, "duration": 1.13}, {"text": "I have received however a report from the Citizens for Decent Literature that it seems to have collected them and they run into the many hundreds, many hundreds --", "start": 1479.535, "stop": 1492.36, "duration": 12.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Annually?", "start": 1492.36, "stop": 1492.714, "duration": 0.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Annually.", "start": 1492.714, "stop": 1494.354, "duration": 1.64}, {"text": "Yes.", "start": 1494.354, "stop": 1494.764, "duration": 0.41}, {"text": "Its fright -- it's really frightening what is going on with regard to these new standards that have been coming out in this field of obscenity.", "start": 1494.764, "stop": 1505.017, "duration": 10.25}, {"text": "But the problem is not really even to have to tolerate material with society has a legitimate right to suppress.", "start": 1505.017, "stop": 1513.863, "duration": 8.85}, {"text": "There are other weapons available.", "start": 1513.863, "stop": 1518.085, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "We are familiar with the fact that there are in rem proceedings where material which is thought to be obscene can be suppress without criminalizing an innocent man for selling it.", "start": 1518.085, "stop": 1529.83, "duration": 11.74}, {"text": "And while this is a great evil to have this kind of prior restraint as Mr. Justice Black indicated in the Ginzburg case, it's less of an evil than sending man to jail for 25 years or 10 years or 5 years.", "start": 1529.83, "stop": 1543.215, "duration": 13.38}, {"text": "I reserve the rest of my time Your Honor.", "start": 1543.215, "stop": 1544.728, "duration": 1.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you want to say --", "start": 1544.728, "stop": 1545.844, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1545.844, "stop": 1547.748, "duration": 1.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do you feel that (Inaudible)?", "start": 1547.748, "stop": 1558.848, "duration": 11.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Under the limited --", "start": 1558.848, "stop": 1559.376, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1559.376, "stop": 1564.32, "duration": 4.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Under the limited grant of certiorari, I think we have to assume that it's obscene, although, I'll tell you quite frankly that they are not obscene the magazines.", "start": 1564.32, "stop": 1570.864, "duration": 6.54}, {"text": "They are simply are not but --", "start": 1570.864, "stop": 1573.02, "duration": 2.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose that (Inaudible) do you think whether if he tries to (Inaudible)?", "start": 1573.02, "stop": 1584.232, "duration": 11.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "It has a bearing of course, I believe that there are some materials which would be so very powerful that he denied by a person who read it that he thought it was not obscene would not be given great way.", "start": 1584.232, "stop": 1595.962, "duration": 11.73}, {"text": "On the contrary, --", "start": 1595.962, "stop": 1596.224, "duration": 0.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1596.224, "stop": 1598.315, "duration": 2.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "You take a Playboy Magazine and if he says, I really think Playboy is not obscene.", "start": 1598.315, "stop": 1602.199, "duration": 3.88}, {"text": "I've been fine to think that we'd all agree with him at the --", "start": 1602.199, "stop": 1604.992, "duration": 2.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1604.992, "stop": 1611.364, "duration": 6.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "In this case, I don't believe so.", "start": 1611.364, "stop": 1612.678, "duration": 1.31}, {"text": "I think that there are answers sufficient in our case but in any case surely to go the scienter.", "start": 1612.678, "stop": 1618.282, "duration": 5.6}, {"text": "You have to know what's involved.", "start": 1618.282, "stop": 1619.997, "duration": 1.72}, {"text": "I think our case because we really raise questions of instructions for the most part.", "start": 1619.997, "stop": 1625.538, "duration": 5.54}, {"text": "We're in a position to get a ruling to here because what if we have ask for an instruction of the Court saying that, if you find that the defendant had a good faith belief that it was not was obscene then acquit.", "start": 1625.538, "stop": 1637.149, "duration": 11.61}, {"text": "We believe we're entitled to that instruction in any case no matter how rough the material may be, the defendant should always have that instruction.", "start": 1637.149, "stop": 1644.413, "duration": 7.26}, {"text": "The jury may not think much of his defense but he ought to be -- have that defense available to him.", "start": 1644.413, "stop": 1651.85, "duration": 7.44}, {"text": "I reserve the rest of time, Your Honor.", "start": 1651.85, "stop": 1654.309, "duration": 2.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Browning.", "start": 1654.309, "stop": 1656.49, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.", "start": 1656.49, "stop": 1661.158, "duration": 4.67}, {"text": "The Kentucky statute prohibiting the sale of obscene literature as an old one originally acted -- enacted in its present form in 1894.", "start": 1661.158, "stop": 1672.745, "duration": 11.59}, {"text": "But without any express requirement of scienter until the year 1962 which time the Kentucky legislature amended it to specifically require proof that the defendant had knowledge of the contents or character of the material which he sold.", "start": 1672.745, "stop": 1690.94, "duration": 18.2}, {"text": "That Kentucky statute with the scienter requirement placed in it in 1962 has been construed by the Kentucky courts and the authoritative construction placed on it by the Kentucky courts must be considered to be the instructions given to the jury by the McCracken Circuit Court.", "start": 1690.94, "stop": 1714.927, "duration": 23.99}, {"text": "Sends on appeal to the Kentucky Court of Appeals, the conviction of petitioner was affirmed and there was no opinion.", "start": 1714.927, "stop": 1723.673, "duration": 8.75}, {"text": "There are highest appellate courts simply stating that, we find no error in the case.", "start": 1723.673, "stop": 1729.938, "duration": 6.27}, {"text": "Therefore, if we are concerned with instruction given the Kentucky statute by the Court of Kentucky, we must go to the principle instruction given to the jury and the McCracken Circuit Court.", "start": 1729.938, "stop": 1743.498, "duration": 13.56}, {"text": "Now, that principle instruction, number one, is that the jury must believe from the evidence in this case beyond the reasonable doubt that the defendant as the owner and an operator of Read More newsstand did on the 28th day of September 1963.", "start": 1743.498, "stop": 1763.944, "duration": 20.45}, {"text": "At said place of business knowingly have for sale these two magazines and further that the defendant had knowledge of the contents and the character of the magazines.", "start": 1763.944, "stop": 1777.31, "duration": 13.37}, {"text": "I submit to you that this statute in Kentucky as construed by the Kentucky courts and this principle instruction to the jury below required first that it be found by the jury from the evidence beyond a reasonable doubt that the defendant knew the magazines, these two magazines were for sale at his store.", "start": 1777.31, "stop": 1796.29, "duration": 18.98}, {"text": "And secondly, that he knew the contents of the magazines.", "start": 1796.29, "stop": 1800.11, "duration": 3.82}, {"text": "And thirdly, that he knew the character in the magazine.", "start": 1800.11, "stop": 1802.763, "duration": 2.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was said, contents or character?", "start": 1802.763, "stop": 1806.344, "duration": 3.58}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. -- but for Mr. Justice Stewart, the statute provides that it is required to be proved that he had knowledge of the contents or character.", "start": 1806.344, "stop": 1816.278, "duration": 9.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1816.278, "stop": 1816.667, "duration": 0.39}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I am speaking of the construction authoritatively placed on a Kentucky statute by the Kentucky courts.", "start": 1816.667, "stop": 1822.217, "duration": 5.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "But where are you in the record?", "start": 1822.217, "stop": 1823.846, "duration": 1.63}, {"text": "Where is this page?", "start": 1823.846, "stop": 1824.045, "duration": 0.2}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I am on page 109 in the record and I am referring to the principle instruction given to the jury in the McCracken Circuit Court.", "start": 1824.045, "stop": 1832.017, "duration": 7.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was there an instruction given to the jury on presumption that was in the Kentucky --", "start": 1832.017, "stop": 1836.651, "duration": 4.63}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "There was none whatsoever.", "start": 1836.651, "stop": 1838.783, "duration": 2.13}, {"text": "In this entire record, there is not one reference of any sort to a statutory presumption it was never used, it was never involved in this case.", "start": 1838.783, "stop": 1847.89, "duration": 9.11}, {"text": "The jury was not instructed concerning any presumption, counsel did not say a word about it in the argument of the jury.", "start": 1847.89, "stop": 1856.026, "duration": 8.14}, {"text": "It is not brought out or mentioned anywhere in this record.", "start": 1856.026, "stop": 1859.537, "duration": 3.51}, {"text": "All that you can say is that you have in the statute.", "start": 1859.537, "stop": 1862.652, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "It was not involved, construed or applied in this case.", "start": 1862.652, "stop": 1866.816, "duration": 4.16}, {"text": "And I submit while we are on that point and under the authority of United States versus Raines.", "start": 1866.816, "stop": 1871.751, "duration": 4.93}, {"text": "This Court cannot consider the constitutionality of the statute in a vacuum where it has not application to the case at hand.", "start": 1871.751, "stop": 1881.635, "duration": 9.88}, {"text": "Mr. Justice Stewart have you found the instruction --", "start": 1881.635, "stop": 1884.204, "duration": 2.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have.", "start": 1884.204, "stop": 1884.512, "duration": 0.31}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- which i refer.", "start": 1884.512, "stop": 1886.225, "duration": 1.71}, {"text": "You will note --", "start": 1886.225, "stop": 1886.405, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "The contents and the character of said magazines.", "start": 1886.405, "stop": 1889.128, "duration": 2.72}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 1889.128, "stop": 1889.686, "duration": 0.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now what do you suppose the -- what do you understand by the meaning of character?", "start": 1889.686, "stop": 1894.159, "duration": 4.47}, {"text": "It's something different from contents of?", "start": 1894.159, "stop": 1896.85, "duration": 2.69}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understood character for mean the obscene character of the material.", "start": 1896.85, "stop": 1900.634, "duration": 3.78}, {"text": "This is my understanding.", "start": 1900.634, "stop": 1902.823, "duration": 2.19}, {"text": "I was under the impression that this Court previously had required only knowledge of the contents, if this was sufficient on scienter.", "start": 1902.823, "stop": 1910.486, "duration": 7.66}, {"text": "If according to Michigan, I am mistaken in that conclusion that my personal conclusion.", "start": 1910.486, "stop": 1916.011, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "I am arguing here or not what I conceive the Court is free these opinions to be.", "start": 1916.011, "stop": 1920.581, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "But what the lower court in this case actually gave which was more than I thought it was necessary.", "start": 1920.581, "stop": 1925.378, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "Namely, that they must find that he knew the magazine where at his store that he knew the contents and further, thirdly that he knew the character of the magazines.", "start": 1925.378, "stop": 1936.807, "duration": 11.43}, {"text": "I construe character, personally to mean knowledge of the obscene character.", "start": 1936.807, "stop": 1942.582, "duration": 5.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "That part it didn't --", "start": 1942.582, "stop": 1942.747, "duration": 0.16}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "But what --", "start": 1942.747, "stop": 1943.493, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- it doesn't say that, does it?", "start": 1943.493, "stop": 1945.331, "duration": 1.84}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "It does not.", "start": 1945.331, "stop": 1946.051, "duration": 0.72}, {"text": "But I was asked the question, what do I didn't think about it?", "start": 1946.051, "stop": 1948.554, "duration": 2.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, as compared with what follows in the instruction.", "start": 1948.554, "stop": 1953.973, "duration": 5.42}, {"text": "I didn't say the jury might have found -- might have thought that Mr. Austin thought that these were purely magazines and that so far would be a defined as to character of the magazines.", "start": 1953.973, "stop": 1971.517, "duration": 17.54}, {"text": "But that's quite different from the instructions with the effects of the theory of the jury itself.", "start": 1971.517, "stop": 1978.76, "duration": 7.24}, {"text": "Because the jury itself in the next succeeding phrase was defining that the magazines or either of them are obscene and of an indecent character.", "start": 1978.76, "stop": 1992.458, "duration": 13.7}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Of an obscene or indecent character?", "start": 1992.458, "stop": 1994.528, "duration": 2.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's the jury which the jury defined.", "start": 1994.528, "stop": 1998.514, "duration": 3.99}, {"text": "The jury --", "start": 1998.514, "stop": 1999.66, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1999.66, "stop": 2000.15, "duration": 0.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- has that to ask what then follow if they so understood the instruction to -- for them to ascertain from the knowledge of the character of magazine?", "start": 2000.15, "stop": 2016.073, "duration": 15.92}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I would still say that it looks like it could be the obscene or indecent character.", "start": 2016.073, "stop": 2020.06, "duration": 3.99}, {"text": "Perhaps, I simply don't understand the question.", "start": 2020.06, "stop": 2023.24, "duration": 3.18}, {"text": "I'm pointing out the instruction here as the authoritative construction given the Kentucky statute by the Kentucky courts and I believe, I'm arguing that this construction meant with the Kentucky statute satisfied Smith versus California and that it required all of these points on the issue of scienter.", "start": 2023.24, "stop": 2040.997, "duration": 17.76}, {"text": "I will proceed then to argue that the Commonwealth's evidence in chief made this case and authorize submission of this to the jury.", "start": 2040.997, "stop": 2049.118, "duration": 8.12}, {"text": "And it was certainly not submitted on any statutory presumption but the Commonwealth's evidence in chief made the cases as far as scienter was concerned.", "start": 2049.118, "stop": 2058.395, "duration": 9.28}, {"text": "It was shown that just a few months prior to the particular sale in question.", "start": 2058.395, "stop": 2063.436, "duration": 5.04}, {"text": "The petitioner met with several ministers representing the Committee on Moral and Social Welfare of the Paducah Ministerial Association.", "start": 2063.436, "stop": 2071.411, "duration": 7.97}, {"text": "They talked to him about obscenity in general and in particular about this particular class of magazines known as girlie magazines.", "start": 2071.411, "stop": 2078.516, "duration": 7.11}, {"text": "They made known to him specifically complains which the ministers had been receiving from the public in general concerning the sale of these magazines.", "start": 2078.516, "stop": 2086.897, "duration": 8.38}, {"text": "And they discussed their obscene content in general with him.", "start": 2086.897, "stop": 2090.949, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "As a consequence of this, he went back to his store and personally collected and segregated 25 to 30 titles of girlie magazines and put him on the rack behind the cashier's counter and he stapled them to prevent them from being leak through.", "start": 2090.949, "stop": 2106.359, "duration": 15.41}, {"text": "He put them back there expressly because he considered them to be adult reading only and he knew thereby that they had a prurient interest appeal.", "start": 2106.359, "stop": 2116.712, "duration": 10.35}, {"text": "This was sufficient to show that he knew or should have known the contents of the magazine.", "start": 2116.712, "stop": 2122.497, "duration": 5.78}, {"text": "Now what about this so-called defense of honest belief that there were not obscene?", "start": 2122.497, "stop": 2127.536, "duration": 5.04}, {"text": "We contend that that defense was actually was not raised in this case.", "start": 2127.536, "stop": 2131.244, "duration": 3.71}, {"text": "He was not entitled to any instructions.", "start": 2131.244, "stop": 2133.575, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "I refer the Court concerning Kentucky procedure on instructing juries in criminal cases to Stanley's authoritative three-volume work on Kentucky instructions to juries' volume 3 Section 771 pages 15 through 18.", "start": 2133.575, "stop": 2148.981, "duration": 15.41}, {"text": "The subject to that Section is special affirmative defenses.", "start": 2148.981, "stop": 2152.504, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "Now, I have stated there that it is a matter of Kentucky law if the negative of the principle instructions to the jury sufficiently covers what the defendant is raising then he is not entitled to a separate instruction.", "start": 2152.504, "stop": 2163.515, "duration": 11.01}, {"text": "The time when he is entitled to an affirmative special defense is when he pleads at -- he pleads by nature of confessions and avoidance.", "start": 2163.515, "stop": 2173.249, "duration": 9.73}, {"text": "In other words he says, I will admit to the many of the things that you charge with me but I will avoid the application of the penalty on a separate defense which I am raising here.", "start": 2173.249, "stop": 2182.719, "duration": 9.47}, {"text": "This was not a confession and avoidance case.", "start": 2182.719, "stop": 2185.46, "duration": 2.74}, {"text": "The defendant here did not testify that of course I knew these magazines were there.", "start": 2185.46, "stop": 2190.087, "duration": 4.63}, {"text": "I -- I was familiar with them but I did not believe that they were obscene.", "start": 2190.087, "stop": 2193.957, "duration": 3.87}, {"text": "He testified that as to one magazine he had no knowledge of the existence of such a publication.", "start": 2193.957, "stop": 2200.08, "duration": 6.12}, {"text": "He never heard of it, never knew of it.", "start": 2200.08, "stop": 2201.862, "duration": 1.78}, {"text": "How can a person in that situation say that I never knew of the existence of it and yet, I have formed a reasonable belief that it was not obscene?", "start": 2201.862, "stop": 2209.521, "duration": 7.66}, {"text": "He could not have, he did not say so.", "start": 2209.521, "stop": 2212.217, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "At no time during his trial that he say that he had formed a reasonable belief that they were not obscene.", "start": 2212.217, "stop": 2218.09, "duration": 5.87}, {"text": "His counsel in arguing the case for the jury, there we should find the counsel harping away on the idea that this man reasonably believe and had a good faith believe that -- belief that these magazines were not obscene.", "start": 2218.09, "stop": 2230.329, "duration": 12.24}, {"text": "Counsel said only on page 82 of the record.", "start": 2230.329, "stop": 2234.785, "duration": 4.46}, {"text": "He said only this, “here isn't a word of proof in this case.”", "start": 2234.785, "stop": 2237.921, "duration": 3.14}, {"text": "Mr. Austin knew that these two magazines were down there.", "start": 2237.921, "stop": 2241.743, "duration": 3.82}, {"text": "So let -- let's face it, what was his defense in this case.", "start": 2241.743, "stop": 2244.901, "duration": 3.16}, {"text": "Simply that he did not know the magazines were there.", "start": 2244.901, "stop": 2248.112, "duration": 3.21}, {"text": "There with it --", "start": 2248.112, "stop": 2248.297, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Its pretty clear that the instructions to the jury were erroneous, isn't it?", "start": 2248.297, "stop": 2252.319, "duration": 4.02}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2252.319, "stop": 2252.668, "duration": 0.35}, {"text": "I -- I don't agree with that.", "start": 2252.668, "stop": 2253.681, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, he doesn't say a word about the necessity of a material being not only without regaining social importance.", "start": 2253.681, "stop": 2260.982, "duration": 7.3}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I think that the concept of -- in the concept of obscenity it is implicit that the material is without regaining social importance.", "start": 2260.982, "stop": 2269.239, "duration": 8.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or it doesn't say a word about that with the jury, does it, as a necessity of what the jury has to find in order to find the people?", "start": 2269.239, "stop": 2275.951, "duration": 6.71}, {"text": "The jury was obscene --", "start": 2275.951, "stop": 2279.514, "duration": 3.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2279.514, "stop": 2285.28, "duration": 5.77}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "This is my understanding --", "start": 2285.28, "stop": 2286.196, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I'm just asking about it.", "start": 2286.196, "stop": 2287.467, "duration": 1.27}, {"text": "Isn't it very clear that the instructions to the jury are erroneous?", "start": 2287.467, "stop": 2290.458, "duration": 2.99}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I certainly don't concede that they are erroneous.", "start": 2290.458, "stop": 2292.368, "duration": 1.91}, {"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2292.368, "stop": 2292.726, "duration": 0.36}, {"text": "I believe to find --", "start": 2292.726, "stop": 2292.883, "duration": 0.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it did say a word about the -- is there a word about the necessity of the material being utterly lacking any redeeming social value?", "start": 2292.883, "stop": 2300.086, "duration": 7.2}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I cannot recall but I heard review of the instructions again that this is in --", "start": 2300.086, "stop": 2303.582, "duration": 3.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm going over very slowly and deliberately.", "start": 2303.582, "stop": 2305.409, "duration": 1.83}, {"text": "I can't find anything.", "start": 2305.409, "stop": 2306.621, "duration": 1.21}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Alright sir, I'll agree with you in it.", "start": 2306.621, "stop": 2308.133, "duration": 1.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "But not in instructions?", "start": 2308.133, "stop": 2308.458, "duration": 0.33}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "If not in the instructions.", "start": 2308.458, "stop": 2311.704, "duration": 3.25}, {"text": "But I don't concede that that makes the instructions totally erroneous.", "start": 2311.704, "stop": 2315.026, "duration": 3.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "But no, just erroneous.", "start": 2315.026, "stop": 2316.937, "duration": 1.91}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't concede that it makes the instructions erroneous, I disagree with you there.", "start": 2316.937, "stop": 2322.33, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "But I did not believe that certiorari being limited here embrace the questions of the propriety of instructions to the jury.", "start": 2322.33, "stop": 2330.699, "duration": 8.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "What's the -- is it constitutional question in constitutional case?", "start": 2330.699, "stop": 2337.117, "duration": 6.42}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the instructions in other facets here were sufficient to indicate that this material must be without redeeming self importance.", "start": 2337.117, "stop": 2345.59, "duration": 8.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "What?", "start": 2345.59, "stop": 2346.681, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Let's say the instructions taken in the whole imply that that if all these factors were believed to be true about the magazines they must be without reading themselves.", "start": 2346.681, "stop": 2354.312, "duration": 7.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "I know it's important.", "start": 2354.312, "stop": 2358.564, "duration": 4.25}, {"text": "I just can't find that here -- the only instructions that are on page 109 to 111?", "start": 2358.564, "stop": 2365.528, "duration": 6.96}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 2365.528, "stop": 2368.448, "duration": 2.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 2368.448, "stop": 2372.005, "duration": 3.56}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "The defense here, as I will take the trouble to repeat was certainly not that he has a reasonable belief the magazines were obscene.", "start": 2372.005, "stop": 2378.088, "duration": 6.08}, {"text": "The defense is very simply.", "start": 2378.088, "stop": 2379.186, "duration": 1.1}, {"text": "He did not know that they were there.", "start": 2379.186, "stop": 2381.183, "duration": 2}, {"text": "If we believe that it is perfectly true that he didn't know it and certainly should have known it.", "start": 2381.183, "stop": 2385.477, "duration": 4.29}, {"text": "The particular class of magazines were complained to him.", "start": 2385.477, "stop": 2388.102, "duration": 2.63}, {"text": "His attention was pointed out that to him.", "start": 2388.102, "stop": 2391.255, "duration": 3.15}, {"text": "His attention was called to them. He personally collected 25 or 30 of them he knew what it seems a category of girlie magazines whose sales should be limited to adult and he put them on this counter and rack behind the cashier's counter.", "start": 2391.255, "stop": 2407.346, "duration": 16.09}, {"text": "And if he says that he didn't know they were there.", "start": 2407.346, "stop": 2410.107, "duration": 2.76}, {"text": "He should have known.", "start": 2410.107, "stop": 2411.644, "duration": 1.54}, {"text": "There is no reason why it could not have taken the trouble to scan the small group magazines.", "start": 2411.644, "stop": 2417.387, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "To see for himself what was in them and to select from among them those which he thought could be sold and which cannot be sold.", "start": 2417.387, "stop": 2424.594, "duration": 7.21}, {"text": "Then --", "start": 2424.594, "stop": 2425.301, "duration": 0.71}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there any (Inaudible)?", "start": 2425.301, "stop": 2439.535, "duration": 14.23}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Justice Harlan, there is evidence of course that he was a wholesale news distributor and that he first got the books as a wholesaler and then that he distributed them to his Read More News retail stand.", "start": 2439.535, "stop": 2454.031, "duration": 14.5}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2454.031, "stop": 2455.936, "duration": 1.91}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right he supplied the books to himself in this case.", "start": 2455.936, "stop": 2462.773, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "And as far as being able to keep the books out of his retail stores since he was supplying the books to himself possibly could have done that.", "start": 2462.773, "stop": 2472.824, "duration": 10.05}, {"text": "He cannot have display them for retail sale.", "start": 2472.824, "stop": 2474.226, "duration": 1.4}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "How long the operation began?", "start": 2474.226, "stop": 2477.49, "duration": 3.26}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "He says that the in his Read More News Story, he handled approximately 11,000 titles a month, 4,000 paperback books paying there titles, 4,000 hardbound books, and 3,000 magazines.", "start": 2477.49, "stop": 2491.423, "duration": 13.93}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Never before in most cases (Inaudible)?", "start": 2491.423, "stop": 2495.277, "duration": 3.85}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "In his wholesale nude distributorship.", "start": 2495.277, "stop": 2497.838, "duration": 2.56}, {"text": "He had five different locations.", "start": 2497.838, "stop": 2500.022, "duration": 2.18}, {"text": "Here in the City of Paducah, he had only one retail new store and the magazines of course were purchased at this Paducah retail newsstand.", "start": 2500.022, "stop": 2509.466, "duration": 9.44}, {"text": "The magazines on which the prosecution was based.", "start": 2509.466, "stop": 2512.219, "duration": 2.75}, {"text": "I think he said at his Read More newsstand handle 11,000 titles each month.", "start": 2512.219, "stop": 2516.907, "duration": 4.69}, {"text": "This is an impressive figure and he says that it tried to say that as a conclusion which could not be called for at which humanly impossible for anybody to read what was in those 11,000 titles and we submit that he didn't have to read everything in his store.", "start": 2516.907, "stop": 2530.834, "duration": 13.93}, {"text": "All in the world he had to do was to take the trouble to scan briefly the 25 or so magazines that he himself had put behind the cash register.", "start": 2530.834, "stop": 2537.745, "duration": 6.91}, {"text": "We're not suggesting that he read 11,000 titles and it wasn't necessary to do so in this case.", "start": 2537.745, "stop": 2542.31, "duration": 4.57}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "The only reason that I asked the question, I wanted to just go and make that 11,000 titles a month, to have other location.", "start": 2542.31, "stop": 2550.508, "duration": 8.2}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think this is what his testimony was.", "start": 2550.508, "stop": 2552.479, "duration": 1.97}, {"text": "I thought myself with that was quite an excessive number but that appears in the record as his statement.", "start": 2552.479, "stop": 2561.439, "duration": 8.96}, {"text": "He was asked, “How many – tell how many volumes or how many different magazines in a month you have at Read More, this Read More stand you're state intact.", "start": 2561.439, "stop": 2570.074, "duration": 8.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2570.074, "stop": 2571.514, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I am reading from page 30.", "start": 2571.514, "stop": 2573.545, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "He was asked, “Tell us how many volumes or how many different magazines in one month you handle at Read More.", "start": 2573.545, "stop": 2579.942, "duration": 6.4}, {"text": "This is just at Read More stand.”", "start": 2579.942, "stop": 2582.31, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "Answer, “You're speaking of titles Mr. Williams?”", "start": 2582.31, "stop": 2584.363, "duration": 2.05}, {"text": "“Yes, sir.", "start": 2584.363, "stop": 2584.861, "duration": 0.5}, {"text": "Titles.”", "start": 2584.861, "stop": 2585.299, "duration": 0.44}, {"text": "Well, it buries, I would say there is 3,000 titles on sale at all time of magazines and approximately 4,000 titles of hard books, and 4,000 titles of paperback books in all about 11,000 I would say.", "start": 2585.299, "stop": 2601.68, "duration": 16.38}, {"text": "11,000 titles that is one Read More retail newsstand a month", "start": 2601.68, "stop": 2606.765, "duration": 5.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Read More -- (Inaudible)", "start": 2606.765, "stop": 2624.887, "duration": 18.12}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I will if I had time.", "start": 2624.887, "stop": 2626.528, "duration": 1.64}, {"text": "I see that I will do so.", "start": 2626.528, "stop": 2628.944, "duration": 2.42}, {"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2628.944, "stop": 2631.024, "duration": 2.08}, {"text": "He first tried to introduce these trial six Paperback books, Lady Chatterley's Lover and others.", "start": 2631.024, "stop": 2636.18, "duration": 5.16}, {"text": "These matters were not introduced at all to show scienter.", "start": 2636.18, "stop": 2640.57, "duration": 4.39}, {"text": "They were introduced as tending to show contemporary community standards.", "start": 2640.57, "stop": 2646.815, "duration": 6.24}, {"text": "The six Paperback books, he never testified that he had read these books or was even familiar with them in anyways.", "start": 2646.815, "stop": 2652.349, "duration": 5.53}, {"text": "So how could they have born on scienter?", "start": 2652.349, "stop": 2654.551, "duration": 2.2}, {"text": "He offer to introduce items from the Paducah Public Library taken from museum of modern art productions taken from a book on Greg Sculpture and taken from U.S. camera annual issue photographic magazine.", "start": 2654.551, "stop": 2668.162, "duration": 13.61}, {"text": "Once again, he did not testify that because these things showing nude form when a Paducah Public Library.", "start": 2668.162, "stop": 2674.651, "duration": 6.49}, {"text": "I reasonably believe that these two magazines were not appeal.", "start": 2674.651, "stop": 2678.109, "duration": 3.46}, {"text": "He didn't say that at all.", "start": 2678.109, "stop": 2679.191, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "They were introduced to show that the betrayal of the nude form could be found in books certainly regarded as acceptable in the Paducah Public Library, but it did not bear on scienter.", "start": 2679.191, "stop": 2689.731, "duration": 10.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, the other question is(Inaudible)?", "start": 2689.731, "stop": 2696.028, "duration": 6.3}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "On the question, whether the books are obscene or not?", "start": 2696.028, "stop": 2697.579, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did he offer -- do you offer (Inaudible)", "start": 2697.579, "stop": 2704.342, "duration": 6.76}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "It -- well I would say, I don't think he offered it on scienter at all.", "start": 2704.342, "stop": 2707.43, "duration": 3.09}, {"text": "I think it was offered entirely on the community -- contemporary community standards.", "start": 2707.43, "stop": 2711.949, "duration": 4.52}, {"text": "They were not comparable in material in any sense.", "start": 2711.949, "stop": 2715.454, "duration": 3.51}, {"text": "They were -- they were certainly far different from these magazines here.", "start": 2715.454, "stop": 2720.479, "duration": 5.02}, {"text": "They -- it should not have been offered an evidence.", "start": 2720.479, "stop": 2722.358, "duration": 1.88}, {"text": "It was irrelevant --", "start": 2722.358, "stop": 2722.558, "duration": 0.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "So it was not for the jury to determine?", "start": 2722.558, "stop": 2724.784, "duration": 2.23}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, it's for the judge to determine whether the evidence is admissible or not.", "start": 2724.784, "stop": 2728.124, "duration": 3.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's the whole point that would said that for which he was offering him for the jury to determine whether or not they were comparable.", "start": 2728.124, "stop": 2735.265, "duration": 7.14}, {"text": "Am I mistaken?", "start": 2735.265, "stop": 2736.739, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "The judge wouldn't let any evidence of being established at all.", "start": 2736.739, "stop": 2738.974, "duration": 2.24}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I'm just arguing that the judge was correct in his ruling because comparable materials should at least be similar in content and style and form to what is in issue.", "start": 2738.974, "stop": 2749.684, "duration": 10.71}, {"text": "We have two magazines on trial here.", "start": 2749.684, "stop": 2751.668, "duration": 1.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "This is where (Inaudible).", "start": 2751.668, "stop": 2754.599, "duration": 2.93}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it should not be admitted, I submit to this Court.", "start": 2754.599, "stop": 2757.572, "duration": 2.97}, {"text": "If it's not comparable in any sense in content or style or form to what's on trial.", "start": 2757.572, "stop": 2763.239, "duration": 5.67}, {"text": "Why bring in material that doesn't conform if not similar to what he is being prosecuted for and try to say, look here, the public biases been accepted.", "start": 2763.239, "stop": 2773.732, "duration": 10.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll recess now Mr. --", "start": 2773.732, "stop": 2775.467, "duration": 1.74}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - October 11, 1966", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren13/oral_argument_audio/23602", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Number 16, William L. Austin, petitioner versus Kentucky.", "start": 0, "stop": 12.744, "duration": 12.74}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Chief Justice --", "start": 12.744, "stop": 13.327, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Browning.", "start": 13.327, "stop": 14.974, "duration": 1.65}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- may it please the Court.", "start": 14.974, "stop": 18.605, "duration": 3.63}, {"text": "As I closed yesterday, I was touching upon a question asked by Mr. Justice Harlan concerning the exclusion of certain material offered at defendant's trial in McCracken Circuit Court in this case.", "start": 18.605, "stop": 37.628, "duration": 19.02}, {"text": "I was making the point that the exhibits, which were not permitted to be placed in evidence by the trial judge, were not similar to the two magazines Spree and High Heels upon which this prosecution was based.", "start": 37.628, "stop": 53.43, "duration": 15.8}, {"text": "There were first six paperback books.", "start": 53.43, "stop": 55.981, "duration": 2.55}, {"text": "They were recognized literary works although containing, of course, questionable passages.", "start": 55.981, "stop": 61.189, "duration": 5.21}, {"text": "One of them was Henry Miller's work Tropic of Capricorn.", "start": 61.189, "stop": 67.591, "duration": 6.4}, {"text": "These books are certainly not similar in any degree to the two girlie magazines for which Mr. Austin was being prosecuted.", "start": 67.591, "stop": 76.59, "duration": 9}, {"text": "They were literary works.", "start": 76.59, "stop": 77.682, "duration": 1.09}, {"text": "The girlie magazines have no literary value whatever.", "start": 77.682, "stop": 81.29, "duration": 3.61}, {"text": "They were entirely printed materials whereas the girlie magazines had most of their prurient interest appeal based on photographs of nude and semi-nude females.", "start": 81.29, "stop": 92.733, "duration": 11.44}, {"text": "As to the material and the public library, it cannot possibly be argued that because the nude form is accepted in the museum of modern art and in series of photographic issues and they invoked some great sculpture that we must therefore accept the same exposure of the nude female form in the girlie magazines in the style and format in which the form is displayed in those magazines.", "start": 92.733, "stop": 117.02, "duration": 24.29}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "But what evidence you're going to need in the trial court from evidence to community standards?", "start": 117.02, "stop": 123.33, "duration": 6.31}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Affirmatively, the evidence which was permitted to go to the jury was the testimony, I think it's Dr. Lowry, who was a professor of Murray State College.", "start": 123.33, "stop": 136.733, "duration": 13.4}, {"text": "He was put on the stand and he was permitted to answer terrible questions, one of which, Would you say that these magazines appeal to the prurient interest and he answered that no.", "start": 136.733, "stop": 150.016, "duration": 13.28}, {"text": "And he was asked if the magazines in his expert opinion were such as would create a morbid interest or prurient interest in nudity or sex in the average person and this was objected to but he was permitted to answer and he said, no, quite the contrary.", "start": 150.016, "stop": 170.544, "duration": 20.53}, {"text": "They would not stimulate prurient interest in anyone.", "start": 170.544, "stop": 174.866, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "It would not appeal to the average of normal adult.", "start": 174.866, "stop": 178.746, "duration": 3.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was his special qualification in the test?", "start": 178.746, "stop": 182.474, "duration": 3.73}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Dr. Lowry was Mr. Austin, the defendant's witness, and he qualified first by saying that he talked the social sciences and that he was acquainted with the community standards and he had kept up with --", "start": 182.474, "stop": 195.08, "duration": 12.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you talking about the standards in Paducah or the standards in the county in which Paducah was located?", "start": 195.08, "stop": 200.472, "duration": 5.39}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that in this case that we're concerned with today, actually, the standards were considered to be national.", "start": 200.472, "stop": 209.336, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "The trial court instructed the jury on a national standard.", "start": 209.336, "stop": 212.814, "duration": 3.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "On a national standard?", "start": 212.814, "stop": 214.365, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "This is what the trial court instructed the jury concerned.", "start": 214.365, "stop": 217.488, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "And what was this man's special expertise that made him qualified to say what effect he would have on an individual?", "start": 217.488, "stop": 225.621, "duration": 8.13}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I believe that he said that he was familiar with community standards and --", "start": 225.621, "stop": 232.856, "duration": 7.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "He was testifying what effect it would have on people?", "start": 232.856, "stop": 237.083, "duration": 4.23}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, he is the head of the Department of Social Science and a professor at Murray and -- well, one might certainly question whether he was properly qualified as an expert here but I'm saying that the Commonwealth, let this go in anyway.", "start": 237.083, "stop": 263.432, "duration": 26.35}, {"text": "In other words, he was permitted to testify and he was permitted to give evidence to the effect that the magazines, in his expert opinion, were not obscene.", "start": 263.432, "stop": 277.466, "duration": 14.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "It would not have any effect to arouse of prurient instinct?", "start": 277.466, "stop": 281.542, "duration": 4.08}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "So he said, he said, quite the contrary.", "start": 281.542, "stop": 285.535, "duration": 3.99}, {"text": "He was also --", "start": 285.535, "stop": 286.061, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) would not.", "start": 286.061, "stop": 287.523, "duration": 1.46}, {"text": "What was his special expertise on that story?", "start": 287.523, "stop": 291.406, "duration": 3.88}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I do not know at the moment.", "start": 291.406, "stop": 294.158, "duration": 2.75}, {"text": "He was the defendant's witness not ours.", "start": 294.158, "stop": 297.905, "duration": 3.75}, {"text": "And his only qualification evidently was that he have had a PH. degree and that he --", "start": 297.905, "stop": 306.781, "duration": 8.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "How old was he?", "start": 306.781, "stop": 311.296, "duration": 4.51}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I do not know well then.", "start": 311.296, "stop": 312.688, "duration": 1.39}, {"text": "Can you tell me, Mr. Fleishman?", "start": 312.688, "stop": 317.019, "duration": 4.33}, {"text": "I think that he had been a professor there at Murray for a great number of years, possibly 40 years which would put him about 60 years old.", "start": 317.019, "stop": 325.355, "duration": 8.34}, {"text": "If I might proceed with this, the expert was also asked if these magazines in any way exceeded or went beyond the customary limits of candor in the community.", "start": 325.355, "stop": 339.426, "duration": 14.07}, {"text": "He was permitted to answer this and he said, my answer to that would be no, they do not go as far as some as, thus far as some, which are generally accepted.", "start": 339.426, "stop": 351.697, "duration": 12.27}, {"text": "And this evidence went to the jury.", "start": 351.697, "stop": 354.98, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "The defendant himself on the stand --", "start": 354.98, "stop": 357.862, "duration": 2.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you know whether he was a paid expert or not?", "start": 357.862, "stop": 361.915, "duration": 4.05}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know whether he was compensated for this appearance or not.", "start": 361.915, "stop": 367.975, "duration": 6.06}, {"text": "But, I'm simply pointing out in answer to Mr. Justice Harlan's inquiry that there was affirmative evidence permitted to be introduced in this case to the effect that this magazines did not exceed community standards; that in the opinion of the so-called experts --", "start": 367.975, "stop": 384.325, "duration": 16.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You mean national community?", "start": 384.325, "stop": 387.178, "duration": 2.85}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir, that in the opinion of a so-called expert, they were not obscene, did not appeal to the prurient interest.", "start": 387.178, "stop": 396.437, "duration": 9.26}, {"text": "The defendant was permitted to testify that he had sold this same type of magazine for many years.", "start": 396.437, "stop": 404.069, "duration": 7.63}, {"text": "And he was then asked and there has never been an objection as far as the community is concerned.", "start": 404.069, "stop": 411.098, "duration": 7.03}, {"text": "Well, unfortunately, the defendant was not able to answer that categorically, no.", "start": 411.098, "stop": 416.389, "duration": 5.29}, {"text": "He said merely there has never been an objection that we didn't observe and correct and adjust.", "start": 416.389, "stop": 421.884, "duration": 5.5}, {"text": "In other words, he's been selling this same type of magazine but there had been objections previously.", "start": 421.884, "stop": 427.008, "duration": 5.12}, {"text": "And finally, since he brought it up, it was brought out in 1960, about three years before this particular sale.", "start": 427.008, "stop": 434.714, "duration": 7.71}, {"text": "The city commissioners of the City of Paducah had come to him and objected to this type of magazine -- that is the classic girlie magazines that he was distributing.", "start": 434.714, "stop": 445.054, "duration": 10.34}, {"text": "And as a result of this complaint at that time, he did was to get all the girlie magazines from a retail store located near a school.", "start": 445.054, "stop": 456.393, "duration": 11.34}, {"text": "This was not yet Read More retail newsstand but another retail store that he was supplying in his capacity as a wholesale news distributor.", "start": 456.393, "stop": 466.278, "duration": 9.89}, {"text": "So, he was asked that question, haven't you been selling that same type of magazine for years?", "start": 466.278, "stop": 472.583, "duration": 6.31}, {"text": "And he said, yes, I've been selling the same thing for years.", "start": 472.583, "stop": 475.524, "duration": 2.94}, {"text": "Then they went ahead with it and I said I'm without objection.", "start": 475.524, "stop": 478.483, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "This was to show that this type of magazine had been generally accepted in the community.", "start": 478.483, "stop": 482.715, "duration": 4.23}, {"text": "Unfortunately, he could not answer that by saying there had never been an objection.", "start": 482.715, "stop": 486.757, "duration": 4.04}, {"text": "As a matter of fact, he had to say that there had been an objection.", "start": 486.757, "stop": 489.653, "duration": 2.9}, {"text": "So this in itself shows that this type of magazine had not been accepted by the community.", "start": 489.653, "stop": 496.166, "duration": 6.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You mean in that community in Paducah around where this drugstore is located.", "start": 496.166, "stop": 503.004, "duration": 6.84}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, in the area in which Mr. Austin did business, you must keep in mind that he was a wholesale news distributor.", "start": 503.004, "stop": 509.463, "duration": 6.46}, {"text": "He had five wholesale outlets.", "start": 509.463, "stop": 511.392, "duration": 1.93}, {"text": "He said in his own testimony that he supplied perhaps 300 different towns.", "start": 511.392, "stop": 516.169, "duration": 4.78}, {"text": "And I think the questions were the sale of this material in the area in which he operated, if I'm not mistaken.", "start": 516.169, "stop": 524.984, "duration": 8.82}, {"text": "I might have to agree with you that perhaps the thrust of this was really in this Paducah area because certainly that's where his Read More newsstand was located.", "start": 524.984, "stop": 534.231, "duration": 9.25}, {"text": "That's where he had his retail store.", "start": 534.231, "stop": 535.665, "duration": 1.43}, {"text": "That's where the citizens came in and bought the magazines.", "start": 535.665, "stop": 539.784, "duration": 4.12}, {"text": "But I think that it was not isolated to Paducah because this gentleman did quite a large business.", "start": 539.784, "stop": 545.34, "duration": 5.56}, {"text": "He supplied 300 towns.", "start": 545.34, "stop": 547.325, "duration": 1.99}, {"text": "He had three wholesale outlets in Tennessee, one in Carbondale, Illinois, and this one in Paducah.", "start": 547.325, "stop": 554.813, "duration": 7.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "What instructions (Inaudible)?", "start": 554.813, "stop": 560.214, "duration": 5.4}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "The instruction given by the trial court to the jury seems to have been on the basis of the country as a whole.", "start": 560.214, "stop": 570.068, "duration": 9.85}, {"text": "This is instruction no. 5 page 110 of your record.", "start": 570.068, "stop": 574.009, "duration": 3.94}, {"text": "The term \"contemporary community standard\" as used in these instructions are not the standard of a particular individual group, of individuals, or locality.", "start": 574.009, "stop": 583.836, "duration": 9.83}, {"text": "But it is the standard of the community, the contemporary society of this country at large or as a whole.", "start": 583.836, "stop": 591.555, "duration": 7.72}, {"text": "So I submit to you that by instruction no. 5 given the jury, the standard used by the trial court was the contemporary society of this country at large or as a whole.", "start": 591.555, "stop": 603.103, "duration": 11.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "If the standard that he gave then is the corporate standard which been a local community standard, the benefit of would be entitled to a new trial, wouldn't he?", "start": 603.103, "stop": 616.713, "duration": 13.61}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "If the proper standard really should be the local standard, I should thank that the defendant would be favored by an instruction such as this.", "start": 616.713, "stop": 626.83, "duration": 10.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why?", "start": 626.83, "stop": 628.581, "duration": 1.75}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because it would permit the defendant to escape the penalty if the jury should surmise that although this material is not accepted by our local people here in Paducah, nevertheless, will have to let him go because it could be accepted in the country as a whole.", "start": 628.581, "stop": 646.15, "duration": 17.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You are saying that the court charged the standard to be control as a national standard that he wouldn't be hurt by having him (Inaudible) even if the standard, correct standard was a local.", "start": 646.15, "stop": 661.197, "duration": 15.05}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think it would benefit the defendant because if the standard --", "start": 661.197, "stop": 664.16, "duration": 2.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "That will be kind of a harmless error?", "start": 664.16, "stop": 667.033, "duration": 2.87}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would, well, I would if it was an error and I don't concede that.", "start": 667.033, "stop": 670.558, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "I think it would be a harmless error because if the standards were confined to the locality, then this jury would say we know what it is in Paducah and we don't like it.", "start": 670.558, "stop": 679.458, "duration": 8.9}, {"text": "But if the standards, if they were told of the standards with the country as a whole, in other words, it's not what you think in Paducah but you have t consider what it is in New York and California, then the jurors might well think well of a law.", "start": 679.458, "stop": 690.062, "duration": 10.6}, {"text": "Although we don't like it here, we'll have to let him go because it's accepted in the country as a whole.", "start": 690.062, "stop": 696.174, "duration": 6.11}, {"text": "In other words, it would create additional doubt in the minds of the jury, which would benefit the defendant, that make it more difficult to convict him.", "start": 696.174, "stop": 704.32, "duration": 8.15}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "That will go the other way?", "start": 704.32, "stop": 707.53, "duration": 3.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 707.53, "stop": 712.786, "duration": 5.26}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "This was my understanding.", "start": 712.786, "stop": 714.645, "duration": 1.86}, {"text": "I thought the ground of certiorari was limited to these particular questions.", "start": 714.645, "stop": 718.679, "duration": 4.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "They didn't make it on the jury?", "start": 718.679, "stop": 721.618, "duration": 2.94}, {"text": "Well, do you think we could --", "start": 721.618, "stop": 722.831, "duration": 1.21}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not trying to raise that actually.", "start": 722.831, "stop": 725.313, "duration": 2.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you think we could decide the case, that we are satisfied that there was a gross flagrant error which defies a man of a fair trial which decided on a limited basis?", "start": 725.313, "stop": 739.176, "duration": 13.86}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "You have already acted.", "start": 739.176, "stop": 741.171, "duration": 2}, {"text": "This Court has -- to limit certiorari.", "start": 741.171, "stop": 743.695, "duration": 2.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "We haven't found any acts on the series of cases here.", "start": 743.695, "stop": 748.203, "duration": 4.51}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I see no gross flagrant error in this case.", "start": 748.203, "stop": 750.08, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I understand that.", "start": 750.08, "stop": 752.096, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "Suppose it was?", "start": 752.096, "stop": 754.359, "duration": 2.26}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think that would be something that the Court would have to resolve for itself.", "start": 754.359, "stop": 757.456, "duration": 3.1}, {"text": "Are you asking me what I would do if I were sitting on a court?", "start": 757.456, "stop": 761.381, "duration": 3.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that might be [Laughter] (Inaudible)?", "start": 761.381, "stop": 785.727, "duration": 24.35}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think that position is well-taken and I was just about to say it myself.", "start": 785.727, "stop": 790.363, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "I didn't expect the argument on two or three points which have been raised here and they were not adequately briefed and perhaps I was not fully prepared.", "start": 790.363, "stop": 799.47, "duration": 9.11}, {"text": "But I think that you are perfectly correct, Mr. Justice Clark that if certiorari is to be extended to all these other matters then we ought to have time to argue it anyway, briefly.", "start": 799.47, "stop": 809.608, "duration": 10.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I was asking you questions so you can argue it now.", "start": 809.608, "stop": 813.94, "duration": 4.33}]}, {"speakerName": "John B. Browning", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would like a little time to prepare a better argument perhaps, Mr. Justice Black and then I'll do my best to answer it.", "start": 813.94, "stop": 820.597, "duration": 6.66}, {"text": "I believe my time is up.", "start": 820.597, "stop": 823.261, "duration": 2.66}, {"text": "Thank you.", "start": 823.261, "stop": 825.911, "duration": 2.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Fleishman.", "start": 825.911, "stop": 829.415, "duration": 3.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, members of the Court.", "start": 829.415, "stop": 832.341, "duration": 2.93}, {"text": "I would like first to address myself to matter raised by Mr. Justice Fortas and that was whether or not the instruction given to the jury that they must find beyond reasonable doubt that the defendant knew the contents and the character of the material was such that the jury knew that they had to find, as the state conceived they had to affirm that he knew the material was in fact obscene.", "start": 832.341, "stop": 862.655, "duration": 30.31}, {"text": "The plain answer is, we respectfully submit that the jury could not have so understood it.", "start": 862.655, "stop": 868.3, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "And I call attention to page 23 of the record and there, the witness was Reverend Simpson.", "start": 868.3, "stop": 879.172, "duration": 10.87}, {"text": "He was asked about two magazines not the two magazines involved in this case but two other girlie magazines that were shown to Mr. Austin at the time of his meeting with the ministerial association.", "start": 879.172, "stop": 895.11, "duration": 15.94}, {"text": "Objection was made to the showing of these other magazines on the ground that they had nothing to do with the case.", "start": 895.11, "stop": 902.081, "duration": 6.97}, {"text": "And the Court, that I will let the jury consider it for the purpose of whether or not he had knowledge of the class or character.", "start": 902.081, "stop": 909.195, "duration": 7.11}, {"text": "It's plain, therefore, that what was meant by \"character\" was, that Mr. Austin knew that he had girlie magazines and only that.", "start": 909.195, "stop": 918.044, "duration": 8.85}, {"text": "Not that he knew the contents of the two specific magazines involved and surely not that he knew that the two specific magazines involved were in fact obscene.", "start": 918.044, "stop": 930.119, "duration": 12.08}, {"text": "Now, in light of the concession by the respondent that the state did have the burden of proving that the defendant knew the material wasn't in fact obscene, in light of the ambiguity of the instruction given where it was never stated to the jury that they had to find that he knew the magazine was obscene, then surely the defendant requested instruction that he should be found not guilty.", "start": 930.119, "stop": 955.362, "duration": 25.24}, {"text": "If the jury found that he in good faith believe that to be not obscene, should have been given.", "start": 955.362, "stop": 962.742, "duration": 7.38}, {"text": "And we submit that such an instruction must be given in the light of the First Amendment in every case because of the very nature of these obscenity proceedings where the jury is really all to, ready to convict, without sufficient evidence as of the case right here.", "start": 962.742, "stop": 982.618, "duration": 19.88}, {"text": "The prosecute -- the respondent says that the defendants, the -- that the, respondent had the burden of proving beyond reasonable doubt that the defendant, the petitioner here knew the contents of the magazine and knew it to be obscene and there is enough evidence in this case, to support either of them and the jury has no hesitance in returning its verdict of guilty.", "start": 982.618, "stop": 1005.672, "duration": 23.05}, {"text": "I believe what the Court pointed out in the case of Unites States against Cloud that there is a great danger in this field because of the strong emotions that aroused in jurors for a jury to convict not on evidence but on prejudice.", "start": 1005.672, "stop": 1021.757, "duration": 16.08}, {"text": "I would like to suggest one word of the presumptions if I may, Mr. --", "start": 1021.757, "stop": 1024.142, "duration": 2.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1024.142, "stop": 1026.084, "duration": 1.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 1026.084, "stop": 1027.861, "duration": 1.78}, {"text": "The respondent has indicated that the presumption that is found in 436 subdivision 4 was not used in this case.", "start": 1027.861, "stop": 1038.233, "duration": 10.37}, {"text": "But that's not so.", "start": 1038.233, "stop": 1040.218, "duration": 1.99}, {"text": "The fact of the matter is, that since there was no evidence that the defendant knew the material was obscene, the only way the case could have been submitted to the jury was to utilize the presumption that a person who sold magazines, found by a jury to be obscene, may meant that the respondent knew in fact that the publications were obscene.", "start": 1040.218, "stop": 1063.561, "duration": 23.34}, {"text": "Moreover, it caused the petitioner to take the stand in order to rebut the presumption.", "start": 1063.561, "stop": 1072.465, "duration": 8.9}, {"text": "The fact that it was meaningful in this case is found on, in the record of page 112 where the attorney for the petitioner, right after the conviction, was complaining.", "start": 1072.465, "stop": 1086.715, "duration": 14.25}, {"text": "In his motion for a dismissal, he points out that that statute under which the defendant was prosecuted is unconstitutional, is violating the Fourteenth Amendment, because it released the Commonwealth of the duty to prove knowledge on the part of the defendant of the fact of the obscenity of the magazines as obscene they were.", "start": 1086.715, "stop": 1105.47, "duration": 18.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why would that make it unconstitutional?", "start": 1105.47, "stop": 1107.849, "duration": 2.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why would that make it unconstitutional?", "start": 1107.849, "stop": 1110.133, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "Because there was unreasonable and arbitrary presumption from the sale of the magazine.", "start": 1110.133, "stop": 1116.487, "duration": 6.35}, {"text": "It was presumed that what the jury found the magazine to be obscene, the presumption was that the man who sold the magazine knew it to be obscene also without any other proof at all.", "start": 1116.487, "stop": 1126.53, "duration": 10.04}, {"text": "And that is totally arbitrary and it's - -", "start": 1126.53, "stop": 1128.26, "duration": 1.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is it your argument that the state could not constitutionally make it a violation to sell obscene magazines even though the owner was unfamiliar with the obscenity?", "start": 1128.26, "stop": 1141.64, "duration": 13.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "In the case Smith against California of this Court held, I believe, that that would be a violation of the First Amendment, to make a bookseller liable merely for selling a book unless you added to it a guilty knowledge which Smith versus California required and we --", "start": 1141.64, "stop": 1157.975, "duration": 16.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "In other words, that it could not be, the state could not constitutionally make procession of that time?", "start": 1157.975, "stop": 1167.164, "duration": 9.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I believe that's true.", "start": 1167.164, "stop": 1167.993, "duration": 0.83}, {"text": "I believe this is what Mr. Justice Stewart said in a concurring opinion of Mapp against Ohio where the Ohio statute was involved and plainly would be a violation of the First Amendment to say to a prison that he could not even possess.", "start": 1167.993, "stop": 1183.869, "duration": 15.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What about making liquor, possession of liquor a violation of the law?", "start": 1183.869, "stop": 1189.103, "duration": 5.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "We had a constitutional amendment that raised some problems there but the difference, of course, between liquor and matter which is within the protection of the First Amendment is a difference of, the greatest important, in which this Court of course has noticed.", "start": 1189.103, "stop": 1204.657, "duration": 15.55}, {"text": "For example, in the Marcus case, it was pointed out, as it was pointed out in Smith, that there are many rules of law that you can have in other areas which simply would not be tolerable in the area where the effect of it is to limit freedom of speech and freedom of press.", "start": 1204.657, "stop": 1220.515, "duration": 15.86}, {"text": "Here, what happens if you do away with the scienter requirement or the mens rea or the two, as we see it, is to make a bookseller a censor.", "start": 1220.515, "stop": 1231.449, "duration": 10.93}, {"text": "Because of his timidity, because of his fear, he simply is not going to circulate the press and all of us will be the losers.", "start": 1231.449, "stop": 1240.513, "duration": 9.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the premise -- but the premise is as I understand it that the obscene literature is not protected by the First Amendment.", "start": 1240.513, "stop": 1251.084, "duration": 10.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is true, Your Honor.", "start": 1251.084, "stop": 1252.1, "duration": 1.02}, {"text": "But in trying to suppress obscene literature, unless the bookseller has some breathing space, he has some security he is not going to circulate constitutionally protected speech either.", "start": 1252.1, "stop": 1262.534, "duration": 10.43}, {"text": "He is not going to circulate material which he believes is not obscene and which in fact is not obscene but because of fear, he simply will stay clear of the whole area whenever a private group comes to a bookseller and says, I don't like it whether that be religious group or any other group.", "start": 1262.534, "stop": 1280.721, "duration": 18.19}, {"text": "Out of fear, he is going to have to withdraw it and there isn't a reason in the world why he shouldn't be under the same precious ultimately for distributing political or religious matter too.", "start": 1280.721, "stop": 1291.081, "duration": 10.36}, {"text": "Today, we are talking about sex speech which is unpopular.", "start": 1291.081, "stop": 1294.877, "duration": 3.8}, {"text": "But the rule of law which says that a bookseller can be made a criminal because he distributes works that somebody doesn't like and that he can be punished upward inevitably has a very high potential for suppressing speech.", "start": 1294.877, "stop": 1310.75, "duration": 15.87}, {"text": "And unless we give the bookseller the kind of protection that has been talked about often in this Court, that a bookseller brought up on a criminal prosecution, is ring the bell with all of these great protections, unless that be given some meaning and effect, we're going to have a (Inaudible) which we haven't seen since Salem because the prosecutors today, under the pressure of private groups, are really running rampant and booksellers today are frightened and something has to be done.", "start": 1310.75, "stop": 1341.493, "duration": 30.74}, {"text": "And pretty soon, to give them the kind of protection so that they will be able to stand up to the pressure, otherwise, as I say, there will be a kind of erosion of the First Amendment that we could not tolerate.", "start": 1341.493, "stop": 1353.979, "duration": 12.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your argument is that the Government must prove, the prosecution must prove a person has sold a magazine, had read it, knew in some way that it was obscene or else he could not be convicted?", "start": 1353.979, "stop": 1370.144, "duration": 16.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's our argument that unless the defend -- a bookseller, who sells a magazine knows it's obscene, he cannot be found guilty.", "start": 1370.144, "stop": 1378.64, "duration": 8.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But suppose he just didn't read it?", "start": 1378.64, "stop": 1380.652, "duration": 2.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "If he didn't read it, then I would say that on the most circumstances, he could not be found guilty.", "start": 1380.652, "stop": 1386.711, "duration": 6.06}, {"text": "I think there might be a situation --", "start": 1386.711, "stop": 1388.734, "duration": 2.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "So you should require the bookseller to read all the literature they have in their bookstore.", "start": 1388.734, "stop": 1394.108, "duration": 5.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, what I --", "start": 1394.108, "stop": 1394.702, "duration": 0.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "He could not be convicted for selling obscene literature.", "start": 1394.702, "stop": 1397.892, "duration": 3.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, what I had in mind, Mr. Justice Black was a situation, for example where there had been a civil proceeding, for example, and which a state have had an adjudication with regard to a book and found that the book is obscene and then, a bookseller is notified of the adjudication.", "start": 1397.892, "stop": 1415.328, "duration": 17.44}, {"text": "If he then sells the book, knowing that there has been an adjudication finding it to be obscene, then he has the requisite guilty knowledge or he might in the Constitution.", "start": 1415.328, "stop": 1424.682, "duration": 9.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you always get to wait until they found out about it.", "start": 1424.682, "stop": 1427.507, "duration": 2.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would say that that --", "start": 1427.507, "stop": 1429.388, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not talking as an advocate of censorship but I'm just asking you the question (Voice Overlap).", "start": 1429.388, "stop": 1435.885, "duration": 6.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand that, Mr. Justice Black.", "start": 1435.885, "stop": 1437.603, "duration": 1.72}, {"text": "Our argument is that, in the ordinary case, there may be unusual ones, but in the ordinary case, unless a bookseller knows it, either by way of some prior adjudication or he may -- there may be admission which he says, \"I read the book and I think that it is obscene.\"", "start": 1437.603, "stop": 1454.68, "duration": 17.08}, {"text": "But in the ordinary case such as the case we have here, what do we have but a man who handles books and magazines?", "start": 1454.68, "stop": 1461.07, "duration": 6.39}, {"text": "The magazines, I respectfully submit, simply as not obscene under decision of this and virtually every appellate court.", "start": 1461.07, "stop": 1470.2, "duration": 9.13}, {"text": "Nevertheless, he is found guilty of it had he read the magazines even he still in my judgment would have to be found by a jury to have known it to be obscene before there could be a proper conviction so that --", "start": 1470.2, "stop": 1485.894, "duration": 15.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "And your argument is that, make it difficult, make it difficult but has censorship?", "start": 1485.894, "stop": 1491.213, "duration": 5.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "My argument Mr. Justice Black is this.", "start": 1491.213, "stop": 1494.413, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "I think my brief has made it plain that there ought not to be --", "start": 1494.413, "stop": 1496.698, "duration": 2.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand it.", "start": 1496.698, "stop": 1497.277, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- censorship.", "start": 1497.277, "stop": 1497.808, "duration": 0.53}, {"text": "But if we're going to have censorship, at least give the bookseller the protection which has been promised to him.", "start": 1497.808, "stop": 1502.232, "duration": 4.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "If we're going to have it, why shouldn't he have it?", "start": 1502.232, "stop": 1504.823, "duration": 2.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "If we're going to have it, we should make it as limited as possible.", "start": 1504.823, "stop": 1507.189, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "I don't subscribe to the notion that an evil, once it's there, we may as well have it in its worse form.", "start": 1507.189, "stop": 1512.947, "duration": 5.76}, {"text": "It's bad enough to have a little evil without having a program going to foot.", "start": 1512.947, "stop": 1519.453, "duration": 6.51}, {"text": "The simple fact of the matter is --", "start": 1519.453, "stop": 1521.231, "duration": 1.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "How is there any stopping shown of just leaving it always to the community standard right if the thing occurred and then let them decide what books they will have, what magazines they'll have, which one is they won't?", "start": 1521.231, "stop": 1534.53, "duration": 13.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, if we got --", "start": 1534.53, "stop": 1535.441, "duration": 0.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is the Court short order that except to say that obscenity is protected by the First Amendment (Voice Overlap)?", "start": 1535.441, "stop": 1543.33, "duration": 7.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well we have two -- we have two problems, Mr. Justice Black.", "start": 1543.33, "stop": 1549.981, "duration": 6.65}, {"text": "The first one is the one you're raising in terms of censorship.", "start": 1549.981, "stop": 1552.366, "duration": 2.38}, {"text": "And if we're going to have that I think you're right that in a long run of expense.", "start": 1552.366, "stop": 1555.502, "duration": 3.14}, {"text": "It's the nature of censorship to just grow and grow and grow.", "start": 1555.502, "stop": 1559.129, "duration": 3.63}, {"text": "On the other hand, we have a problem of due process and an individual, a person who would perform a usual function of society, a bookseller, I'm addressing myself now to the due process argument as apart from the First Amendment argument although it interlocks, that at least if we're going to have book, if we're going to have book censorship don't make criminals out of the booksellers at the same time.", "start": 1559.129, "stop": 1582.841, "duration": 23.71}, {"text": "If we're going to have censorship, maybe what, Your Honor, suggested in the Ginzburg case is to set up a bureau, set up a censor and say this is what we can do and this is what we can't do and let's be open about it that we're engaging in censorship in United States of America today, if that's what we're going to do.", "start": 1582.841, "stop": 1598.934, "duration": 16.09}, {"text": "What I'm arguing for, though, is that the bookseller, the retailer, the wholesaler and the publisher shouldn't be made criminals in the process for doing an act which they couldn't possibly know as a crime at the time they were doing it.", "start": 1598.934, "stop": 1611.755, "duration": 12.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But wouldn't just be of any of the point of voilate, the chance to do it which I didn't read it, I don't know anything about it.", "start": 1611.755, "stop": 1617.294, "duration": 5.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not if you have an in rem proceeding in which there is a censor or adjudication of some kind where the state comes in and says, \"This is what you cannot sell.\"", "start": 1617.294, "stop": 1625.871, "duration": 8.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You're suggesting that there should be some kind of a system whereby no bookseller should be convicted unless the stated book has been adjudicated to be obscene?", "start": 1625.871, "stop": 1635.959, "duration": 10.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm saying that that is a certainly preferable to the procedure we have now.", "start": 1635.959, "stop": 1640.387, "duration": 4.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay (Inaudible).", "start": 1640.387, "stop": 1644.928, "duration": 4.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1644.928, "stop": 1647.711, "duration": 2.78}, {"text": "I want to make it plain that --", "start": 1647.711, "stop": 1650.336, "duration": 2.63}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1650.336, "stop": 1652.802, "duration": 2.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Let me just in passing say that I find that intolerable really but the lesser of two evils, I find the present criminal situation.", "start": 1652.802, "stop": 1662.556, "duration": 9.75}, {"text": "There are two grounds where as the Arkansas type situation is bad on only one ground and a very important one.", "start": 1662.556, "stop": 1668.98, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "It's bad because it brings about censorship and I think censorship is bad.", "start": 1668.98, "stop": 1674.2, "duration": 5.22}, {"text": "These criminal prosecutions are doubly bad.", "start": 1674.2, "stop": 1677.615, "duration": 3.41}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "There were (Inaudible).", "start": 1677.615, "stop": 1694.847, "duration": 17.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "On that premise, I believe that the Arkansas type situation is more tolerable but not good.", "start": 1694.847, "stop": 1701.591, "duration": 6.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Fleishman, can I ask you --", "start": 1701.591, "stop": 1704.439, "duration": 2.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1704.439, "stop": 1704.92, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You are suggesting (Inaudible)", "start": 1704.92, "stop": 1713.779, "duration": 8.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "On the clipping, I'm not positive, it's certainly was done on the orders of the petitioner.", "start": 1713.779, "stop": 1719.182, "duration": 5.4}, {"text": "And, I believe that it was the petitioner who physically took the girlie magazines that were in the Read More Store and placed them in a rack behind the counter after he have had the meeting of the Ministers Association.", "start": 1719.182, "stop": 1734.385, "duration": 15.2}, {"text": "I'd like to make it plain though that in that regard that these were, these are not under the counter.", "start": 1734.385, "stop": 1740.811, "duration": 6.43}, {"text": "Sometimes, it's thought as under the counter.", "start": 1740.811, "stop": 1742.471, "duration": 1.66}, {"text": "They were on rocks, in view but what the effect of this was that a person couldn't go there and thumb through it.", "start": 1742.471, "stop": 1749.857, "duration": 7.39}, {"text": "He had to ask some specific magazine by title.", "start": 1749.857, "stop": 1754.21, "duration": 4.35}, {"text": "As Mrs. Wolfen did, she came and she said, I would like four magazines and she gave the names of the magazines she wanted.", "start": 1754.21, "stop": 1762.057, "duration": 7.85}, {"text": "Two of them were out of stock, two of them she purchased.", "start": 1762.057, "stop": 1765.655, "duration": 3.6}, {"text": "But the answer to your two questions is, certainly the petitioner knew that he had girlie magazines.", "start": 1765.655, "stop": 1770.443, "duration": 4.79}, {"text": "There is no question about that.", "start": 1770.443, "stop": 1771.874, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "How will you put that on the magazine?", "start": 1771.874, "stop": 1774.193, "duration": 2.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I believe there were 30 that were place there subsequent to the meeting he had with the Ministers.", "start": 1774.193, "stop": 1780.615, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "But I'd like to say a word about that, Mr. Justice Black because although we talk about only 25 or only 30 magazines, in the Marcus case where the police were after what they thought was obscene material, there were 280 publications that when the police marched in there, they picked up 280 different titles in Bantam where you had the Road Island Morality Commission, they had a list of 106.", "start": 1780.615, "stop": 1806.094, "duration": 25.48}, {"text": "We are not talking about 25 or 30 magazines.", "start": 1806.094, "stop": 1809.09, "duration": 3}, {"text": "The minute the censor get its foot on the door, it's 2 today and it's 75 tomorrow and it's 300 before the end of the month.", "start": 1809.09, "stop": 1817.573, "duration": 8.48}, {"text": "So that in the end, if the bookseller has to start examining the material that the censor whether he be a private or non-private persons says, watch out, we're talking about examining virtually everything that it's in the bookstore.", "start": 1817.573, "stop": 1831.839, "duration": 14.27}, {"text": "And if I may, Mr. Justice Black, with regard to the number of titles that were in the store, the 11,000 which were allotted to for Kentucky, I think the record says that they were there.", "start": 1831.839, "stop": 1841.537, "duration": 9.7}, {"text": "It wasn't that many sale, 11,000 each month. They have some books that are there for a long period of time --", "start": 1841.537, "stop": 1848.255, "duration": 6.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1848.255, "stop": 1849.19, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1849.19, "stop": 1849.402, "duration": 0.21}, {"text": "And in the very nature of things, the way the industry works, each month the national distributor send them a whole new batch of books and magazines and the old ones go out for which creditors given to the retailers.", "start": 1849.402, "stop": 1860.093, "duration": 10.69}, {"text": "So there is a great deal of movement, back and forth, but there aren't that many sales unfortunately in the --", "start": 1860.093, "stop": 1865.98, "duration": 5.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Fleishman, is it your position that the Government should have neither the state nor the federal government should have any part to restrict what the people publish?", "start": 1865.98, "stop": 1879.586, "duration": 13.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would say that that is the rule that I would favor.", "start": 1879.586, "stop": 1881.997, "duration": 2.41}, {"text": "I recognize, of course, that's not the rule of this Court and I'm accepting as Mr. Justice Harlan properly admonished me to accept the fact that we do have an obscenity law.", "start": 1881.997, "stop": 1892.602, "duration": 10.61}, {"text": "But I do think that the --", "start": 1892.602, "stop": 1893.952, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh!", "start": 1893.952, "stop": 1894.159, "duration": 0.21}, {"text": "I know but you talk always of censorship and I just wonder if you consider any limitation of any kind that government puts on what is published to be censorship.", "start": 1894.159, "stop": 1908.86, "duration": 14.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, that is censorship, surely.", "start": 1908.86, "stop": 1910.291, "duration": 1.43}, {"text": "A criminal conviction such as we had here of the petitioner is censorship and as real they sensed, as if we had the kind of restraint that was true in Kingsley or in the Arkansas court.", "start": 1910.291, "stop": 1921.688, "duration": 11.4}, {"text": "I think that Mr. Justice Frankfurt have pointed out quite correctly in the Kingsley Book case that the terror that a bookseller feels for -- out of fear of a criminal prosecution can work a suppression of material, which is really censorship, more lawful than a prior restraint canon enlarged.", "start": 1921.688, "stop": 1939.708, "duration": 18.02}, {"text": "That's in particularly where the rules are very lax where the standards are of obscenity are unknown and where a defendant, a publisher or a bookseller ends up without any real defense.", "start": 1939.708, "stop": 1951.763, "duration": 12.05}, {"text": "The kind of trial that Mr. Austin had here is no different really from the kind of trial you will have before a Censorship Board.", "start": 1951.763, "stop": 1958.399, "duration": 6.64}, {"text": "What is it?", "start": 1958.399, "stop": 1959.255, "duration": 0.86}, {"text": "You take that magazine, you throw them before people and the prosecutor says, \"You don't like them, do you.", "start": 1959.255, "stop": 1964.347, "duration": 5.09}, {"text": "You don't want these in your home, do you?", "start": 1964.347, "stop": 1966.538, "duration": 2.19}, {"text": "You wouldn't want your children to read it!?", "start": 1966.538, "stop": 1968.8, "duration": 2.26}, {"text": "That's the kind of argument you make to a Censorship Board and it's a censorship in practice and in operation and evidence effect.", "start": 1968.8, "stop": 1974.833, "duration": 6.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "We sometimes get caught on the horns of a dilemma and because that might happen, do you -- is it your position that the state has no right of any kind to protect decency by some limitations on what is published even though it might be vile and (Inaudible) to the extreme hardcore pornography, if you want to use that term, but they must let (Inaudible).", "start": 1974.833, "stop": 2014.121, "duration": 39.29}, {"text": "So anything that they wanted or they want us out to children in the public school or any place else.", "start": 2014.121, "stop": 2021.24, "duration": 7.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, that is not my position --", "start": 2021.24, "stop": 2022.601, "duration": 1.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do you limit it?", "start": 2022.601, "stop": 2023.849, "duration": 1.25}, {"text": "That's what I'd like to get asked.", "start": 2023.849, "stop": 2025.692, "duration": 1.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would like to state this first that if we're talking about adults and the rights of adults to read, either the most obnoxious sexual material or the most obnoxious political material or the most obnoxious religious material, I believe that in a free society that the adult must be permitted to read it.", "start": 2025.692, "stop": 2048.246, "duration": 22.55}, {"text": "And if he's going to be permitted to read it, he must be able to obtain it and that would require the rule, as I would see it that adults should have the permission to read and to purchase material of any kind.", "start": 2048.246, "stop": 2061.514, "duration": 13.27}, {"text": "Now, the suggestion made by Mr. Justice Brennan in Jacobellis is a suggestion which I think makes sense and constitutionally, I believe stands on a much stronger footing.", "start": 2061.514, "stop": 2072.279, "duration": 10.76}, {"text": "And that is, with regard to minors, with regard to persons who are unable to make judgments.", "start": 2072.279, "stop": 2080.274, "duration": 7.99}, {"text": "There is room, I think, for some kind of an accommodation with regard to keeping out of the hands of minors in something like the same passion that liquor or cigarettes are kept from minors.", "start": 2080.274, "stop": 2092.716, "duration": 12.44}, {"text": "But when we're talking about adults, they are said, Mr. Justice Black was correct in terms of how old was the man, the witness for the petitioner who looked at the material and he was saying that it didn't appeal to prurient interest and the like.", "start": 2092.716, "stop": 2108.734, "duration": 16.02}, {"text": "I think that most adults, all adults, if we're talking about the average normal adult is totally able to handle sexual material just as surely as he was able to handle terrible political material.", "start": 2108.734, "stop": 2124.715, "duration": 15.98}, {"text": "It's such an anomaly to say that we can trust adults in all these other areas.", "start": 2124.715, "stop": 2130.216, "duration": 5.5}, {"text": "But somehow, he goes to pieces when he sees something that is very strong.", "start": 2130.216, "stop": 2134.611, "duration": 4.39}, {"text": "However, you want to form it and talk about it in the sexual sense.", "start": 2134.611, "stop": 2137.607, "duration": 3}, {"text": "If we come down to the path that's really just like we get used to, I saw on NBC today on television, morning.", "start": 2137.607, "stop": 2147.698, "duration": 10.09}, {"text": "But if we on a news, much more fright, much more fright than any of the news in these two magazines.", "start": 2147.698, "stop": 2155.697, "duration": 8}, {"text": "They were completely revealed and there wasn't any feeling.", "start": 2155.697, "stop": 2159.724, "duration": 4.03}, {"text": "I mean, we get used to certain things one way or the other.", "start": 2159.724, "stop": 2162.081, "duration": 2.36}, {"text": "Ten years ago, we would have thought that the American people couldn't possibly tolerate it.", "start": 2162.081, "stop": 2167.334, "duration": 5.25}, {"text": "Now, in the morning show on today on NBC in Washington, it's there and I think that we see, for example, that the American people has been able to read Tropic of Cancer, Tropic of Capricorn without the words for it.", "start": 2167.334, "stop": 2182.411, "duration": 15.08}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "What's the name of that program?", "start": 2182.411, "stop": 2183.791, "duration": 1.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was today?", "start": 2183.791, "stop": 2185.575, "duration": 1.78}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "What?", "start": 2185.575, "stop": 2186.107, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's called today it was on -- before I went to put this morning and it was, I think it we would be very interesting to have a rerun of it and compare it.", "start": 2186.107, "stop": 2193.556, "duration": 7.45}, {"text": "Compare it with the pictures here and I can only assure you that the nudes there are far more revealing, far more seductive than any of the pictures in these magazines.", "start": 2193.556, "stop": 2203.818, "duration": 10.26}, {"text": "What are we then talking about in terms of all the need to censor?", "start": 2203.818, "stop": 2208.879, "duration": 5.06}, {"text": "People can read these things and look at it without our society falling of - -", "start": 2208.879, "stop": 2213.32, "duration": 4.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I ask you this?", "start": 2213.32, "stop": 2214.659, "duration": 1.34}, {"text": "What constitutional section do you rely on to separate what can be sold to adults and what can be sold to minors?", "start": 2214.659, "stop": 2227.776, "duration": 13.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I believe the case of Prince against New Hampshire, if my memory serves me.", "start": 2227.776, "stop": 2230.52, "duration": 2.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I beg your pardon.", "start": 2230.52, "stop": 2231.222, "duration": 0.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I believe the case of Prince against New Hampshire, if my memory serves right has drawn a constitutional line between saying that children for example may not be as free to go on the streets and circulate petitions as adults would be.", "start": 2231.222, "stop": 2243.834, "duration": 12.61}, {"text": "That is a limitation upon an adult would have violated the Constitution whereas, constitutionally speaking, we said that it would be proper to have that limitation with regard to youth.", "start": 2243.834, "stop": 2253.964, "duration": 10.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But without in the context of this case, would that be the same principle that's involved here?", "start": 2253.964, "stop": 2260.861, "duration": 6.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, I, that I would be saying so.", "start": 2260.861, "stop": 2262.634, "duration": 1.77}, {"text": "Yes, that we could say that material which an adult has the right to read and therefore our society cannot punish a person for making it available might nevertheless be punishable if it is sold to a child, and particularly if it is sold to a child for the purpose of engaging in some improper conduct.", "start": 2262.634, "stop": 2280.341, "duration": 17.71}, {"text": "But I think that the limitation might be fairly drawn as Mr. Justice Brennan had indicated in Jacobellis with a statute which says, you cannot sell or make available to youth certain types of material which material is otherwise generally available to the adult population.", "start": 2280.341, "stop": 2298.165, "duration": 17.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I don't disagree with that.", "start": 2298.165, "stop": 2299.857, "duration": 1.69}, {"text": "I'm just asking what constitutional -- what section of the Constitution separates one from the other?", "start": 2299.857, "stop": 2308.623, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "Can you give me that without you saying Prince case, does it?", "start": 2308.623, "stop": 2313.938, "duration": 5.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I could not do it anymore fairly than in the Prince case it was the same kind of conduct.", "start": 2313.938, "stop": 2319.907, "duration": 5.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, but what section of the Constitution (Voice overlap).", "start": 2319.907, "stop": 2323.418, "duration": 3.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I can't -- I'm sorry, Mr. Chief Justice, I cannot give you the answer of that.", "start": 2323.418, "stop": 2329.349, "duration": 5.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I, may I put it this way.", "start": 2329.349, "stop": 2331.939, "duration": 2.59}, {"text": "Permit me.", "start": 2331.939, "stop": 2335.008, "duration": 3.07}, {"text": "If the position is of the First Amendment prohibits the sort of restraint with respect to adults, it started with that proposition, how do you reach with both hands seems to be a qualification of it and say that the First Amendment does not prohibit the restraint with respect to children?", "start": 2335.008, "stop": 2365.319, "duration": 30.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that is a portion of the judgment that a, in a free society we make an assumption and that assumption is, that adults for example, can do things that youth cannot it.", "start": 2365.319, "stop": 2377.291, "duration": 11.97}, {"text": "If something like, I would suspect that the notion of voting, you arbitrarily say that at certain age, a person is unable to vote and therefore, he is not entitled to the franchise.", "start": 2377.291, "stop": 2389.455, "duration": 12.16}, {"text": "But I would say that it would be.", "start": 2389.455, "stop": 2392.602, "duration": 3.15}, {"text": "If you take the position that there can be no limitation of any kind, then we would have to say the same is true with regard to children.", "start": 2392.602, "stop": 2403.284, "duration": 10.68}, {"text": "I am taking a position, some play short of that in terms of saying that the limitation has to be as narrow as the requirements that we feel have to be filled are.", "start": 2403.284, "stop": 2414.067, "duration": 10.78}, {"text": "If we say there is a problem and the problem is children, then a statute, in order to be valid ought to be as narrow as the need so that we say, using the principle that when we invade the free speech area, we have to use the narrowest rule that we can use.", "start": 2414.067, "stop": 2432.134, "duration": 18.07}, {"text": "If we take that approach, I would say this is a narrower rule than one would say that adults would have to be have a material beyond their reach also.", "start": 2432.134, "stop": 2441.249, "duration": 9.11}, {"text": "And therefore, it is a narrower rule, it's the narrowest rule that one can draw and therefore it is the one that ought to be accepted.", "start": 2441.249, "stop": 2449.076, "duration": 7.83}, {"text": "If we agree that the problem is youth then that adult at least are able to handle it then we should have a statue which says --", "start": 2449.076, "stop": 2456.523, "duration": 7.45}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2456.523, "stop": 2464.201, "duration": 7.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, there has been some - -", "start": 2464.201, "stop": 2466.339, "duration": 2.14}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2466.339, "stop": 2474.293, "duration": 7.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "There has been, there has been ---", "start": 2474.293, "stop": 2475.66, "duration": 1.37}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right?", "start": 2475.66, "stop": 2476.407, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, it's quite right.", "start": 2476.407, "stop": 2477.534, "duration": 1.13}, {"text": "However, on the same rule I suppose that sometimes after considering the case, this Court has determined that certiorari has been improvidently granted.", "start": 2477.534, "stop": 2485.945, "duration": 8.41}, {"text": "This Court may be of the view that certiorari was improvidently restricted here and perhaps --", "start": 2485.945, "stop": 2491.064, "duration": 5.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the Court has, the Court has done that?", "start": 2491.064, "stop": 2493.758, "duration": 2.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that --", "start": 2493.758, "stop": 2494.162, "duration": 0.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Many of them?", "start": 2494.162, "stop": 2495.036, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that in this case, it was due respect.", "start": 2495.036, "stop": 2498.275, "duration": 3.24}, {"text": "I think that the issues ought to be more fully explored.", "start": 2498.275, "stop": 2502.847, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "The instructions were plainly wrong.", "start": 2502.847, "stop": 2504.804, "duration": 1.96}, {"text": "The determination of obscenity was plainly wrong.", "start": 2504.804, "stop": 2507.763, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "And I think that the discussion we're having here now is perhaps whether or not certiorari on broader terms ought not to be granted with full argument and opportunity to respond into, address himself to the full issues.", "start": 2507.763, "stop": 2521.473, "duration": 13.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Very well.", "start": 2521.473, "stop": 2521.616, "duration": 0.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Stanley Fleishman", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 2521.616, "stop": 2523.31, "duration": 1.69}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - October 11, 1966", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren13/oral_argument_audio/23656", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Number 50, Gent et al., appellants, versus Arkansas.", "start": 0, "stop": 16.428, "duration": 16.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, members of the Court.", "start": 16.428, "stop": 21.101, "duration": 4.67}, {"text": "I represent --", "start": 21.101, "stop": 21.721, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Redfield, you may proceed.", "start": 21.721, "stop": 25.345, "duration": 3.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "I represent seven magazines whose names appear in the title of this action, as well as their publishers.", "start": 25.345, "stop": 37.776, "duration": 12.43}, {"text": "All of these magazines were published outside of the State of Arkansas and all the publishers are non-residence of Arkansas.", "start": 37.776, "stop": 49.444, "duration": 11.67}, {"text": "Six of them are from New York and one is from Connecticut.", "start": 49.444, "stop": 56.748, "duration": 7.3}, {"text": "Yet, they have been subjected to the sovereign power of the State of Arkansas, for that -- for the courts of that state to determine whether or not these publications may be sent through the mails and otherwise across state lines into the State of Arkansas.", "start": 56.748, "stop": 90.823, "duration": 34.07}, {"text": "An action was brought in the county of Jefferson in Arkansas, in a little town with 20,000 population by the name of Pine Bluff.", "start": 90.823, "stop": 108.61, "duration": 17.79}, {"text": "And the court adjudicated these magazines to be obscene although they have national circulation and are accepted as readily as the Playboy Magazine or anything of similar types of magazines in current circulation.", "start": 108.61, "stop": 135.159, "duration": 26.55}, {"text": "I'm not going into the question whether or not these magazines are obscene because of the limited review in this case.", "start": 135.159, "stop": 145.144, "duration": 9.99}, {"text": "I'm addressing myself to the statute and the record was made on the statute alone.", "start": 145.144, "stop": 154.469, "duration": 9.32}, {"text": "The object of the statute as -- has specifically stated among other things, is to catch the nonresident authors and publishers.", "start": 154.469, "stop": 171.722, "duration": 17.25}, {"text": "They state that in Section 2714 if Your Honors are following me.", "start": 171.722, "stop": 177.952, "duration": 6.23}, {"text": "The statute provides that the mere sending of the literature across state lines into Arkansas shall be deemed a submission by the sender to the jurisdiction of Arkansas.", "start": 177.952, "stop": 203.666, "duration": 25.71}, {"text": "And that a statute -- an action may be commenced by the prosecuting attorney of the (Voice Overlap) for adjudication of the obscenity of mailable matter.", "start": 203.666, "stop": 221.04, "duration": 17.37}, {"text": "And I emphasize the obscenity of mailable matter because I think it will be a bothersome phrase because to me it seems contradictory.", "start": 221.04, "stop": 233.553, "duration": 12.51}, {"text": "The statute also provide with service on the nonresident office and publishing by mail.", "start": 233.553, "stop": 242.685, "duration": 9.13}, {"text": "And I should emphasize too that this statute as distinct from the one you had here nine years ago in the Kingsley Books case does not fix a period for trial immediately after joined thereof issue, nor does it fix a period for the determination of the issue as we had continuably books.", "start": 242.685, "stop": 270.452, "duration": 27.77}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the books will be banned in Jefferson County?", "start": 270.452, "stop": 272.85, "duration": 2.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 272.85, "stop": 273.629, "duration": 0.78}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Until adjudication?", "start": 273.629, "stop": 274.536, "duration": 0.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir, it does not.", "start": 274.536, "stop": 276.81, "duration": 2.27}, {"text": "Does not provide for non -- was anything like that determined.", "start": 276.81, "stop": 281.288, "duration": 4.48}, {"text": "And the -- a judgment may be rendered declaring the obscenity of the publication and enjoined any act condemn by the statute and it may direct a respondent to dispose of obscene mailable matter and may direct the sheriff to seize and destroy all such obscene mailable matter in control of the respondents wherever it may be found.", "start": 281.288, "stop": 326.23, "duration": 44.94}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's if the respondent doesn't dispose of it himself?", "start": 326.23, "stop": 329.487, "duration": 3.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 329.487, "stop": 333.144, "duration": 3.66}, {"text": "And contempt proceedings have provided together with the extradition of the publisher in the event should fail to abide by the decree and should he fail to do so, he may be subjected also to a felony prosecution with one year in jail and a $2000 fine.", "start": 333.144, "stop": 367.943, "duration": 34.8}, {"text": "Now, as I said before, none of my clients are residents of Arkansas.", "start": 367.943, "stop": 376.809, "duration": 8.87}, {"text": "In order to show a cause was issued in February of '64, they appeared with an advisory jury trial hand and the jury advised the court that these books were obscene whereupon the court entered a decree declaring their obscenity and enjoin the appellants from sending or causing to be sent into Jefferson County the above magazines.", "start": 376.809, "stop": 411.983, "duration": 35.17}, {"text": "He does not say which issues.", "start": 411.983, "stop": 413.52, "duration": 1.54}, {"text": "He just talks about the above magazines.", "start": 413.52, "stop": 417.135, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "That all said magazines shall be destroyed within ten days by them and the court retained jurisdiction.", "start": 417.135, "stop": 425.8, "duration": 8.67}, {"text": "He determined whether or not subsequent issues of the magazines may be obscene.", "start": 425.8, "stop": 434.664, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "Now, this is not the Kingsley Book case which I argued here nine years ago.", "start": 434.664, "stop": 445.663, "duration": 11}, {"text": "It has certain features that are similar but it does not wind itself at all within the context of the Kingsley opinion.", "start": 445.663, "stop": 462.974, "duration": 17.31}, {"text": "And I should add too as I emphasized before that although this Court recently in the Freeman against Maryland case sort of found favor was the Kingsley statute in a sort of a model.", "start": 462.974, "stop": 483.406, "duration": 20.43}, {"text": "In Kingsley, there was a provision for a trial one day after the issue was joined.", "start": 483.406, "stop": 491.239, "duration": 7.83}, {"text": "And the decision had to be rendered within two days.", "start": 491.239, "stop": 497.662, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "And I suppose that is why the statute appealed to the court in the Freedman case, as we've -- some of the justices.", "start": 497.662, "stop": 507.324, "duration": 9.66}, {"text": "I -- I have not been reconciled to the Kingsley decision as a protection of the right of speech that is guaranteed Fourteenth and First Amendments.", "start": 507.324, "stop": 521.64, "duration": 14.32}, {"text": "But I know from -- I hope I know that I'm not quixotic enough to ask this Court to overrule it in view of what happen in the Freedman case.", "start": 521.64, "stop": 534.901, "duration": 13.26}, {"text": "But, as I cannot help observing that one of the features that you might have heard -- one of the counsel who might have been on my side say -- that he say that this sort of a procedure because it lends a certain amount of security to the bookseller and perhaps it does.", "start": 534.901, "stop": 563.241, "duration": 28.34}, {"text": "I'm pretty sure he's mistaken because I have seen cases, at least one case I've participated in where the -- moving picture censor, order of the State of New York granted a license for the reduction -- for the showing of a motion picture and nevertheless, the police department in the City of New York threaten the exhibitor because he claimed it was obscene although the censorship board held it to be non-obscene.", "start": 563.241, "stop": 599.401, "duration": 36.16}, {"text": "So I'm not sure that there is any security in this form of a statute.", "start": 599.401, "stop": 609.454, "duration": 10.05}, {"text": "But some people as I say are always looking for security, I've even found people who find security in jail and they're willing to go to jail for the sake of the comfort they may find there.", "start": 609.454, "stop": 622.149, "duration": 12.7}, {"text": "But being as it may, there's a great distinction here between Kingsley and the Arkansas statute.", "start": 622.149, "stop": 635.922, "duration": 13.77}, {"text": "In Kingsley, there was no attempt to control the authors and publishers who were non-residence.", "start": 635.922, "stop": 644.496, "duration": 8.57}, {"text": "The statute operated against persons in the State of New York and the books that were found in the State of New York.", "start": 644.496, "stop": 657.852, "duration": 13.36}, {"text": "And here, there is no attempt to conceal the fact that they are trying to reach the out-of-towners.", "start": 657.852, "stop": 667.27, "duration": 9.42}, {"text": "So it makes the publisher and author in New York subject to the terms of this statute.", "start": 667.27, "stop": 674.366, "duration": 7.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Redfield --", "start": 674.366, "stop": 675.29, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 675.29, "stop": 676.494, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "From this entire branch of your argument, that is to say the extra territorial effect on the --", "start": 676.494, "stop": 682.504, "duration": 6.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 682.504, "stop": 683.566, "duration": 1.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- statute and the order.", "start": 683.566, "stop": 685.972, "duration": 2.41}, {"text": "I would be grateful if you would explain that if any effect the general appearance of your clients in the proceedings below may have had --", "start": 685.972, "stop": 700.765, "duration": 14.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think --", "start": 700.765, "stop": 700.986, "duration": 0.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- because I understand that they did enter a general appearance --", "start": 700.986, "stop": 704.19, "duration": 3.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, they've --", "start": 704.19, "stop": 704.418, "duration": 0.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- obviously, there is a question as to the waiver?", "start": 704.418, "stop": 708.58, "duration": 4.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they might have waived it so far as that service has summed it but that doesn't mean that they are waiving the effect and operation of the statute.", "start": 708.58, "stop": 719.769, "duration": 11.19}, {"text": "They still attack the statute, as I am doing here.", "start": 719.769, "stop": 724.153, "duration": 4.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand that but they have taken on the grounds of -- in part on the grounds of extra territorial effect.", "start": 724.153, "stop": 732.431, "duration": 8.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, they --", "start": 732.431, "stop": 732.869, "duration": 0.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, you -- it's your position I take it, I don't remember that it was briefed by you at the -- I thought you did brief it.", "start": 732.869, "stop": 744.686, "duration": 11.82}, {"text": "I think that if -- since your position that the general appearance below, without any reservation or any qualification did not constitute a submission to the jurisdiction of the court for purposes of the application of the statute in the form in which it was applied?", "start": 744.686, "stop": 770.325, "duration": 25.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, its not.", "start": 770.325, "stop": 770.72, "duration": 0.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "That it --", "start": 770.72, "stop": 771.814, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I wouldn't say that one has to do with the other to question one appearing in a court and not forcing another to serve you outside the state or anywhere else but just coming in and still maintaining -- you claim that the statute is unconstitutional because it has this effect upon the out-of-towner.", "start": 771.814, "stop": 798.789, "duration": 26.98}, {"text": "I don't think it -- I don't think the procedure with respect to the service of the summons has anything to do with the operation of this law.", "start": 798.789, "stop": 815.547, "duration": 16.76}, {"text": "If this statute would mean that an author or publisher who conducts himself in New York by standards of New York would become amenable to the laws of every other middle Pine Bluff in the United States of which we have a myriad of them.", "start": 815.547, "stop": 840.794, "duration": 25.25}, {"text": "Now, under the laws of the State of New York, these magazines were perfectly inoffensive.", "start": 840.794, "stop": 849.272, "duration": 8.48}, {"text": "Gent Magazine for example was a magazine involved in a Richmond County case which the court has noted in several opinions.", "start": 849.272, "stop": 860.846, "duration": 11.57}, {"text": "And if Gent case was published and distributed in New York under the New York concepts of what is bad or obscene, it would place a publisher or an author in a -- not only unfair but in -- it would burden them completely if he couldn't send them out across state lines without the fear that he was going to be subjected to every little town that decides for itself, what this -- its standards are.", "start": 860.846, "stop": 906.884, "duration": 46.04}, {"text": "It appeared as a burden on him, of having to engage counsel in every little town that decided to initiate proceedings like this against him.", "start": 906.884, "stop": 920.453, "duration": 13.57}, {"text": "And moreover, he couldn't meet the standards of every little town in advance.", "start": 920.453, "stop": 925.451, "duration": 5}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose the -- I beg your pardon.", "start": 925.451, "stop": 927.283, "duration": 1.83}, {"text": "Supposed a New York publisher sent agents down into Arkansas and those agents open up a newsstand so that this would be the publisher operating directly in Arkansas, selling this.", "start": 927.283, "stop": 945.908, "duration": 18.63}, {"text": "Now you wouldn't have any doubt as to the jurisdiction of the Arkansas legislature in the courts there would you?", "start": 945.908, "stop": 952.056, "duration": 6.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, if he's operating within Arkansas then he -- he's in the same position as any other resident of Arkansas.", "start": 952.056, "stop": 958.792, "duration": 6.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And this -- but the theory of this statute that the jurisdiction of Arkansas attaches here because of -- acts done by the publisher within the State of Arkansas.", "start": 958.792, "stop": 971.878, "duration": 13.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think they are doing that.", "start": 971.878, "stop": 974.96, "duration": 3.08}, {"text": "They make no claim as to because there wasn't -- no such act here.", "start": 974.96, "stop": 980.154, "duration": 5.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, what (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 980.154, "stop": 980.522, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "And nor does the statute make any provision for that.", "start": 980.522, "stop": 983.902, "duration": 3.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there anything that the --", "start": 983.902, "stop": 984.46, "duration": 0.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "If the -- the claim is merely that these publications originated outside of Arkansas, they were being shipped toward Arkansas and they were going to stop them.", "start": 984.46, "stop": 996.88, "duration": 12.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the statute talks in terms of sending across and to be sent or bringing or coursing to be brought into the state --", "start": 996.88, "stop": 1006.266, "duration": 9.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1006.266, "stop": 1007.272, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the allegedly offending material.", "start": 1007.272, "stop": 1011.963, "duration": 4.69}, {"text": "Is there anything in this record that shows the mechanics, what happened here in this case?", "start": 1011.963, "stop": 1018.485, "duration": 6.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, that's what -- there's nothing in the record at all.", "start": 1018.485, "stop": 1022.256, "duration": 3.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "So when the publishers appear, made a general appearance below, did they make this point, reserved a point, offer any evidence on the jurisdictional point?", "start": 1022.256, "stop": 1037.914, "duration": 15.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 1037.914, "stop": 1039.925, "duration": 2.01}, {"text": "There was no -- there's no evidence taken on that.", "start": 1039.925, "stop": 1042.105, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "In other words, there was general submission of the jurisdiction in the court?", "start": 1042.105, "stop": 1047.016, "duration": 4.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "General submission in a sense that they've submitted to the processes of the Court.", "start": 1047.016, "stop": 1051.065, "duration": 4.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And there's not (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1051.065, "stop": 1051.365, "duration": 0.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was to the -- there were no -- submitting to the statute.", "start": 1051.365, "stop": 1054.602, "duration": 3.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And no point was made out of the theory -- no point was made to the effect that these publishers are not found or doing visits in the State of Arkansas?", "start": 1054.602, "stop": 1068.718, "duration": 14.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 1068.718, "stop": 1069.651, "duration": 0.93}, {"text": "There was no such issue at all.", "start": 1069.651, "stop": 1070.418, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you're bringing that -- making that point here for the first time?", "start": 1070.418, "stop": 1075.021, "duration": 4.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it's all part of the same question as to -- I mean, I'm not involving myself with a question that you are raising because I didn't think its part of the case at all.", "start": 1075.021, "stop": 1090.247, "duration": 15.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I'm -- and haply it does bother me, I wish it didn't bother me.", "start": 1090.247, "stop": 1093.937, "duration": 3.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I don't see why it should bother you because it's an entirely different question from what's involved here.", "start": 1093.937, "stop": 1102.791, "duration": 8.85}, {"text": "For example, if in Kingsley Books case, if the local publisher or author was served with summons incorrectly, I don't think that would be an issue as to whether or not the statute is constitutional or not.", "start": 1102.791, "stop": 1121.799, "duration": 19.01}, {"text": "He could still come into court and make a general appearance and attack the statute on the ground that it's a form of a restriction on a speech.", "start": 1121.799, "stop": 1135.85, "duration": 14.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1135.85, "stop": 1138.386, "duration": 2.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Pardon me sir.", "start": 1138.386, "stop": 1139.572, "duration": 1.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "The fact it admit, to quash the process rather than following a general exit?", "start": 1139.572, "stop": 1144.593, "duration": 5.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I don't see why they have to.", "start": 1144.593, "stop": 1146.966, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "They could always --", "start": 1146.966, "stop": 1147.956, "duration": 0.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, they didn't benefit the state.", "start": 1147.956, "stop": 1149.767, "duration": 1.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "They could always -- they could attack the statute even by a general appearance?", "start": 1149.767, "stop": 1157.241, "duration": 7.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, --", "start": 1157.241, "stop": 1158.166, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "We're not --", "start": 1158.166, "stop": 1158.61, "duration": 0.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "I know but (Inaudible) --", "start": 1158.61, "stop": 1159.654, "duration": 1.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "We're not fighting here the method of service on them.", "start": 1159.654, "stop": 1164.541, "duration": 4.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "For awhile you said they didn't make an appearance at all, what could Arkansas do?", "start": 1164.541, "stop": 1169.77, "duration": 5.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Arkansas would probably -- would render a decree by default.", "start": 1169.77, "stop": 1175.108, "duration": 5.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1175.108, "stop": 1176.636, "duration": 1.53}, {"text": "Now they've (Inaudible) take the books in Arkansas?", "start": 1176.636, "stop": 1182.007, "duration": 5.37}, {"text": "The books were in Arkansas?", "start": 1182.007, "stop": 1183.07, "duration": 1.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "They were in Arkansas, yes sir.", "start": 1183.07, "stop": 1185.723, "duration": 2.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "How did they get hold of the books and pick them up a stand or --?", "start": 1185.723, "stop": 1190.32, "duration": 4.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they'd insist in here, they just went after the -- went after them by what they call this in rem proceeding to have it determine whether or not the books were obscene or not.", "start": 1190.32, "stop": 1201.046, "duration": 10.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "But people in Arkansas may be parties of --", "start": 1201.046, "stop": 1203.606, "duration": 2.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Emanuel Redfield", "textObjs": [{"text": "But -- yes, there was a book distributor there, people there.", "start": 1203.606, "stop": 1212.687, "duration": 9.08}, {"text": "Now, in -- we have to bear in mind something that would seem obvious but could stand repetitions that in the Jacobellis case this Court pointed out that we cannot tolerate the situation whether limits of expressions fixed by state lines only.", "start": 1212.687, "stop": 1243.942, "duration": 31.26}, {"text": "And Mr. Justice Harlan, I state of another generation in 1909 in the International Textbook Case, pointed out that even where a correspondent school was required -- a correspondent school of Pennsylvania was required to qualify as a foreign corporation in another state before it could maintain a suit, that Justice Harlan writing for the Court held such a requirement unconstitutional because this was an obstruction to the transmission of intelligence from one state to the other.", "start": 1243.942, "stop": 1295.273, "duration": 51.33}, {"text": "And I suppose those sentiments can be brought up to date by other members of the court.", "start": 1295.273, "stop": 1306.7, "duration": 11.43}, {"text": "And in the case of Licey v. Haden (ph) where one of the states attempted to prevent the sending of liquor across state lines into that state, this Court held that the sending -- even a sending of liquor was forbidden -- I mean, even the obstruction to the importation of liquor within a state would be condemned.", "start": 1306.7, "stop": 1340.587, "duration": 33.89}, {"text": "Yet this Court has held from time -- time and time again that the literature certainly is on a higher level than liquor.", "start": 1340.587, "stop": 1352.289, "duration": 11.7}, {"text": "The burden that was placed on the author and publisher here unjustly to nothing but timidity and terrorize them.", "start": 1352.289, "stop": 1363.145, "duration": 10.86}, {"text": "And the expense in defending everywhere would be just another added burden to his already harassed job of being a publisher.", "start": 1363.145, "stop": 1383.04, "duration": 19.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Jackson.", "start": 1383.04, "stop": 1385.82, "duration": 2.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, members of the Court.", "start": 1385.82, "stop": 1389.242, "duration": 3.42}, {"text": "The Arkansas statute was enacted in 1961, this was four years after Roth and Kingsley's Books.", "start": 1389.242, "stop": 1397.069, "duration": 7.83}, {"text": "The statute was drawn with those two cases in view.", "start": 1397.069, "stop": 1400.697, "duration": 3.63}, {"text": "They took the definition verbatim from Roth.", "start": 1400.697, "stop": 1404.209, "duration": 3.51}, {"text": "The -- Roth allowed the criminal action.", "start": 1404.209, "stop": 1407.192, "duration": 2.98}, {"text": "As to several proceedings, they went from Kingsley's Books and they aid one additional safeguard, there's no injunction pendente lite.", "start": 1407.192, "stop": 1415.951, "duration": 8.76}, {"text": "There is no restraint under the statute until there's been judicial determination of obscenity.", "start": 1415.951, "stop": 1424.686, "duration": 8.73}, {"text": "In Freedman versus Maryland, you all point out that Kingsley could service a month, this is the way the Arkansas statute is setup.", "start": 1424.686, "stop": 1432.705, "duration": 8.02}, {"text": "It's an even -- more safeguards for First Amendment rights than in Kingsley's Books.", "start": 1432.705, "stop": 1441.862, "duration": 9.16}, {"text": "There's about 25 other states which have similar statutes where you get a declaratory judgment as to obscenity and then get an injunction.", "start": 1441.862, "stop": 1452.329, "duration": 10.47}, {"text": "Some of --", "start": 1452.329, "stop": 1453.019, "duration": 0.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1453.019, "stop": 1453.396, "duration": 0.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "25, sir?", "start": 1453.396, "stop": 1454.947, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "45?", "start": 1454.947, "stop": 1455.383, "duration": 0.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Twenty-five.", "start": 1455.383, "stop": 1456.442, "duration": 1.06}, {"text": "Twenty-five if our statute follows they would surely follow because our statute doesn't have any provision for any restraint before termination.", "start": 1456.442, "stop": 1466.419, "duration": 9.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "But are the other statutes all defined obscenity in the same way as the Arkansan statute?", "start": 1466.419, "stop": 1470.936, "duration": 4.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's so and probably they do, most of them, I believe they use blanket word of obscenity, indecency and so forth.", "start": 1470.936, "stop": 1477.392, "duration": 6.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is it then --", "start": 1477.392, "stop": 1477.524, "duration": 0.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "This --", "start": 1477.524, "stop": 1479.106, "duration": 1.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "The definition on top page 21 of the appendix to the accounts briefed leaves out entirely the necessary ingredient of totally lacking in regaining social importance to?", "start": 1479.106, "stop": 1496.106, "duration": 17}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "They could be added in this case.", "start": 1496.106, "stop": 1497.896, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "They could have asked for an instruction to that effect and to add it and they took this.", "start": 1497.896, "stop": 1501.877, "duration": 3.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but the statute --", "start": 1501.877, "stop": 1503.186, "duration": 1.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Statute does --", "start": 1503.186, "stop": 1503.617, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- statutory definition which --", "start": 1503.617, "stop": 1504.766, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Even in --", "start": 1504.766, "stop": 1505.323, "duration": 0.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- they're completely deficient in that essential ingredient, isn't it?", "start": 1505.323, "stop": 1508.774, "duration": 3.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Isn't that element of lack of social value implied in the Roth definition having you all re-approve Roth, the definition in saying that it includes this.", "start": 1508.774, "stop": 1524.411, "duration": 15.64}, {"text": "There was a lack of social --", "start": 1524.411, "stop": 1524.987, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because I wasn't here when Roth was written and I --", "start": 1524.987, "stop": 1528.328, "duration": 3.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, --", "start": 1528.328, "stop": 1528.685, "duration": 0.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I -- and I think -- I'm not sure that I understand all of the opinions of the Court in this area where they have that opinions of the Court but my understanding of one of the opinions in the Massachusetts case last term was that there had to be -- that a -- that in order prosecute or suppress something in the teeth First and Fourteenth Amendments of the United States Constitution.", "start": 1528.685, "stop": 1556.554, "duration": 27.87}, {"text": "That something had to have three conjunctive ingredients, not disjunctive.", "start": 1556.554, "stop": 1562.3, "duration": 5.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1562.3, "stop": 1563.472, "duration": 1.17}, {"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1563.472, "stop": 1564.797, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "One of which was that it be utterly lacking in any redeeming social importance, so that's just not in the statute at all.", "start": 1564.797, "stop": 1571.567, "duration": 6.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 1571.567, "stop": 1571.834, "duration": 0.27}, {"text": "But -- neither is the thing about adding defensiveness.", "start": 1571.834, "stop": 1574.913, "duration": 3.08}, {"text": "But if ever -- every time you add an element by a decision, the legislature would affirm that to add another sentence into this definition.", "start": 1574.913, "stop": 1586.066, "duration": 11.15}, {"text": "The order -- since consistently approved this language here from Roth, even though you do seem to add other elements.", "start": 1586.066, "stop": 1594.438, "duration": 8.37}, {"text": "These other elements will have to come in under instructions as for the jury.", "start": 1594.438, "stop": 1599.741, "duration": 5.3}, {"text": "There's no way you could -- just keep adding sentences to each time the legislature amends.", "start": 1599.741, "stop": 1607.261, "duration": 7.52}, {"text": "Now(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1607.261, "stop": 1607.556, "duration": 0.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "As a matter it points to the other states, it might have been a better word just to use the word (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1607.556, "stop": 1612.266, "duration": 4.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just the word saint.", "start": 1612.266, "stop": 1613.433, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "And then that has a continuing -- it's continually redefined in the decisions of this in other courts.", "start": 1613.433, "stop": 1620.501, "duration": 7.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That would be one way to --", "start": 1620.501, "stop": 1621.655, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that's not what your legislature did?", "start": 1621.655, "stop": 1623.533, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 1623.533, "stop": 1623.9, "duration": 0.37}, {"text": "But I think that what our legislature did was -- is permissible.", "start": 1623.9, "stop": 1627.143, "duration": 3.24}, {"text": "Is to -- definition that you'll continually refer to even though you'll say -- the court says to construe it differently as to include other elements.", "start": 1627.143, "stop": 1636.652, "duration": 9.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's really important, doesn't it?", "start": 1636.652, "stop": 1638.736, "duration": 2.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "What?", "start": 1638.736, "stop": 1639.105, "duration": 0.37}, {"text": "They could -- they construed the word obscene as to in -- as it is here to include the lack of social value and that an offensiveness.", "start": 1639.105, "stop": 1648.962, "duration": 9.86}, {"text": "They could be so instructed to the jury if requested.", "start": 1648.962, "stop": 1653.053, "duration": 4.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Of course, here there was no (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1653.053, "stop": 1653.733, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's not inconsistent --", "start": 1653.733, "stop": 1654.669, "duration": 0.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "There was no jury here, was it?", "start": 1654.669, "stop": 1656.197, "duration": 1.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That it was --", "start": 1656.197, "stop": 1656.282, "duration": 0.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "That it was an advisory jury --", "start": 1656.282, "stop": 1657.611, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just advisory jury, yes sir.", "start": 1657.611, "stop": 1659.69, "duration": 2.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "And how was the advisory jury instructed us to the definition?", "start": 1659.69, "stop": 1662.326, "duration": 2.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1662.326, "stop": 1663.009, "duration": 0.68}, {"text": "Are the court itself, it -- hears it by itself.", "start": 1663.009, "stop": 1665.271, "duration": 2.26}, {"text": "It could be advised as to -- considered the three elements at most coalesce.", "start": 1665.271, "stop": 1670.984, "duration": 5.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well it could if the -- but the statute doesn't require it to.", "start": 1670.984, "stop": 1673.444, "duration": 2.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Doesn't require but they could be added into the --", "start": 1673.444, "stop": 1675.259, "duration": 1.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they did -- did either the jury or the court do so here?", "start": 1675.259, "stop": 1678.109, "duration": 2.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was never asked to do so.", "start": 1678.109, "stop": 1679.444, "duration": 1.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or did they, either one?", "start": 1679.444, "stop": 1682.215, "duration": 2.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 1682.215, "stop": 1682.84, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Were there instructions to this advisory jury?", "start": 1682.84, "stop": 1684.909, "duration": 2.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The instructions given were the definition of obscenity -- the appellants here never asked for any instructions as to include the element of -- having an offensive (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1684.909, "stop": 1692.877, "duration": 7.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Were there instructions to the advisory jury?", "start": 1692.877, "stop": 1694.796, "duration": 1.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1694.796, "stop": 1696.811, "duration": 2.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where are they in the record, do you remember?", "start": 1696.811, "stop": 1698.584, "duration": 1.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "They're not in -- did they -- put you from the front of the record?", "start": 1698.584, "stop": 1706.324, "duration": 7.74}, {"text": "This -- 1909 in the printed record but there is no instruction as to lack of social value.", "start": 1706.324, "stop": 1713.772, "duration": 7.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 1713.772, "stop": 1719.725, "duration": 5.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "What this case -- what came up under the several proceedings of the statutes, we have a twin weapons here.", "start": 1719.725, "stop": 1727.013, "duration": 7.29}, {"text": "We have a civil and criminal proceedings and as to our civil proceedings is from the last two cases today this could solve some of this scienter problems.", "start": 1727.013, "stop": 1737.32, "duration": 10.31}, {"text": "Because here you have to -- in any criminal prosecution, you're going to have to show knowledge of contents under our statute and you're also going to have to show either that 2907 has turn it down or that it has been judicially determined to be obscene in an Arkansas proceeding.", "start": 1737.32, "stop": 1755.445, "duration": 18.13}, {"text": "Plus, they knew it was -- had been so adjudicated.", "start": 1755.445, "stop": 1759.128, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "You've really got some scienter provisions here that are no funds than any other state and protecting First Amendment rights and Fourteenth as -- incorporating the Fourteenth.", "start": 1759.128, "stop": 1771.95, "duration": 12.82}, {"text": "This law was carefully drafted in Roth and Kingsley's Books.", "start": 1771.95, "stop": 1775.467, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "They tried to put as many safeguards as they could to bail it.", "start": 1775.467, "stop": 1782.176, "duration": 6.71}, {"text": "Basic safeguard is the definition on mailable matter and non-mailable matter.", "start": 1782.176, "stop": 1786.841, "duration": 4.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, this is kind of a different scienter or mens rea set up here, first, you have a civil proceeding, that's --", "start": 1786.841, "stop": 1798.204, "duration": 11.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1798.204, "stop": 1798.291, "duration": 0.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- what you have here, isn't it?", "start": 1798.291, "stop": 1799.164, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1799.164, "stop": 1800.407, "duration": 1.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And in that civil proceeding, as I am dispended as applied to these publications which are mailable and non-mailable.", "start": 1800.407, "stop": 1810.57, "duration": 10.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1810.57, "stop": 1812.267, "duration": 1.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "As applied to these publications all that the state had to be -- had to show was that they are both obscene from the Roth test or -- am I right?", "start": 1812.267, "stop": 1827.022, "duration": 14.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, that's right.", "start": 1827.022, "stop": 1827.73, "duration": 0.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And once that was shown, then the judicial determination had been made.", "start": 1827.73, "stop": 1839.477, "duration": 11.75}, {"text": "It doesn't have to -- you don't have to show any intent or any pandering or any knowledge of content or knowledge that the magazines were obscene.", "start": 1839.477, "stop": 1855.849, "duration": 16.37}, {"text": "Isn't that correct counsel?", "start": 1855.849, "stop": 1857.935, "duration": 2.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "You -- the start -- the proceedings, the prosecuting attorney would have to have reasonable cause where the statute reads that respondent had knowledge of the contents.", "start": 1857.935, "stop": 1868.984, "duration": 11.05}, {"text": "That's set out in Section 5 which talks about, you know, bringing the action.", "start": 1868.984, "stop": 1875.928, "duration": 6.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, wait a minute.", "start": 1875.928, "stop": 1876.73, "duration": 0.8}, {"text": "Let's take a look at that.", "start": 1876.73, "stop": 1877.958, "duration": 1.23}, {"text": "Will you give me that exact language?", "start": 1877.958, "stop": 1881.347, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "Only has -- it says that every person whom with knowledge of its current offense --", "start": 1881.347, "stop": 1887.899, "duration": 6.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Come to that is the civil action under Section 5, whatever the prosecuting attorney for any county has reasonable cause to believe that any person with knowledge of his current offense --", "start": 1887.899, "stop": 1896.352, "duration": 8.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where is -- where are you, what page?", "start": 1896.352, "stop": 1898.918, "duration": 2.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It would -- in the appellant's appendix, it would be on page 22.", "start": 1898.918, "stop": 1904.208, "duration": 5.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Before it?", "start": 1904.208, "stop": 1905.587, "duration": 1.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was -- being Section 41-2717 is the first sentence after the title.", "start": 1905.587, "stop": 1915.278, "duration": 9.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well that applies to proceedings after this judicial finding, after the kind of proceeding we have here.", "start": 1915.278, "stop": 1923.998, "duration": 8.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, this is to bring the action, to get the judicial determination.", "start": 1923.998, "stop": 1928.635, "duration": 4.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Alright.", "start": 1928.635, "stop": 1928.743, "duration": 0.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's the commencement of the action.", "start": 1928.743, "stop": 1930.327, "duration": 1.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1930.327, "stop": 1932.183, "duration": 1.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you have knowledge of contents and as far as pandering and so forth, that would probably an element as to -- that could be proved during a civil trial too, as well as in the criminal.", "start": 1932.183, "stop": 1945.632, "duration": 13.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or it could be proven but there's no requirement.", "start": 1945.632, "stop": 1948.189, "duration": 2.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No requirement, no sir.", "start": 1948.189, "stop": 1949.752, "duration": 1.56}, {"text": "You just --", "start": 1949.752, "stop": 1951.172, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "We have to do is (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1951.172, "stop": 1952.029, "duration": 0.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Prove the elements of Roth.", "start": 1952.029, "stop": 1953.126, "duration": 1.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "All you have to do is to show that the publisher for example of Gent or one of these magazines had knowledge of its contents, correct?", "start": 1953.126, "stop": 1963.095, "duration": 9.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It has --", "start": 1963.095, "stop": 1963.744, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I assume that it follows that somebody who publishes a magazine is chargeable with knowledge of its contents, or do you construe the statute as requiring something beyond that?", "start": 1963.744, "stop": 1975.061, "duration": 11.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would assume -- as far as not in the content you wouldn't have any problem as to publisher-distributor.", "start": 1975.061, "stop": 1979.597, "duration": 4.54}, {"text": "The problem there is the --", "start": 1979.597, "stop": 1980.386, "duration": 0.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1980.386, "stop": 1980.72, "duration": 0.33}, {"text": "But we're talking here about publishers.", "start": 1980.72, "stop": 1982.286, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Obviously, yes sir.", "start": 1982.286, "stop": 1983.482, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And so all you have to do is to show that he published some magazine.", "start": 1983.482, "stop": 1987.318, "duration": 3.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "You have to show that he published -- to bring a civil action to get -- to get a declaration, you'd have to have a prosecutor attorney bring the action.", "start": 1987.318, "stop": 1998.32, "duration": 11}, {"text": "You'd have to have a reasonable cause to believe that any person with knowledge of its contents is engaging and bringing in of -- or in this -- or in Arkansas publishing and preparing obscene mailable matter.", "start": 1998.32, "stop": 2010.112, "duration": 11.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, I tell you, you have to show --", "start": 2010.112, "stop": 2011.123, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2011.123, "stop": 2011.388, "duration": 0.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "There was no scienter in there part on the (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2011.388, "stop": 2013.877, "duration": 2.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2013.877, "stop": 2014.177, "duration": 0.3}, {"text": "There's no scienter as far as the -- that was scienter would come in after the determination as far as the knowledge of obscenity of the product itself.", "start": 2014.177, "stop": 2024.995, "duration": 10.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "If it's entirely (Inaudible) --", "start": 2024.995, "stop": 2025.828, "duration": 0.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, wait a minute Mr. Jackson, I'm sorry to take your time but you're going to have to play it easy and help me on this thing.", "start": 2025.828, "stop": 2033.743, "duration": 7.91}, {"text": "The -- this proceeding, that we're concerned here was brought and could be brought under the statute just on the basis of a reasonable belief by the prosecuting attorney.", "start": 2033.743, "stop": 2049.076, "duration": 15.33}, {"text": "That each of these publishers with knowledge of the contents is --", "start": 2049.076, "stop": 2057.447, "duration": 8.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Engaged?", "start": 2057.447, "stop": 2057.761, "duration": 0.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- instrumental in send -- shipping the magazine into the state and that the magazine is obscene, right?", "start": 2057.761, "stop": 2064.645, "duration": 6.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's the way that the action is commenced, I mean --", "start": 2064.645, "stop": 2066.505, "duration": 1.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's the way the action was commenced?", "start": 2066.505, "stop": 2068.414, "duration": 1.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2068.414, "stop": 2068.908, "duration": 0.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And then what results is a judgment as it did in this case requiring that the issues of the magazine be destroyed, impounded, etcetera, right?", "start": 2068.908, "stop": 2082.212, "duration": 13.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The fact of the thing is that -- and first, that -- since you have a judicial declaration that the matter is obscene.", "start": 2082.212, "stop": 2087.411, "duration": 5.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand.", "start": 2087.411, "stop": 2087.806, "duration": 0.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then in addition, you can -- and whereas, it was done here, you can enjoin this Acts (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2087.806, "stop": 2093.536, "duration": 5.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And what was done here was that the magazine -- the issues of the magazine were to be destroyed.", "start": 2093.536, "stop": 2097.977, "duration": 4.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2097.977, "stop": 2098.751, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Alright.", "start": 2098.751, "stop": 2099.97, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "Now that's phase one, that's what we have here and all of the scienter that's involved here is that publishing magazine, therefore he has knowledge of the contents.", "start": 2099.97, "stop": 2110.599, "duration": 10.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2110.599, "stop": 2111.165, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And no requirement of men rea either beyond what we've said.", "start": 2111.165, "stop": 2115.522, "duration": 4.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your mens rea would come after the judicial declaration.", "start": 2115.522, "stop": 2117.741, "duration": 2.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand.", "start": 2117.741, "stop": 2118.555, "duration": 0.81}, {"text": "I'm talking to you if it --", "start": 2118.555, "stop": 2119.919, "duration": 1.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2119.919, "stop": 2119.942, "duration": 0.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- if I may about this phase one which is all we have before us.", "start": 2119.942, "stop": 2123.611, "duration": 3.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2123.611, "stop": 2124.263, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Only have before us is a proceeding and which says, “No requirement of scienter or mens rea.”", "start": 2124.263, "stop": 2130.573, "duration": 6.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Alright.", "start": 2130.573, "stop": 2131.442, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now somebody violates the order or somebody brings in to the state and let's suppose one of these publishers, despite the order that has been entered in the proceeding before it, sends in to the state some copies of the particular issue of the magazine that has been condemned.", "start": 2131.442, "stop": 2154.092, "duration": 22.65}, {"text": "Then he have subject to criminal prosecution, is that right?", "start": 2154.092, "stop": 2160.498, "duration": 6.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2160.498, "stop": 2160.996, "duration": 0.5}, {"text": "Under the criminal provisions, if he had knowledge of the judicial (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2160.996, "stop": 2164.5, "duration": 3.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "But he had knowledge, he was (Voice Overlap) and since he had knowledge and he said, “Nevertheless, the copy of the issue, the magazine into the state.”", "start": 2164.5, "stop": 2174.557, "duration": 10.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir under Section 4 --", "start": 2174.557, "stop": 2175.7, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then the prosecuting attorney presumably would proceed under --", "start": 2175.7, "stop": 2183.718, "duration": 8.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Section 4, the -- under what the others -- if the others, 41 --", "start": 2183.718, "stop": 2188.661, "duration": 4.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "41-2716 --", "start": 2188.661, "stop": 2190.572, "duration": 1.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2190.572, "stop": 2190.85, "duration": 0.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- is the number here.", "start": 2190.85, "stop": 2192.238, "duration": 1.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2192.238, "stop": 2192.923, "duration": 0.68}, {"text": "It can proceed under or proceed -- or attempt proceedings.", "start": 2192.923, "stop": 2195.908, "duration": 2.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 2195.908, "stop": 2196.787, "duration": 0.88}, {"text": "Now, under that provision, is there any requirement of a specific intent scienter, mens rea in the sense that publisher brought it in with the intent of selling, distributing something knowing it to be obscene and with the purpose of capitalizing on its quality as obscene literature, it's a very rough statement of what a -- well, summed up by -- what I sum up by the phrase specific intent.", "start": 2196.787, "stop": 2242.446, "duration": 45.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The --", "start": 2242.446, "stop": 2242.894, "duration": 0.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there any such requirement here?", "start": 2242.894, "stop": 2244.939, "duration": 2.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "As I interpret the first section of that, this -- the two-part reveals what position but the first seems deal in selling or dealing or giving a way of obscene matter, it would be in the business, most of it.", "start": 2244.939, "stop": 2257.417, "duration": 12.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, as a matter of fact, is it correct that under 41-2716, the prosecuting attorney would bring a criminal proceeding against the publisher in the keys that I put to?", "start": 2257.417, "stop": 2274.216, "duration": 16.8}, {"text": "All he would have to show is that the publisher has sent the magazine into the state for the purpose of it's -- the magazines being sold and that the magazine, the issue of the magazine was judicially found to be obscene and he's made his case, isn't that right?", "start": 2274.216, "stop": 2300.607, "duration": 26.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "You got the other element -- you also got the knowledge of can say of the knowledge that it has judicially --", "start": 2300.607, "stop": 2304.948, "duration": 4.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where is that?", "start": 2304.948, "stop": 2306.19, "duration": 1.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- fair to be obscene?", "start": 2306.19, "stop": 2307.523, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 2307.523, "stop": 2308.773, "duration": 1.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "As to knowledge of content, that's in the first sentence of very person who had knowledge of its contents sent or causes to send in to Arkansas --", "start": 2308.773, "stop": 2317.602, "duration": 8.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think we agreed on that but --", "start": 2317.602, "stop": 2319.156, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2319.156, "stop": 2319.398, "duration": 0.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- or do you think that this is any different, knowledge of its contents mean something different in 2716 than it does in 2717?", "start": 2319.398, "stop": 2332.575, "duration": 13.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or you'd definitely had to prove as -- (Inaudible) you have to show knowledge of contents or (Inaudible) to show us that it's just the prosecutor's belief.", "start": 2332.575, "stop": 2341.86, "duration": 9.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well then, let's take that very carefully if you don't mind.", "start": 2341.86, "stop": 2347.142, "duration": 5.28}, {"text": "In 2716, which is this proceeding, the civil proceeding, the prosecuting attorney brings the case on.", "start": 2347.142, "stop": 2355.825, "duration": 8.68}, {"text": "All he has to do is to show it to satisfy the requirement of knowledge of contents is to show that such and such a person or a company published this magazine.", "start": 2355.825, "stop": 2368.632, "duration": 12.81}, {"text": "That satisfies knowledge of contents for purposes of the civil proceeding?", "start": 2368.632, "stop": 2374.076, "duration": 5.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2374.076, "stop": 2374.825, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Alright.", "start": 2374.825, "stop": 2376.032, "duration": 1.21}, {"text": "Now, subsequently, after -- this -- that a civil order has been entered, the prosecuting attorney brings a criminal proceeding, are you telling us and if so, what's the basis of it, that the prosecuting attorney in order to satisfy that same requirement mainly with knowledge of its contents, has to prove something else.", "start": 2376.032, "stop": 2403.523, "duration": 27.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "He has to prove these elements.", "start": 2403.523, "stop": 2405.316, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "One, that the person had knowledge of the contents.", "start": 2405.316, "stop": 2408.482, "duration": 3.17}, {"text": "Two, that they are sending or you know, for sale and so forth into the state this obscene matter.", "start": 2408.482, "stop": 2415.506, "duration": 7.02}, {"text": "He's got to show that it was either -- other than mailable matter or that it was mailable matter known by such person to have been judicially found to be obscene.", "start": 2415.506, "stop": 2423.298, "duration": 7.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Alright.", "start": 2423.298, "stop": 2423.641, "duration": 0.34}, {"text": "What I'm going to ask you --", "start": 2423.641, "stop": 2423.783, "duration": 0.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or it just got --", "start": 2423.783, "stop": 2424.621, "duration": 0.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand all that.", "start": 2424.621, "stop": 2425.869, "duration": 1.25}, {"text": "Here, we have in these cases, we have mailable matter.", "start": 2425.869, "stop": 2429.048, "duration": 3.18}, {"text": "We have a judicial determination in the proceeding before us.", "start": 2429.048, "stop": 2433.87, "duration": 4.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2433.87, "stop": 2434.786, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And therefore, we have knowledge of the judicial determination --", "start": 2434.786, "stop": 2439.073, "duration": 4.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2439.073, "stop": 2439.521, "duration": 0.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- in the case that I have put.", "start": 2439.521, "stop": 2441.809, "duration": 2.29}, {"text": "What I'm asking you is, whether it's your submission to this Court that the prosecution has got to prove anything additionally to show that the defendant in this phase number two proceeding had knowledge of the contents of the magazine.", "start": 2441.809, "stop": 2462.253, "duration": 20.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2462.253, "stop": 2462.584, "duration": 0.33}, {"text": "He'd have to show like a -- an affirmative showing of knowledge of contents.", "start": 2462.584, "stop": 2466.458, "duration": 3.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Of what kind?", "start": 2466.458, "stop": 2467.516, "duration": 1.06}, {"text": "That's what I'm asking.", "start": 2467.516, "stop": 2470.58, "duration": 3.06}, {"text": "Remember, we're talking about the publisher.", "start": 2470.58, "stop": 2472.374, "duration": 1.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The publisher?", "start": 2472.374, "stop": 2473.137, "duration": 0.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2473.137, "stop": 2473.821, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "You'd have to show that he was -- to prove by showing he's supervised the printing or he read it before publication.", "start": 2473.821, "stop": 2482.593, "duration": 8.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that is -- is that the kind of showing -- and that's the kind of --", "start": 2482.593, "stop": 2484.7, "duration": 2.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That would show knowledge of contents, wouldn't it?", "start": 2484.7, "stop": 2487.965, "duration": 3.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "But my point is that neither phase number one nor phase number two, if I correctly understand the statute in your explanation, is there any requirement that the prosecution proves specific intent and the question that we have before us and I think further to the question that we have before us maybe, whether in view of the lack of necessity in the statutory scheme of the showing of specific intent or scienter beyond the point that you have described?", "start": 2487.965, "stop": 2523.952, "duration": 35.99}, {"text": "And either phase one or phase two, whether in view of that fact, phase one, the phase one order, is constitutionally defective.", "start": 2523.952, "stop": 2537.111, "duration": 13.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "You'd still have to prove mens rea in -- even under number one, you'd have to show intent, intent to sell or distribute these obscene matters if you have to show mens rea even under this.", "start": 2537.111, "stop": 2553.11, "duration": 16}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "You and I know that there are lots of kinds of these in qualities in mens rea and scienter --", "start": 2553.11, "stop": 2557.615, "duration": 4.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2557.615, "stop": 2558.725, "duration": 1.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And we're talking about two kinds here.", "start": 2558.725, "stop": 2560.504, "duration": 1.78}, {"text": "I'm talking about what the sort refer to as specific intent and you're referring it to the knowledge of the contents, etcetera.", "start": 2560.504, "stop": 2571.85, "duration": 11.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "My point was sir that this judicial determination will put a publisher or a distributor of a notice that this matter is likely to found of -- that it is obscene in the civil matter and he's likely to be found obscene in a criminal matter.", "start": 2571.85, "stop": 2588.441, "duration": 16.59}, {"text": "In other words, it gives him -- what problem as yesterday in one of those cases was that knowledge of contents and knowledge that the material was obscene.", "start": 2588.441, "stop": 2598.531, "duration": 10.09}, {"text": "And this goes a little bit further than the usual statute.", "start": 2598.531, "stop": 2608.989, "duration": 10.46}, {"text": "Towards the mailable matter and non-mailable matter, the great book of all publications would be a mailable matter.", "start": 2608.989, "stop": 2615.282, "duration": 6.29}, {"text": "That definition of mailable matter, the -- be part it makes it almost completely broad.", "start": 2615.282, "stop": 2620.357, "duration": 5.07}, {"text": "It says any other printed or written matter or material which has not been determined to be non-mailable under the laws of the United States.", "start": 2620.357, "stop": 2628.073, "duration": 7.72}, {"text": "That was the definition of mailable matter, is anything that has been given a second class permit or has never been presented to the post office for determination.", "start": 2628.073, "stop": 2638.068, "duration": 10}, {"text": "That would leave non-mailable matters s to something that has been excluded by the post office.", "start": 2638.068, "stop": 2643.351, "duration": 5.28}, {"text": "And anything that's been excluded by the post office, that would be this -- in effect, same as a judicial determination as far as showing you all later a scienter.", "start": 2643.351, "stop": 2654.546, "duration": 11.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, do we have before us a section of the statute dealing with non-mailable matter?", "start": 2654.546, "stop": 2660.971, "duration": 6.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The definition sir?", "start": 2660.971, "stop": 2662.262, "duration": 1.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I said, do we have that, the court determination?", "start": 2662.262, "stop": 2665.779, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "Aren't all of these magazines mailable matter?", "start": 2665.779, "stop": 2668.272, "duration": 2.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "All of them are mailable matter, yes sir.", "start": 2668.272, "stop": 2670.821, "duration": 2.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because the statute is much -- what shall I say, much more rugged with respect to non-mailable matter --", "start": 2670.821, "stop": 2678.053, "duration": 7.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2678.053, "stop": 2678.287, "duration": 0.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Apparently on the theory that you've just stated, namely that the matter is non-mailable, it does not have the advantage, protection or sanctification of the post office department action and giving it a second -- allowing it the exercise second class privileges.", "start": 2678.287, "stop": 2697.383, "duration": 19.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It allows publishers and distributors to rely on the post office determination as their -- you know basic protection.", "start": 2697.383, "stop": 2704.512, "duration": 7.13}, {"text": "If they have that protection, they're pretty well safe unless it's a borderline case.", "start": 2704.512, "stop": 2712.313, "duration": 7.8}, {"text": "The main thing I wish to stress is -- he raises the prior restraint to him.", "start": 2712.313, "stop": 2718.261, "duration": 5.95}, {"text": "And really, this is not really a prior restraint case.", "start": 2718.261, "stop": 2721.685, "duration": 3.42}, {"text": "There is no restraint before an adversary hearing.", "start": 2721.685, "stop": 2726.042, "duration": 4.36}, {"text": "There's no I -- provision for an injunction pendente lite.", "start": 2726.042, "stop": 2731.28, "duration": 5.24}, {"text": "You can only have -- you can -- the prosecuting attorney can only ask for a power in injunction.", "start": 2731.28, "stop": 2737.566, "duration": 6.29}, {"text": "And a power injunction can only be given after judicial determination.", "start": 2737.566, "stop": 2743.257, "duration": 5.69}, {"text": "We're not really in the -- depends on where a prior restraint is.", "start": 2743.257, "stop": 2749.646, "duration": 6.39}, {"text": "But here, you got a judicial determination before there is any restraint.", "start": 2749.646, "stop": 2753.716, "duration": 4.07}, {"text": "A matter of fact, in the present case, the testimony shows that these magazines were still on the stand after the suit was filed all up to judgment.", "start": 2753.716, "stop": 2761.879, "duration": 8.16}, {"text": "One of the witnesses bought some later editions before the final trial was over.", "start": 2761.879, "stop": 2767.031, "duration": 5.15}, {"text": "These magazines until they were ordered -- ceased were never taken off the stand.", "start": 2767.031, "stop": 2773.77, "duration": 6.74}, {"text": "So, the issues can go on the stand.", "start": 2773.77, "stop": 2776.49, "duration": 2.72}, {"text": "There's really not much restraint here.", "start": 2776.49, "stop": 2779.166, "duration": 2.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "As a practical matter, the criminal provision never come into play in a magazine case or ask you, why can your injunction ever be effective in a magazine case?", "start": 2779.166, "stop": 2796.18, "duration": 17.01}, {"text": "Say you'd proceed against the magazine that comes out every two weeks?", "start": 2796.18, "stop": 2802.931, "duration": 6.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The only way I understood --", "start": 2802.931, "stop": 2803.548, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- twice a month, you can't have a preliminary injunction.", "start": 2803.548, "stop": 2807.01, "duration": 3.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2807.01, "stop": 2807.611, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "You can't be at the magazine until you've had a trial.", "start": 2807.611, "stop": 2810.765, "duration": 3.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2810.765, "stop": 2811.273, "duration": 0.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "So by the time you've had your trial, that issue with the magazine is long since out of date and then it gets new ones on the stand.", "start": 2811.273, "stop": 2820.228, "duration": 8.95}, {"text": "Then you haven't been to ban that magazine on the stand anyway while -- during the trial.", "start": 2820.228, "stop": 2826.837, "duration": 6.61}, {"text": "And so -- and once the newer issue comes out, the old magazine is not going to be sold again anyway so you will never have an opportunity to apply your injunction to the old issue or the criminal provision, isn't that true?", "start": 2826.837, "stop": 2841.384, "duration": 14.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "As far more or less what's happened here?", "start": 2841.384, "stop": 2844.335, "duration": 2.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, what's Arkansas wasting this time for?", "start": 2844.335, "stop": 2848.636, "duration": 4.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Trip to Washington -- it seems to me that the -- to make the statute effective, the only way it can --", "start": 2848.636, "stop": 2855.767, "duration": 7.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "You're really telling me -- what you're saying to the public here is, you go ahead and send later issues in here, we'll have to try those.", "start": 2855.767, "stop": 2863.643, "duration": 7.88}, {"text": "And we can never apply the criminal provisions to you anyway.", "start": 2863.643, "stop": 2868.949, "duration": 5.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's -- in fact, we can't understand why they appealed?", "start": 2868.949, "stop": 2873, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "This is the --", "start": 2873, "stop": 2873.076, "duration": 0.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or why are you wasting (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2873.076, "stop": 2873.568, "duration": 0.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- this is no perfect statute they've ever have.", "start": 2873.568, "stop": 2876.452, "duration": 2.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "It may be but books, it might be different.", "start": 2876.452, "stop": 2878.918, "duration": 2.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The books, it could -- rather different.", "start": 2878.918, "stop": 2880.434, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Would have a -- that has some kind of affirmative (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2880.434, "stop": 2882.322, "duration": 1.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2882.322, "stop": 2883.681, "duration": 1.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well the Court retains jurisdiction under this order to consider subsequent issues in the magazines so that they can go ahead and have what presumably would be a very snappy procedure with respect to subsequent issues, when the prosecuting attorney and -- that same (Inaudible) that they bring to the court.", "start": 2883.681, "stop": 2906.926, "duration": 23.24}, {"text": "One issue -- one of these issues after another and you get an order, isn't that the way it works without the time-consuming process of service and the usual things that (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2906.926, "stop": 2924.267, "duration": 17.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That would be the only thing it would show us.", "start": 2924.267, "stop": 2925.692, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- and then initiation of litigation.", "start": 2925.692, "stop": 2926.892, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2926.892, "stop": 2927.892, "duration": 1}, {"text": "You are short the way it -- the order is finally was short circuit service, the process, that would be the only thing which I can see.", "start": 2927.892, "stop": 2934.541, "duration": 6.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "In the complaint they answered it, I assume.", "start": 2934.541, "stop": 2938.163, "duration": 3.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I assume that you have to go ahead and file a new complaint with new -- attached new exhibits to it to go through the --", "start": 2938.163, "stop": 2944.316, "duration": 6.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "You'd have to do a set of --", "start": 2944.316, "stop": 2945.435, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- somewhat the same processes.", "start": 2945.435, "stop": 2947.326, "duration": 1.89}, {"text": "You'd have to have another hearing.", "start": 2947.326, "stop": 2949.141, "duration": 1.82}, {"text": "It says here --", "start": 2949.141, "stop": 2949.875, "duration": 0.73}, {"text": "I don't know, where it says, “If they are found obscene, you'd have to have another full scale hearing.", "start": 2949.875, "stop": 2953.39, "duration": 3.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And in effect, what's happening here is that the court refrains jurisdiction and persona -- and these defendants render in the days so far as appears here, so long as they have magazines appearing on the stands in Arkansas (Inaudible).", "start": 2953.39, "stop": 2973.305, "duration": 19.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2973.305, "stop": 2975.185, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you don't mind, I'd like to ask you one question.", "start": 2975.185, "stop": 2977.628, "duration": 2.44}, {"text": "I'm concerned here, the -- by this point, if I correctly understand it.", "start": 2977.628, "stop": 2984.905, "duration": 7.28}, {"text": "The standard applied, the community standard applied was set at the time -- the law of Arkansas?", "start": 2984.905, "stop": 2989.873, "duration": 4.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2989.873, "stop": 2991.086, "duration": 1.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "The order, as entered prohibit it, I think the sale of these magazines anywhere in the state, in other words, the standard applied was Pine Bluff, the order operates statewide, am I wrong with that there?", "start": 2991.086, "stop": 3010.336, "duration": 19.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The order just applies to say (Inaudible) from bringing into Jefferson County for sale or distribution in Jefferson County in order to -- you know, destroy said magazines which --", "start": 3010.336, "stop": 3021.586, "duration": 11.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "The order applies only to --", "start": 3021.586, "stop": 3022.921, "duration": 1.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Only to Jefferson County.", "start": 3022.921, "stop": 3023.939, "duration": 1.02}, {"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3023.939, "stop": 3026.754, "duration": 2.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "And this is in -- in one specific issue of the magazine?", "start": 3026.754, "stop": 3029.577, "duration": 2.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3029.577, "stop": 3029.837, "duration": 0.26}, {"text": "It's one specific issue.", "start": 3029.837, "stop": 3032.503, "duration": 2.67}, {"text": "It names in the decree and in the complaint and everything.", "start": 3032.503, "stop": 3034.868, "duration": 2.36}, {"text": "It names a specific issues of the magazines that are -- you're quite correct that -- this is about as good a statute is to protect First Amendment rights that you can have.", "start": 3034.868, "stop": 3051.627, "duration": 16.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "It doesn't keep the -- doesn't keep the publishers under a continual restraint and doesn't it subject their future conduct to sanctions for violation of this injunction through other issues.", "start": 3051.627, "stop": 3069.626, "duration": 18}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I wouldn't apply to other issues, it would just be the specific issues that have been determined obscene of --", "start": 3069.626, "stop": 3074.645, "duration": 5.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, let me read this, this paragraph to you, from the decree.", "start": 3074.645, "stop": 3080.882, "duration": 6.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3080.882, "stop": 3081.503, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Court finds that seven magazines are obscene and it specifically retains jurisdiction to determine whether any future issues are obscene and whether or not they come within the terms of this order.", "start": 3081.503, "stop": 3098.071, "duration": 16.57}, {"text": "That defendants are hereby notified that any future distribution of obscene publications as set out, can found out to be obscene will also be restrained and enjoined and magazines will be removed.", "start": 3098.071, "stop": 3114.72, "duration": 16.65}, {"text": "Isn't that -- doesn't that keep them under a constant injunction?", "start": 3114.72, "stop": 3119.457, "duration": 4.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 3119.457, "stop": 3120.797, "duration": 1.34}, {"text": "All they say is, it says, found above.", "start": 3120.797, "stop": 3129.86, "duration": 9.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "And they --", "start": 3129.86, "stop": 3130, "duration": 0.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Look at (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 3130, "stop": 3130.797, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "They specifically retains jurisdiction to determine whether any future issues are obscene and whether or not they come within the terms of this order?", "start": 3130.797, "stop": 3142.163, "duration": 11.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think it clarifies matters over in this order itself.", "start": 3142.163, "stop": 3144.891, "duration": 2.73}, {"text": "That was just in the findings of -- in the last paragraph in its order sir.", "start": 3144.891, "stop": 3151.837, "duration": 6.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "And then the Supreme Court of Arkansas, assume the decree but at this point you have to agree within --", "start": 3151.837, "stop": 3158.021, "duration": 6.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3158.021, "stop": 3158.43, "duration": 0.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- with Arkansas?", "start": 3158.43, "stop": 3159.484, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3159.484, "stop": 3159.846, "duration": 0.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "And assume, the (Inaudible) of Arkansas through that -- did the court -- but the court just defined just to keep the issues amends and enjoined upon showing that these magazines are obscene, isn't it?", "start": 3159.846, "stop": 3172.511, "duration": 12.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that doesn't mean that a new --", "start": 3172.511, "stop": 3173.309, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "If this --", "start": 3173.309, "stop": 3174.315, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- a new law suit?", "start": 3174.315, "stop": 3176.14, "duration": 1.82}, {"text": "Or is that mean -- is that mean as this is here, the court retains jurisdiction?", "start": 3176.14, "stop": 3184.399, "duration": 8.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Would you look the last paragraph sir, in the --", "start": 3184.399, "stop": 3186.607, "duration": 2.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where?", "start": 3186.607, "stop": 3187.127, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "In the decree.", "start": 3187.127, "stop": 3188.698, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3188.698, "stop": 3189.162, "duration": 0.46}, {"text": "But which page, you say?", "start": 3189.162, "stop": 3192.49, "duration": 3.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Would be on --", "start": 3192.49, "stop": 3193.356, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "29 in the record?", "start": 3193.356, "stop": 3194.385, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It'd be on page 30 of the record.", "start": 3194.385, "stop": 3195.965, "duration": 1.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Page 30.", "start": 3195.965, "stop": 3199.002, "duration": 3.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is further considered, ordered and decreed defendants are hereby notified that any future distribution or sale of above magazines which are of like obscene character comparable to the above issues of said magazine will be enjoined and here's an important language above showing that said magazines are obscene that which will have to have a new trial.", "start": 3199.002, "stop": 3221.001, "duration": 22}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is further no -- considered, ordered and decreed that the defendants are hereby notified that any future distribution or sale of the above magazines which are of like obscene character comparable to the above issues of said magazine will be enjoined upon a showing that said magazines are obscene and the court retains jurisdiction of this cause of action that carry out the terms and conditions of this order and to make such orders as may be necessary concerning the sale of the following described magazines in the future.", "start": 3221.001, "stop": 3260.011, "duration": 39.01}, {"text": "And then it goes on, Gents, Swank, Modern and so forth and not to any specific issues, but to the sale of the magazines.", "start": 3260.011, "stop": 3270.728, "duration": 10.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "As to the feature, all it did was retain jurisdiction for a later determination as to the obscenity of any future issues.", "start": 3270.728, "stop": 3278.169, "duration": 7.44}, {"text": "All in effect it does is -- it would short circuit as to service of process.", "start": 3278.169, "stop": 3283.09, "duration": 4.92}, {"text": "It doesn't really matter -- anything, just retain the jurisdiction because the prosecuting attorney will have to go through the same steps again and prove the obscenity of future issues.", "start": 3283.09, "stop": 3291.67, "duration": 8.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You mean, he'll have to start a new action?", "start": 3291.67, "stop": 3294.839, "duration": 3.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "He'd have to start a new action (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 3294.839, "stop": 3297.893, "duration": 3.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- or on a peremptory hearing, could they determine that he was in violation of this decree?", "start": 3297.893, "stop": 3302.772, "duration": 4.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 3302.772, "stop": 3303.886, "duration": 1.11}, {"text": "They would -- as to future issues and future -- I'd say that March or April issue that comes out next month, he would have to prove obscenity again.", "start": 3303.886, "stop": 3314.66, "duration": 10.77}, {"text": "That if have to another full adversary hearing before they could be of --", "start": 3314.66, "stop": 3317.928, "duration": 3.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You mean another action?", "start": 3317.928, "stop": 3320.257, "duration": 2.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3320.257, "stop": 3321.16, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, and --", "start": 3321.16, "stop": 3321.309, "duration": 0.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "As far as the Supreme Court of Arkansas is construed this is --", "start": 3321.309, "stop": 3323.021, "duration": 1.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then what does -- they mean by saying that it retains jurisdiction to determine that act -- that fact?", "start": 3323.021, "stop": 3328.33, "duration": 5.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, by retaining jurisdiction, he would keep them in court.", "start": 3328.33, "stop": 3333.618, "duration": 5.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "You don't mean another action, you mean another hearing --", "start": 3333.618, "stop": 3335.832, "duration": 2.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Another hearing, yes sir, another hearing.", "start": 3335.832, "stop": 3337.304, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Abe Fortas", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the same action.", "start": 3337.304, "stop": 3338.512, "duration": 1.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I mean another -- yes, sir.", "start": 3338.512, "stop": 3339.255, "duration": 0.74}, {"text": "My mistake --", "start": 3339.255, "stop": 3340.828, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But they are -- under an injunction, continuing injunction, not to publish any more magazines of this character.", "start": 3340.828, "stop": 3351.364, "duration": 10.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 3351.364, "stop": 3352.774, "duration": 1.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just this what?", "start": 3352.774, "stop": 3353.635, "duration": 0.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just this one issue.", "start": 3353.635, "stop": 3355.536, "duration": 1.9}, {"text": "Just the issues that are named in there is the only ones they were really enjoined from (Inaudible).", "start": 3355.536, "stop": 3360.313, "duration": 4.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, some are or rather I don't get that from this language, is this further considered, ordered and decreed that the defendants are hereby notified that any future distribution or sale of the above magazines, and that doesn't mean the specific ones there -- they are which they -- you're talking about which are of like obscene character comparable to the above issues of said magazine will be enjoined upon a showing of that -- if the magazines are obscene.", "start": 3360.313, "stop": 3392.928, "duration": 32.61}, {"text": "Now does that simply mean that if they dared to publish any magazine of like character, that they can be summoned in the court on an order to show cause under this injunction and have those burned in the same way?", "start": 3392.928, "stop": 3411.12, "duration": 18.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 3411.12, "stop": 3411.378, "duration": 0.26}, {"text": "I don't think so.", "start": 3411.378, "stop": 3412.616, "duration": 1.24}, {"text": "I think, you'll have to have a complete new hearing.", "start": 3412.616, "stop": 3417.408, "duration": 4.79}, {"text": "Would you turn to page 18 of my brief sir and --", "start": 3417.408, "stop": 3419.997, "duration": 2.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "What page?", "start": 3419.997, "stop": 3420.614, "duration": 0.62}, {"text": "What?", "start": 3420.614, "stop": 3421.143, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Page 18 of the -- brief of appellee --", "start": 3421.143, "stop": 3423.033, "duration": 1.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "18, yes.", "start": 3423.033, "stop": 3425.362, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "Well, I took a little of your time, you take three or four minutes more to finish your argument.", "start": 3425.362, "stop": 3434.056, "duration": 8.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would like to --", "start": 3434.056, "stop": 3437.486, "duration": 3.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Don't -- about my questions anymore, you go finish up your argument.", "start": 3437.486, "stop": 3441.537, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "You may have three or four minutes to do it.", "start": 3441.537, "stop": 3443.822, "duration": 2.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand.", "start": 3443.822, "stop": 3444.228, "duration": 0.41}, {"text": "So that by saying as to the -- you're question sir, there, the -- in the middle of page 18 is an excerpt from the Arkansas Supreme Court hearing which shows the fact of what this decree is.", "start": 3444.228, "stop": 3457.517, "duration": 13.29}, {"text": "They construed this Chancellor's Decree in it's -- it says, the -- it doesn't really mean anything, just retaining of jurisdiction unless it would mean the -- as to service of process and having them subject to the jurisdiction that would mean only --", "start": 3457.517, "stop": 3474.797, "duration": 17.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, didn't the Supreme Court of Arkansas -- I concede did not apply to futuristic --", "start": 3474.797, "stop": 3478.223, "duration": 3.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3478.223, "stop": 3478.816, "duration": 0.59}, {"text": "They specifically said -- that they said that it would violate -- I think the court in Near versus Minnesota said it would violate the -- this --", "start": 3478.816, "stop": 3486.734, "duration": 7.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3486.734, "stop": 3487.453, "duration": 0.72}, {"text": "The court said that the decree here has advised (Inaudible) magazines are not so but it does not enjoin --", "start": 3487.453, "stop": 3495.011, "duration": 7.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Future issue, yes sir.", "start": 3495.011, "stop": 3496.679, "duration": 1.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- future issues.", "start": 3496.679, "stop": 3496.875, "duration": 0.2}, {"text": "Or to the timemean the court held a hearing that has to be held before any order of (Inaudible).", "start": 3496.875, "stop": 3500.44, "duration": 3.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Fletcher Jackson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3500.44, "stop": 3502.079, "duration": 1.64}, {"text": "That's why they construed the Chancellor's Decree.", "start": 3502.079, "stop": 3506.559, "duration": 4.48}, {"text": "They knew they couldn't enjoin future issues.", "start": 3506.559, "stop": 3510.272, "duration": 3.71}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Warren Court", "arguedOn": "Oct  10 - 11, 1966", "petitioner": "Redrup", "respondent": "New York", "docket": "3", "citation": "386 US 767 (1967)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/386/767", "lowerCourt": "State appellate court", "grantedOn": "", "decidedOn": "May 8, 1967", "wikiData": {"title": "Redrup v. New York", "Litigants": "Redrup v. New York", "ArgueDateA": "October 10", "ArgueDateB": "11", "ArgueYear": "1966", "DecideDate": "May 8", "DecideYear": "1967", "FullName": "Robert Redrup, Petitioners v. State of New York; William L. Austin, Petitioner v. State of Kentucky; [[Gent (magazine)|Gent]], et al., Appellants v. State of Arkansas", "USVol": "386", "USPage": "767", "ParallelCitations": "87 S. Ct. 1414; 18 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 515; 1967 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 1571", "Prior": "", "Subsequent": "", "Holding": "Written materials that were not sold to minors, or foisted on unwilling audiences were constitutionally protected.", "SCOTUS": "1965-1967", "PerCuriam": "Yes", "JoinMajority": "", "Concurrence": "", "JoinConcurrence": "", "Concurrence2": "", "JoinConcurrence2": "", "Concurrence/Dissent": "", "JoinConcurrence/Dissent": "", "Dissent": "Harlan", "JoinDissent": "Clark", "Dissent2": "", "JoinDissent2": "", "LawsApplied": ""}}